00/wsj_0044:While giving the Comprehensive Test of Basic Skills to ninth graders at Greenville High School last March 16, she spotted a student looking at crib sheets. 
00/wsj_0044:She had seen cheating before, but these notes were uncanny. "A stockbroker is an example of a profession in trade and finance. . . . At the end of World War II, Germany surrendered before Japan. . . . The Senate-House conference committee is used when a bill is passed by the House and Senate in different forms." 
00/wsj_0044:Virtually word for word, the notes matched questions and answers on the social-studies section of the test the student was taking.
00/wsj_0044:In fact, the student had the answers to almost all of the 40 questions in that section.
00/wsj_0044:The teacher in question was Nancy Yeargin -- considered by many students and parents to be one of the best at the school.
00/wsj_0044:Her story is partly one of personal downfall.
00/wsj_0044:In her wake she left the bitterness and anger of a principal who was her friend and now calls her a betrayer; of colleagues who say she brought them shame; of students and parents who defended her and insist she was treated harshly; and of school-district officials stunned that despite the bald-faced nature of her actions, she became something of a local martyr. 
00/wsj_0044:Mrs. Yeargin's case also casts some light on the dark side of school reform, where pressures on teachers are growing and where high-stakes testing has enhanced the temptation to cheat.
00/wsj_0044:The 1987 statute Mrs. Yeargin violated was designed to enforce provisions of South Carolina's school-improvement laws.
00/wsj_0044:"There is incredible pressure on school systems and teachers to raise test scores," says Walt Haney, an education professor and testing specialist at Boston College. "So efforts to beat the tests are also on the rise." And most disturbing, it is educators, not students, who are blamed for much of the wrongdoing. 
00/wsj_0044:Evidence of widespread cheating has surfaced in several states in the last year or so.
00/wsj_0044:After numerous occurrences of questionable teacher help to students, Texas is revising its security practices. 
00/wsj_0044:And sales of test-coaching booklets for classroom instruction are booming.
