01/wsj_0100:Mr. Hahn, the 62-year-old chairman and chief executive officer of Georgia-Pacific Corp. is leading the forest-product concern's unsolicited $3.19 billion bid for Great Northern Nekoosa Corp. Nekoosa has given the offer a public cold shoulder, a reaction Mr. Hahn hasn't faced in his 18 earlier acquisitions, all of which were negotiated behind the scenes. 
01/wsj_0100:So far, Mr. Hahn is trying to entice Nekoosa into negotiating a friendly surrender while talking tough. "We are prepared to pursue aggressively completion of this transaction," he says. 
01/wsj_0100:But a takeover battle opens up the possibility of a bidding war, with all that implies.
01/wsj_0100:If a competitor enters the game, for example, Mr. Hahn could face the dilemma of paying a premium for Nekoosa or seeing the company fall into the arms of a rival. 
01/wsj_0100:Given that choice, associates of Mr. Hahn and industry observers say the former university president -- who has developed a reputation for not overpaying for anything -- would fold. 
01/wsj_0100:Says long-time associate Jerry Griffin, vice president, corporate development, at WTD Industries Inc.: "He isn't of the old school of winning at any cost." 
01/wsj_0100:The decision to make the bid for Nekoosa, for example, was made only after all six members of Georgia-Pacific's management committee signed onto the deal -- even though Mr. Hahn knew he wanted to go after the company early on, says Mr. Correll.
01/wsj_0100:Associates say Mr. Hahn picked up that careful approach to management as president of Virginia Polytechnic Institute.
01/wsj_0100:Assuming that post at the age of 35, he managed by consensus, as is the rule in universities, says Warren H. Strother, a university official who is researching a book on Mr. Hahn.
01/wsj_0100:In 1975, Mr. Pamplin enticed Mr. Hahn into joining the company as executive vice president in charge of chemicals; the move befuddled many in Georgia-Pacific who didn't believe a university administrator could make the transition to the corporate world. 
01/wsj_0100:The son of a physicist, Mr. Hahn skipped first grade because his reading ability was so far above his classmates.
01/wsj_0100:Moving rapidly through school, he graduated Phi Beta Kappa from the University of Kentucky at age 18, after spending only 2 1/2 years in college.
01/wsj_0100:He earned his doctorate in nuclear physics from the Massachusetts Institute of Technology. 
01/wsj_0100:Mr. Hahn also has engineered a surprising turnaround of Georgia-Pacific.
01/wsj_0100:At the same time, he began building up the pulp and paper segment of the company while refocusing building products on home repair and remodeling, rather than materials for new-home construction.
01/wsj_0100:Mr. Hahn attributes the gains to the philosophy of concentrating on what a company knows best. 
01/wsj_0100:"The record of companies that have diversified isn't all that impressive," he says. 
01/wsj_0100:It would be a good match, Mr. Hahn and many analysts say, of two healthy companies with high-quality assets and strong cash flows.
01/wsj_0100:The resulting company would be the largest forest-products concern in the world with combined sales of more than $13 billion. 
