01/wsj_0108:You now may drop by the Voice of America offices in Washington and read the text of what the Voice is broadcasting to those 130 million people around the world who tune in to it each week.
01/wsj_0108:You can do all this even if you're not a reporter or a researcher or a scholar or a member of Congress. 
01/wsj_0108:And my newspaper can print the text of those broadcasts. 
01/wsj_0108:Until the other day, you as an ordinary citizen of this democracy had no right to see what your government was telling your cousins around the world.
01/wsj_0108:Government press releases, speeches, briefings, tours of military facilities, publications are all propaganda of sorts.
01/wsj_0108:Propaganda is just information to support a viewpoint, and the beauty of a democracy is that it enables you to hear or read every viewpoint and then make up your own mind on an issue. 
01/wsj_0108:The restrictions on viewing and dissemination of Voice material were especially absurd: An agency in the information business was not being allowed to inform. 
01/wsj_0108:Assuming it wasn't one of those columns that you clipped and put on the refrigerator door, I'll review the facts. 
01/wsj_0108:The Voice of America is a government agency that broadcasts news and views -- some might say propaganda -- in 43 languages to 130 million listeners around the world.
01/wsj_0108:But a 1948 law barred the "dissemination" of that material in the U.S.
01/wsj_0108:The law let scholars, reporters and researchers read texts of VOA material, only at VOA headquarters in Washington, but it barred them from copying texts.
01/wsj_0108:And, of course, there's that word "dissemination." 
01/wsj_0108:That sounded a lot like censorship, so after years of letters and conversations that went nowhere, I sued. 
01/wsj_0108:A couple of weeks ago, I lost the case in federal district court in Des Moines.
01/wsj_0108:But I -- I like to think of it in terms of we, all of us -- won the point. 
01/wsj_0108:-- The USIA said that, on reflection, of course I could print anything I could get my hands on.
01/wsj_0108:The word dissemination, it decided, referred only to itself. "The USIA officially and publicly declared the absolute right of everyone except the USIA to disseminate agency program materials in the United States," my lawyer, the scholarly Mark McCormick of Des Moines, said in a memo pointing out the facts and trying to make me feel good after the press reported that I had lost.
01/wsj_0108:-- The USIA said that, on reflection, anyone could view the VOA materials, not just the reporters, scholars, researchers and congressmen who are mentioned in the statute. "The USIA publicly and officially stated in the litigation that all persons are allowed access to the materials, notwithstanding the statutory designations, because the USIA has determined that it will not check the credentials of any person appearing and requesting to see the materials," Mr. McCormick noted. 
01/wsj_0108:-- And the USIA said that all of us could take extensive notes. "The agency publicly and officially declared in the lawsuit that persons who examine the materials may make notes and, while the agency position is that persons may not take verbatim notes, no one will check to determine what notes a person has taken," Mr. McCormick reported. 
01/wsj_0108:But the court disagreed. "The First Amendment proscribes the government from passing laws abridging the right to free speech," Judge Donald O'Brien ruled. "The First Amendment does not prescribe a duty upon the government to assure easy access to information for members of the press." 
01/wsj_0108:So now the situation is this: You have a right to read Voice of America scripts if you don't mind traveling to Washington every week or so and visiting the Voice office during business hours.
01/wsj_0108:But neither of us can copy the material on a Xerox machine or have it sent to us. 
01/wsj_0108:Section 501 of the United States Information and Educational Exchange Act of 1948 says Voice material shall be available to certain of us (but now, thanks to the USIA's new position, all of us) "for examination only." If those words weren't there, the nice people at the Voice would be able to send you the information or, at the very least, let you photocopy it. 
01/wsj_0108:"You have . . . raised important questions which ought to be answered: What does USIA say about America abroad; how do we say it; and how can American taxpayers get the answers to these questions?" a man wrote me a couple of years ago.
01/wsj_0108:At the time, he was director of the 
01/wsj_0108:Mr. Gartner is editor and co-owner of the Daily Tribune in Ames, Iowa, and president of NBC News in New York. 
01/wsj_0109:R. Gordon McGovern was forced out as Campbell Soup Co. 's president and chief executive officer, the strongest evidence yet of the power that Dorrance family members intend to wield in reshaping the troubled food company. 
01/wsj_0109:Herbert M. Baum, the 53-year-old president of the company's Campbell U.S.A. unit, and Edwin L. Harper, 47, the chief financial officer, will run Campbell as a team, dividing responsibilities rather evenly until a successor is named.
01/wsj_0109:"The profit motive of the major shareholders has clearly changed for the better," said John McMillin, a food industry analyst for Prudential-Bache in New York.
01/wsj_0109:Some of the surge in the stock's price appeared to be linked to revived takeover speculation, which has contributed to volatility of Campbell shares in recent months. 
01/wsj_0109:Campbell's international businesses, particularly in the U.K. and Italy, appear to be at the heart of its problems.
01/wsj_0109:Growth has fallen short of targets and operating earnings are far below results in U.S. units. 
01/wsj_0109:Mr. Harper, a veteran of several manufacturing companies who joined Campbell in 1986, will take charge of all overseas operations as well as Pepperidge. 
01/wsj_0109:Mr. McGovern, 63, had been under intense pressure from the board to boost Campbell's mediocre performance to the level of other food companies.
01/wsj_0109:The board is dominated by the heirs of the late John T. Dorrance Jr., who controlled about 58% of Campbell's stock when he died in April.
01/wsj_0109:Campbell officials said Mr. McGovern wasn't available yesterday to discuss the circumstances of his departure.
01/wsj_0109:But people familiar with the agenda of the board's meeting last week in London said Mr. McGovern was fired. 
01/wsj_0109:Mr. McGovern himself had said repeatedly that he intended to stay on until he reached the conventional retirement age of 65 in October 1991, "unless I get fired." Campbell said Mr. McGovern had withdrawn his name as a candidate for re-election as a director at the annual shareholder meeting, scheduled for Nov. 17. 
01/wsj_0109:For fiscal 1989, Mr. McGovern received a salary of $877,663.
01/wsj_0109:He owns about 45,000 shares of Campbell stock and has options to buy more than 100,000 additional shares.
01/wsj_0109:He will be eligible for an annual pension of more than $244,000 with certain other fringe benefits. 
01/wsj_0109:Mr. Harper expressed confidence that he and Mr. Baum can convince the board of their worthiness to run the company. "We look upon this as a great opportunity to prove the fact that we have a tremendous management team," he said.
01/wsj_0109:Mr. Baum said the two have orders to "focus on bottom-line profits" and to "take a hard look at our businesses -- what is good, what is not so good." Analysts generally applaud the performance of Campbell U.S.A., the company's largest division, which posted 6% unit sales growth and a 15% improvement in operating profit for fiscal 1989. "The way that we've been managing Campbell U.S.A. can hopefully spread to other areas of the company," Mr. Baum said. 
