01/wsj_0117:The United Kingdom High Court declared illegal a variety of interest-rate swap transactions and options deals between a London borough council and commercial banks. 
01/wsj_0117:The ruling could lead to the cancellation of huge bank debts the London Borough of Hammersmith and Fulham ran up after losing heavily on swap transactions.
01/wsj_0117:In response to the ruling, gilt futures swiftly plunged more than a point yesterday before recovering much of the loss by the end of the session.
01/wsj_0117:Gilts, or British government bonds, which also fell sharply initially, retraced some of the losses to end about 3/8 point lower. 
01/wsj_0117:The council, which is alleged to have engaged in over 600 deals valued at over #6 billion ($9.5 billion), lost millions of pounds from soured swap deals.
01/wsj_0117:At one point, Hammersmith is reported to have accounted for as much as 10% of the sterling market in interest-rate swap dealings. 
01/wsj_0117:In most of the British transactions, the municipalities agreed to make floating-rate payments to banks, which would make fixed-rate payments.
01/wsj_0117:The court hearing began in early October at the request of Anthony Hazell, district auditor for Hammersmith, who argued that local councils aren't vested with constitutional authority to engage in such capital-markets activities.
01/wsj_0117:"While this court ruling was only on Hammersmith, it will obviously be very persuasive in other cases of a similar nature," a solicitor representing one of the banks said. 
01/wsj_0117:If the banks exhaust all avenues of appeal, it is possible that they would seek to have the illegality ruling work both ways, some market sources said.
01/wsj_0118:In the aftermath of the stock market's gut-wrenching 190-point drop on Oct. 13, Kidder, Peabody & Co. 's 1,400 stockbrokers across the country began a telephone and letter-writing campaign aimed at quashing the country's second-largest program trader. 
01/wsj_0118:The target of their wrath?
01/wsj_0118:Since October's minicrash, Wall Street has been shaken by an explosion of resentment against program trading, the computer-driven, lightning-fast trades of huge baskets of stocks and futures that can send stock prices reeling in minutes. 
01/wsj_0118:Program trading itself, according to many academics who have studied it, is merely caught in the middle of this battle, unfairly labeled as the evil driving force of the marketplace.
01/wsj_0118:On one side of this power struggle stand the forces in ascendency on Wall Street -- the New Guard -- consisting of high-tech computer wizards at the major brokerage firms, their pension fund clients with immense pools of money, and the traders at the fast-growing Chicago futures exchanges.
01/wsj_0118:These are the main proponents of program trading. 
01/wsj_0118:Defending their ramparts are Wall Street's Old Guard -- the traditional, stock-picking money managers, tens of thousands of stock brokers, the New York Stock Exchange's listed companies and the clannish floor traders, known as specialists, who make markets in their stocks. 
01/wsj_0118:The Chicago Mercantile Exchange, a major futures marketplace, yesterday announced the addition of another layer of trading halts designed to slow program traders during a rapidly falling stock market, and the Big Board is expected today to approve some additional restrictions on program trading. 
01/wsj_0118:Stung by charges that their greed is turning the stock market into a gigantic crapshoot, almost all the big investment banking houses have abandoned index arbitrage, a common form of program trading, for their own accounts in the past few days.
01/wsj_0118:Big Board stock specialists, in a bold palace revolt, began shortly after Oct. 13 to telephone the corporate executives of the companies whose stock is listed on the Big Board to have them pressure the exchange to ban program trading. 
01/wsj_0118:Charles Wohlstetter, the chairman of Contel Corp. who is rallying other CEOs to the anti-program trading cause, says he has received "countless" letters offering support. "They said universally, without a single exception: Don't even compromise.
01/wsj_0118:Program trading money managers have gained control over a big chunk of the invested funds in this country, and the pressures on such money managers to produce consistent profits has wedded them to the ability to move rapidly in and out the market that program trading gives them.
01/wsj_0118:What's more, the last time major Wall Street firms said they were getting out of program trading -- in the aftermath of the 1987 crash -- they waited a few months and then sneaked back into it. 
01/wsj_0118:Even some members of the Old Guard, despite their current advantage, seem to be conceding that the future belongs with the New Guard.
01/wsj_0118:Last week, Robert M. Bradley, one of the Big Board's most respected floor traders and head of a major traders' organization, surrendered.
01/wsj_0118:At Kidder, a unit of General Electric Co., and other big brokerage firms, stockbrokers battle their own firm's program traders a few floors away.
01/wsj_0118:But the Big Board's leadership -- over the specialists' protests -- two weeks ago began trading a new stock "basket" product designed to facilitate program trading. "A lot of people would like to go back to 1970," before program trading, Mr. Phelan said this week. "I would like to go back to 1970.
01/wsj_0118:They say greedy market manipulators have made a shambles of the nation's free-enterprise system, turning the stock market into a big gambling den, with the odds heavily stacked against the small investor. "The public didn't come to the market to play a game; they can go to Off-Track Betting for that," says A. Brean Murray, chairman of Brean Murray, Foster Securities, a traditional money management firm. 
01/wsj_0118:The program traders, on the other hand, portray old-fashioned stock pickers as the Neanderthals of the industry.
01/wsj_0118:Critics like Mr. Murray "are looking for witches, and people who use computers to trade are a convenient boogieman," says J. Thomas Allen, president of Advanced Investment Management Inc., a Pittsburgh firm that runs a $200 million fund that uses index arbitrage. "Just a blind fear of the unknown is causing them to beg the regulators for protection." 
01/wsj_0118:For all the furor, there is nothing particularly complex about the concept of stock-index arbitrage, the most controversial type of computer-assisted program trading.
01/wsj_0118:Like other forms of arbitrage, it merely seeks to take advantage of momentary discrepancies in the price of a single product -- in this case, a basket of stocks -- in different markets -- in this case the New York Stock Exchange and the Chicago futures markets. 
01/wsj_0118:When it occurs, the traders place orders via computers to buy the basket of stocks (such as the 500 stocks that constitute the Standard & Poor's 500 stock index) in whichever market is cheaper and sell them in the more expensive market; they lock in the difference in price as profit. 
01/wsj_0118:Such program trades, which can involve the purchase or sale of millions of dollars of stock, occur in a matter of seconds.
01/wsj_0118:A program trade of $5 million of stock typically earns a razor-thin profit of $25,000.
01/wsj_0118:To keep program-trading units profitable in the eyes of senior brokerage executives, traders must seize every opportunity their computers find. 
01/wsj_0118:But many experts and traders say that program trading isn't the main reason for stock-market gyrations. "I have not seen one iota of evidence" to support restrictions on program trading, says a Vanderbilt University finance professor, Hans Stoll, an authority on the subject.
01/wsj_0118:The Oct. 13 plunge was triggered not by program traders, but by news of the unraveling of the $6.79 billion buy-out of UAL Corp. Unable to unload UAL and other airline shares, takeover-stock speculators, or risk arbitragers, dumped every blue-chip stock they had.
01/wsj_0118:Susan Del Signore, head trader at Travelers Investment Management Co., says critics are ignoring "the role the {takeover stock} speculator is taking in the market as a source of volatility." Many arbs are "overleveraged," she says, and they "have to sell when things look like they fall apart." 
01/wsj_0118:Like virtually everything on Wall Street, the program-trading battle is over money, and the traditionalists have been losing out on bundles of it to the New Guard in recent years.
01/wsj_0118:Yet many such managers consistently fail to even keep up with, much less beat, the returns of standard benchmarks like the S&P 
01/wsj_0118:Today, about $200 billion, or 20% of all pension-fund stock investments, is held by index funds. 
01/wsj_0118:The new Wall Street of computers and automated trading threatens to make dinosaurs of the 49 Big Board stock-specialist firms.
01/wsj_0118:These small but influential floor brokers long have earned fat returns of 30% to 40% a year on their capital, by virtue of their monopoly in making markets in individual stocks.
01/wsj_0118:The son of a specialist and once one himself, Mr. Phelan has nonetheless been striving -- with products like the new stock basket that his former colleagues dislike so much -- to keep index funds and other program traders from taking their business to overseas markets. 
01/wsj_0118:Meanwhile, specialists' trading risks have skyrocketed as a result of stock-market volatility. "When the sell programs hit, you can hear the order printers start to go" on the Big Board trading floor, says one specialist there. "The buyers walk away, and the specialist is left alone" as the buyer of last resort for his stable of stocks, he contends. 
01/wsj_0118:They are still trying to lure back small investors spooked by the 1987 stock-market crash and the market's swings since then. "Small investors are absolutely dismayed that Wall Street is stacking the deck against them, and these wide swings are scaring them to death," says Raymond A. Mason, chairman of regional broker Legg Mason Inc. in Baltimore.
01/wsj_0118:Corporate executives resent that their company's stock has been transformed into a nameless piece of a stock-index basket.
01/wsj_0118:Index traders who buy all 500 stocks in the S&P 500 often don't even know what the companies they own actually do, complains Andrew Sigler, chairman of Champion International Corp. "Do you make sweatshirts or sparkplugs?
01/wsj_0118:By this September, program traders were doing a record 13.8% of the Big Board's average daily trading volume.
01/wsj_0118:Stock futures trading has minted dozens of millionaires in their 20s and 30s.
01/wsj_0118:Now, on a good day, Chicago's stock-index traders trade more dollars worth of stock futures than the Big Board trades in stock. 
01/wsj_0118:"You're not going to stop the idea of trading a basket of stocks," says Vanderbilt's Prof.
01/wsj_0118:Short of a total ban, some anti-programmers have proposed several middle-ground reforms, which they say would take away certain advantages program traders currently enjoy in the marketplace that other investors don't. 
01/wsj_0118:One such proposal regarding stock-index futures is an increase in the margin requirement -- or the "good-faith" payment of cash needed to trade them -- to about the same level as the margin requirement for stocks.
01/wsj_0118:Higher margins would chase away dozens of smaller traders who help larger traders buy and sell, they say. 
01/wsj_0118:Another proposed reform is to have program traders answer to an "uptick rule"a reform instituted after the Great Crash of 1929 that protects against stocks being relentlessly beaten downward by those seeking to profit from lower prices, namely short sellers.
01/wsj_0118:The Big Board's uptick rule prevents the short sale of a stock when the stock is falling in price. 
01/wsj_0118:A reinstatement of the uptick rule for program traders would slow their activity considerably.
01/wsj_0118:Program traders argue that a reinstatement of the rule would destroy the "pricing efficiency" of the futures and stock markets. 
01/wsj_0118:Thus the band-wagon psychology of recent days picks up new impetus. 
01/wsj_0118:Index arbitrage is a common form of program trading.
01/wsj_0118:As usually practiced it takes advantage of a rather basic concept: Two separate markets in different locations, trading basically the same widgets, can't trade them for long at prices that are widely different.
01/wsj_0118:If the money manager performing this service is being paid by his clients to match or beat the return of the S&P 500 index, he is likely to remain fully invested at all times. (Few, if any, index-fund managers will risk leveraging performance by owning more than 100% exposure to stocks, and equally few will want to own less than a 100% position should stocks rise.) 
01/wsj_0118:By constantly seeking to own the cheapest widget, index-arbitrage traders hope to add between 1% and 3% to the annual return of the S&P 500.
01/wsj_0118:The fact that a vast majority of fundamentalist money managers fail to beat the S&P 500 may contribute to the hysteria surrounding the issue. 
01/wsj_0118:The New York Stock Exchange's attempt to introduce a new portfolio basket is evidence of investors' desires to make fast and easy transactions of large numbers of shares. 
01/wsj_0118:So if index arbitrage is simply taking advantage of thin inefficiencies between two markets for the same widget, how did "program trading" evolve into the evil creature that is evoking the curses of so many observers?
01/wsj_0118:But many of these reforms are unneeded, even harmful. 
01/wsj_0118:The start of the whole process is the key-someone must fundamentally increase or decrease his ownership in widgets to make widget prices move. 
01/wsj_0118:Why does this large hypothetical seller trade in Chicago instead of New York?
01/wsj_0118:Perhaps he is willing to sacrifice to the arbitrage trader some small profit in order to get quick and certain execution of his large trade.
01/wsj_0118:Volatility surrounding his trades occurs not because of index arbitrage, but because his is a large addition or subtraction to a widget market with finite liquidity.
01/wsj_0118:Eliminate arbitrage and liquidity will decline instead of rising, creating more volatility instead of less.
01/wsj_0118:The speed of his transaction isn't to be feared either, because faster and cleaner execution is desirable, not loathsome.
01/wsj_0118:If slowing things down could reduce volatility, stone tablets should become the trade ticket of the future. 
01/wsj_0118:We must be very cautious about labeling investors as "long-term" or "short-term." Policies designed to encourage one type of investor over another are akin to placing a sign over the Big Board's door saying: "Buyers welcome, sellers please go away!" The ultimate goal of any investor is a profit motive, and regulators should not concern themselves with whether investors are sufficiently focused on the long term.
01/wsj_0118:In point of fact, volatility as measured by the annualized standard deviation of daily stock price movements has frequently been much higher than it is today.
01/wsj_0118:Periods before the advent of futures or program trading were often more volatile, usually when fundamental market conditions were undergoing change (1973-75, 1937-40, and 1928-33 for example).
01/wsj_0118:Could rising volatility possibly be related to uncertainty about the economics of stocks, instead of the evil deeds of program-trading goblins? 
01/wsj_0118:Some of the proposed fixes for what is labeled "program-trading volatility" could be far worse than the perceived problem.
01/wsj_0118:This argument is perhaps the most interesting one for abolishing program trading -- not because of its merits, but because of the firms championing the cause.
01/wsj_0118:The loudest of these reformers are money managers who cater to smaller investors.
01/wsj_0118:Yet our efforts are somehow less noble than those of an investment expert studiously devouring press clippings on each company he follows. 
01/wsj_0118:Almost all new regulation is introduced in the interests of protecting the little guy, and he invariably is the one least able to cope with its consequences. 
01/wsj_0118:The sad reality is that the retail investor continues to pursue stellar performers first, while leaving institutions to grapple with basis points of performance on large sums of money quarter by quarter.
