01/wsj_0123:Researchers at American Telephone & Telegraph Co. 's Bell Laboratories reported they raised the electrical current-carrying capacity of new superconductor crystals by a factor of 100, moving the materials closer to commercial use. 
01/wsj_0123:The scientists said they created small changes in the crystal-lattice structures of the superconductors to raise the amount of current that single crystals could carry to 600,000 amps per square centimeter in a moderately strong magnetic field.
01/wsj_0123:Their report appears in today's issue of the journal Nature. 
01/wsj_0123:Scientists had obtained even higher current-carrying capacity in thin films of the new superconductors, but have had problems increasing the amount of current that bulk crystals could carry. 
01/wsj_0123:A family of ceramic superconductors discovered during the past three years promise new technologies such as cheaper electrical generation -- but only if their current-carrying capacity can be raised. 
01/wsj_0123:The AT&T advance shows how one aspect of the current-carrying problem can be overcome.
01/wsj_0123:But "it won't lead to imminent use" of new superconductors, cautioned Robert B. van Dover, one of the AT&T researchers.
01/wsj_0123:He added that the current-carrying capacity of multi-crystal samples of superconductors remains too low for most practical uses because of so-called weak links between crystals.
01/wsj_0123:Still, scientists breathed a collective sigh of relief about the finding, because it demonstrates how to overcome the "flux pinning" problem that earlier this year was widely publicized as undercutting new superconductors' potential.
01/wsj_0123:The problem involves the motion of small magnetic fields within superconductor crystals, limiting their current-carrying capacity.
01/wsj_0123:The combined processes may significantly raise the current-carrying capacity of multi-crystal samples. 
