02/wsj_0286:This corporate glasnost is a big reason Nissan, after years of making lackluster cars and lousy profits, has loosened up its rigid ways and now is riding a string of hits, ranging from the sleek Maxima sedan and Porsche-like 300ZX to the whimsically nostalgic Pao, a minicar sold only in Japan.
02/wsj_0286:Atsushi Muramatsu, Nissan's executive vice president for finance, helped set the tone in December 1986, when the company was heading toward the first operating loss by a Japanese auto maker since the nation's postwar recovery. "This is a time of self-criticism to discover what is wrong with us," he said.
02/wsj_0286:Nissan's market share in Japan had been dropping year by year since the beginning of the decade.
02/wsj_0286:Its U.S. sales sagged, partly because of price increases due to the rising yen.
02/wsj_0286:Worst of all, Nissan was preoccupied with management infighting, cronyism and corporate rigidity. 
02/wsj_0286:Consider the experience of Satoko Kitada, a 30-year-old designer of vehicle interiors who joined Nissan in 1982.
02/wsj_0286:At that time, tasks were assigned strictly on the basis of seniority. "The oldest designer got to work on the dashboard," she recalls. "The next level down did doors.
02/wsj_0286:If a new person got to work on part of the speedometer, that was a big deal." 
02/wsj_0286:Meanwhile, President Kume ordered everyone from top executives to rookie designers to go "town watching," to visit chic parts of Tokyo to try to gain insights into developing cars for trend-setters. 
02/wsj_0286:One group of middle-aged manufacturing men from the company's Zama plant outside Tokyo was supposed to check out a trendy restaurant in the city.
02/wsj_0286:But when they arrived at the door, all were afraid to go in, fearing that they would be out of place. 
