02/wsj_0296:Mr. Wain is editor of The Asian Wall Street Journal. 
02/wsj_0297:Dr. Levy's answer may come with a new kind of magnetic brain probe, a device that he and dozens of U.S. researchers are studying with great hope.
02/wsj_0297:Besides holding the promise of safer spinal surgery, the probe could improve the diagnosis of brain and nerve disorders such as strokes and multiple sclerosis.
02/wsj_0297:Perhaps most exciting, the device is thrusting open a window to the workings of the brain. 
02/wsj_0297:The probe, which is painless, non-invasive and apparently harmless, employs strong magnetic fields to induce small whirlwinds of electricity within the brain.
02/wsj_0297:"Until now, we've had no objective way of measuring motor function," says Keith Chiappa, a neurologist conducting clinical tests with the devices at Boston's Massachusetts General Hospital. "All we could do was tell a patient, `squeeze my fingers as hard as you can' or `raise your arm. ' " Under the best circumstances such tests are subjective; when a patient is unconscious, they don't work at all. 
02/wsj_0297:Magnetic brain tweaking started in the early 1900s, when researchers produced flashes of light in the visual field with magnets.
02/wsj_0297:But for brain tests, the unwieldy machines "would have required patients to stand on their heads," says Reginald Bickford, a researcher at the University of California at San Diego. 
02/wsj_0297:"We don't feel we can use {the devices} routinely in surgery yet, but we're getting close," says Dr. Levy, who is now with the University of Pittsburgh.
02/wsj_0297:The devices could help indicate when surgery would help, says Charles Tator, a University of Toronto neurosurgeon.
02/wsj_0297:"The cost {of magnetic stimulators} would seem like peanuts if we could retrieve limb function" in such people, Dr. Tator says. 
02/wsj_0297:But no significant problems have been reported among hundreds of people tested with the devices. 
02/wsj_0297:And some doctors who have conducted hours of tests on themselves report temporary headaches. 
02/wsj_0297:At least two companies, Cadwell Laboratories Inc. of Kennewick, Wash., and Novametrix Medical Systems Inc. of Wallingford, Conn., now sell versions of the magnetic devices.
02/wsj_0297:At the University of Kentucky, a team led by Dean Currier, a physical therapy researcher, is testing the stimulators in conjunction with electric shocks to induce muscle contractions to help prevent wasting of thigh muscles after knee surgery.
02/wsj_0297:Probing with the stimulators, National Institutes of Health scientists recently showed how the brain reorganizes motor-control resources after an amputation.
02/wsj_0297:At the State University of New York at Brooklyn, researchers flash two groups of different letters on a computer screen in front of human guinea pigs.
02/wsj_0297:When the jolt is timed just right, the subjects don't recall seeing the first group of letters. 
02/wsj_0297:"Where does that first stimulus go?" exclaims SUNY neurologist Paul Maccabee. "Trying to answer that is suggesting all kinds of theories," such as precisely where and how the brain processes incoming signals from the eyes.
02/wsj_0298:The collaboration will include at least 25 researchers and will be aimed primarily at developing thin films of high-temperature superconductors for use in electronics, the companies said.
02/wsj_0298:Joint-research programs have proliferated as U.S. companies seek to spread the risks and costs of commercializing new superconductors and to meet the challenges posed by foreign consortia, especially in Japan. 
02/wsj_0298:The latest research pact bolsters Du Pont's growing portfolio of investments in superconductors.
02/wsj_0298:Last year, Du Pont agreed to pay $4.5 million for rights to superconductor work at the University of Houston. 
02/wsj_0298:The Los Alamos laboratory is one of three U.S. Department of Energy national laboratories designed as pilot centers to foster joint industry-government programs to speed the transfer of new superconductors to the marketplace. 
