03/wsj_0301:Shaken by tumbling stock prices and pessimistic projections of U.S. economic growth, currency analysts around the world have toned down their assessments of the dollar's near-term performance. 
03/wsj_0301:Most of the 10 analysts polled last week by Dow Jones International News Service in Frankfurt, Tokyo, London and New York expect the U.S. dollar to ease only mildly in November.
03/wsj_0301:Half of those polled see the currency trending lower over the next three months, while the others forecast a modest rebound after the New Year. 
03/wsj_0301:A month ago, a similar survey predicted the dollar would be trading at 1.8690 marks and 139.75 yen by the end of October.
03/wsj_0301:In Tokyo Wednesday, the U.S. currency was trading at about 142.95 yen at midmorning, up from 142.80 yen at the opening and up from Tuesday's Tokyo close of 142.15 yen. 
03/wsj_0301:The average of estimates of the 10 economists polled puts the dollar around 1.8200 marks at the end of November and at 141.33 yen. 
03/wsj_0301:A number of those polled predict the dollar will slip as the Federal Reserve eases interest rates. 
03/wsj_0301:David Owen, an economist at Kleinwort Benson & Co. in London, said he expects further cuts in short-term U.S. rates in an effort to encourage a narrowing of the trade gap and to ensure a soft landing in the U.S. economy. 
03/wsj_0301:Robert White, a vice president and manager of corporate trade at First Interstate of California, agreed with that view and predicted the U.S. federal funds rate will drop to between 7 3/4% and 8% within 60 days from its current level at 8 13/16%.
03/wsj_0301:He expects such a cut "because of problems in several sectors of the economy, particularly real estate and automobiles." 
03/wsj_0301:In last month's survey, a number of currency analysts predicted the dollar would be pressured by a narrowing of interest rate differentials between the U.S. and West Germany. 
03/wsj_0301:But predictions that central banks of the Group of Seven (G-7) major industrial nations would continue their massive dollar sales went astray, as the market drove the dollar downward on its own, reacting to Wall Street's plunge and subsequent price volatility, lower U.S. interest rates and signs of a slowing U.S. economy.
03/wsj_0301:G-7 consists of the U.S., Japan, Britain, West Germany, Canada, France and Italy. 
03/wsj_0301:Tomoshige Kakita, senior deputy manager in the treasury department of Mitsui Bank Ltd. in Tokyo, suggested that uncertainty about U.S. stocks and bonds has made Japanese investors leery of holding those securities in the near term, thus damping dollar demand. 
03/wsj_0301:Alfred Zapfel, chief trader at Bank of Boston in Frankfurt, took an opposite stance.
03/wsj_0301:He said he expects U.S. interest rates to decline, dragging the dollar down to around 1.80 marks by the end of January after a short-lived dash to 1.87 marks by the end of November.
03/wsj_0301:"But I'm not one of these great dollar bears you see more of these days," Mr. Zapfel said. "I can't really see it dropping far below 1.80 marks." 
03/wsj_0301:Scott Greene, chief foreign exchange dealer with Julius Baer & Co. in New York, fits the description of a "great dollar bear." He predicted the U.S. unit will skid below 1.80 marks to around 1.78 marks this month and 1.75 marks by the beginning of the new year. 
03/wsj_0301:"We're finally seeing the culmination of all the recessionary buildup of the last few months," he said, noting a continuing downward trend in U.S. interest rates, a shaky stock market and "gloomier economic times ahead" all signal a significantly lower dollar. 
03/wsj_0301:In the wake of British Chancellor of the Exchequer Nigel Lawson's surprise resignation and sterling's subsequent nose-dive, most analysts had little good to say about the pound's near-term prospects. 
03/wsj_0301:Mr. Owen of Kleinwort Benson suggested that the new chancellor, John Major, will take a tough line in his autumn statement later this month, helping to underpin the pound.
03/wsj_0302:West Germany will repeal the unpopular turnover tax on securities transactions as of Jan. 1, 1991, Economics Minister Helmut Haussmann said. 
03/wsj_0302:He said the government will also repeal the 1% transaction tax on the first-time purchase of stakes in companies. 
03/wsj_0302:The announcement follows several comments by government officials that the government will speed up the repeal of the tax, which was originally scheduled to fall with the start of the single internal market in the European Community at the end of 1992. 
03/wsj_0302:The securities-turnover tax has been long criticized by the West German financial community because it tends to drive securities trading and other banking activities out of Frankfurt into rival financial centers, especially London, where trading transactions isn't taxed. 
03/wsj_0302:In the interview, Mr. Haussmann didn't specify the amount of revenue the government will lose after the tax disappears. 
03/wsj_0302:The new date means that the tax will be officially repealed before the end of the current parliamentary term at the end of 1990 and guarantees its abolition even if the current center-right coalition loses the elections in December 1990. 
