03/wsj_0339:(During its centennial year, The Wall Street Journal will report events of the past century that stand as milestones of American business history.) 
03/wsj_0339:In 1953, James Watson and his colleagues unlocked the double helix of DNA (deoxyribonucleic acid), the genetic key to heredity.
03/wsj_0339:With $500 apiece and an injection of outside capital, they formed Genentech Inc. Commercial gene-splicing was born. 
03/wsj_0339:The next to be cloned, human insulin, had market potential and Genentech licensed it to Eli Lilly, which produced 80% of the insulin used by 1.5 million U.S. diabetics. 
03/wsj_0339:At the time, Genentech had only one profitable year behind it (a modest $116,000 on revenue of $2.6 million in 1979) and no product of its own on the market.
03/wsj_0339:Gene-splicing now is an integral part of the drug business.
