03/wsj_0384:As the leading candidate for president of his country in next year's election, Mario Vargas Llosa ought to be in an enviable position.
03/wsj_0384:Published everywhere to universal acclaim, doted on like a movie star in the Hispanic world from Barcelona to Ushuaia, Mr. Vargas Llosa could live comfortably on his royalties and console his political conscience with the thought that Peru is a hopeless mess not of his making and that he already did his best to reform it with his magnificently cinematic novel about the years of military dictatorship of his youth, "Conversation in the Cathedral." 
03/wsj_0384:But, after some hesitation, he is back on the stump and also still writing important novels about Peru. "The Storyteller" (Farrar, Straus & Giroux, 246 pages, $17.95), splendidly translated by Helen Lane, first appeared in Spanish in 1987 before the Peruvian economy had reached its present state of virtual collapse.
03/wsj_0384:Even still, the very first sentence of this fable that weaves together Peru's most advanced and most primitive cultural strands speaks of "my unfortunate country." The narrator may be talking about the depredations of the Shining Path Maoists among the Indians of the Andes, or he may be referring to the plunging inti, Peru's rubber currency, or the corrupting effect of the cocaine trade.
03/wsj_0384:But he is swiftly drawn into a tangle of memories about a less newsworthy and more exotic part of Peru: its corner of the Amazon jungle. 
03/wsj_0384:He is in Florence to shake himself free of Peru and get some writing done, just as Mr. Vargas Llosa has gone to Paris and now goes frequently to London for the same purpose.
03/wsj_0384:But this narrator happens upon some photographs in a gallery, pictures taken in Peruvian Amazonia of the untamed and nomadic Machiguenga tribe.
03/wsj_0384:And they remind him of his own experiences with that unhappy scattered culture and of his friend at Lima's University of San Marcos, Saul Zuratas.
03/wsj_0384:Saul was a high-strung student of ethnography, a Jew marked doubly as an outsider because of a huge wine-dark birthmark on his face, for which people called him Mascarita, Mask Face.
03/wsj_0384:Saul knew about the Machiguengas from his studies, and through him the narrator became interested in this most recalcitrant and un-Westernizable of all the indigenous peoples who had come under the Spanish yoke.
03/wsj_0384:Saul, meanwhile, came to believe that anthropology, even at its most benign, was as insidious a form of cultural imperialism as the superficially more blatant activities of Christian missionaries.
03/wsj_0384:This is what we know at the end of the opening section of "The Storyteller." The next voice we hear sounds like this: "There was no evil, there was no wind, there was no rain.
03/wsj_0384:For most of the book, there is no direct connection between its urban and its Amazonian modes.
03/wsj_0384:But the contrast between them becomes a living thing through the brilliant contrast of narrative styles that Mr. Vargas Llosa creates.
03/wsj_0384:The storytellers traveled among the bands, reminding them of their identity.
03/wsj_0384:I am trying to give away as little as possible, but this is not really a mystery or some kind of jungle thriller.
03/wsj_0384:It will be read for the brilliant clash of styles of narration and the even more brilliant way that they have been tied together into a large metaphor for literature and its function in society. 
