04/wsj_0415:The candidates have been crisscrossing this huge country of 145 million people, holding rallies and televised debates in hope of being elected to what must be one of the world's most thankless political jobs: trying to drag Brazil out of its economic and social mess. 
04/wsj_0415:A half-dozen candidates, backing policies ranging from Thatcherism to watered-down Marxism, are given a chance of winning. "Whoever says he knows which of the six will win is out of his mind," says Antonio Britto, a centrist member of Parliament. 
04/wsj_0415:The favorite remains Fernando Collor de Mello, a 40-year-old former governor of the state of Alagoas.
04/wsj_0415:He came out of nowhere to grab the lead in opinion polls, probably less because of his vague program to "build a new Brazil" than because of his good looks, the open backing of the powerful Rede Globo television network and his reputation as a hunter of "maharajahs," or overpaid and underworked civil servants. 
04/wsj_0415:But after building up a commanding lead, the moderate to conservative Mr. Collor has slipped to about 30% in the polls from a high of about 43% only a few weeks ago.
04/wsj_0415:To avoid a runoff, one candidate would have to win 50% of the vote -- a feat that most analysts consider impossible with so many candidates running. 
04/wsj_0415:Two left-wing politicians, Socialist Leonel Brizola, a former governor of Rio de Janeiro state, and Marxist-leaning Luis Inacio da Silva, currently are running neck and neck at about 15%, and three other candidates are given a chance of reaching the Dec. 17 runoff election between the two biggest vote-getters: Social Democrat Mario Covas and two conservatives, Paulo Salim Maluf, a former governor of the state of Sao Paulo, and Guilherme Afif Domingos. 
04/wsj_0415:The dollar, the best indicator of the country's mood, has skyrocketed on the parallel market, as has gold.
