04/wsj_0437:Declines came because of concern that demand for copper may slow down. 
04/wsj_0437:The December contract was down three cents a pound, settling at $1.1280, which was just above the day's low of $1.1270. 
04/wsj_0437:Futures prices fell during three of five sessions last week, and the losses, individually and cumulatively, were greater than the advances. 
04/wsj_0437:Two of the major factors buoying prices, the prolonged strikes at the Highland Valley mine in Canada and the Cananea mine in Mexico, were finally resolved.
04/wsj_0437:Also, the premiums paid by the U.S. government on a purchase of copper for the U.S. Mint were lower than expected, and acted as a price depressant, analysts said.
04/wsj_0437:At the time merchants were asking for premiums of about five cents a pound. 
04/wsj_0437:All this has led to prolonged selling in futures, mostly on the part of computer-guided funds.
04/wsj_0437:The reluctance of traders to buy contracts indicates that they have begun focusing on demand rather than supply.
04/wsj_0437:At least one analyst noted that as production improves, the concern among traders is whether the prospective increased supply will find buyers because of uncertainty over national economies. 
04/wsj_0437:"Demand from Japan is expected to continue strong, but not from other areas of the world into the first quarter of next year," he said. 
04/wsj_0437:The Bougainville mine is generally expected to remain closed until at least the end of the year.
04/wsj_0437:It hasn't been operating since May 15 because of attacks by native landowners.
04/wsj_0437:The mines produced a total of 110,000 tons of copper in 1988. 
