04/wsj_0465:Medical scientists are starting to uncover a handful of genes which, if damaged, unleash the chaotic growth of cells that characterizes cancer. 
04/wsj_0465:Scientists say the discovery of these genes in recent months is painting a new and startling picture of how cancer develops.
04/wsj_0465:An emerging understanding of the genes is expected to produce an array of new strategies for future cancer treatment and prevention. 
04/wsj_0465:"It's a super-exciting set of discoveries," says Bert Vogelstein, a Johns Hopkins University researcher who has just found a gene pivotal to the triggering of colon cancer. "Only a decade ago cancer was a black box about which we knew nothing at the molecular level.
04/wsj_0465:Today, we know that the accumulation of several of these altered genes can initiate a cancer and, then, propel it into a deadly state." 
04/wsj_0465:Scientists call the new class of genes tumor-suppressors, or simply anti-cancer genes.
04/wsj_0465:The newly identified genes differ from a family of genes discovered in the early 1980s called oncogenes.
04/wsj_0465:In recent months, researchers have come to believe the two types of cancer genes work in concert: An oncogene may turn proliferating cells malignant only after the tumor-suppressor gene has been damaged. 
04/wsj_0465:A person who is born with one defective copy of a suppressor gene, or in whom one copy is damaged early in life, is especially prone to cancer because he need only lose the other copy for a cancer to develop. 
04/wsj_0465:Emerging genetic tests will be able to spot such cancer-susceptible individuals, ushering in what some scientists believe is a new age of predictive cancer diagnosis. 
04/wsj_0465:Bill and Bonnie Quinlan are among the first beneficiaries of the new findings.
04/wsj_0465:The Dedham, Mass., couple knew even before Bonnie became pregnant in 1987 that any child of theirs had a 50% chance of being at risk for retinoblastoma, an eye cancer that occurs about once every 20,000 births.
04/wsj_0465:Because of the isolation of the retinoblastoma tumor-suppressor gene, it became possible last January to find out what threat the Quinlan baby faced.
04/wsj_0465:A test using new "genetic probes" showed that little Will Quinlan had not inherited a damaged retinoblastoma supressor gene and, therefore, faced no more risk than other children of developing the rare cancer. "It made our New Year," says Mr. Quinlan. 
04/wsj_0465:Equally important, the initial discovery of the gene that controls retinal cell growth, made by a Boston doctor named Thaddeus Dryja, has opened a field of cancer study, which in recent months has exploded. "It turns out that studying a tragic but uncommon tumor made possible some fundamental insights about the most basic workings of cancer," says Samuel Broder, director of the National Cancer Institute. "All this may not be obvious to the public, which is concerned about advances in treatment, but I am convinced this basic research will begin showing results there soon." 
04/wsj_0465:To date, scientists have fingered two of these cancer-suppressors.
04/wsj_0465:Colon, lung and breast cancers are the most common and lethal forms of the disease, collectively killing almost 200,000 Americans a year.
04/wsj_0465:Researchers say the inactivation of tumor-suppressor genes, alone or in combination, appears crucial to the development of such scourges as cancer of the brain, the skin, kidney, prostate, and cervix.
04/wsj_0465:There is evidence that if people inherit defective versions of these genes, they are especially prone to cancer, perhaps explaining, finally, why some cancers seem to haunt certain families. 
04/wsj_0465:The story of tumor-suppressor genes goes back to the 1970s, when a pediatrician named Alfred G. Knudson Jr. proposed that retinoblastoma stemmed from two separate genetic defects.
04/wsj_0465:He theorized that in the eye cancer, an infant inherited a damaged copy of a gene from one parent and a normal copy from the other.
04/wsj_0465:Back then, scientists had no way of ferreting out specific genes, but under a microscope they could see the 23 pairs of chromosomes in the cells that contain the genes.
04/wsj_0465:Dr. Knudson found that some children with the eye cancer had inherited a damaged copy of chromosome No. 13 from a parent who had had the disease.
04/wsj_0465:Under a microscope he could actually see that a bit of chromosome 13 was missing.
04/wsj_0465:Then, a scientific team led by molecular geneticist Webster Cavenee, then at the University of Utah, found the answer.
04/wsj_0465:The team used a battery of the newly developed "gene probes," snippets of genetic material that can track a gene's presence in a cell.
04/wsj_0465:By analyzing cells extracted from eye tumors, they found defects in the second copy of chromosome 13 in the exact area as in the first copy of the chromosome. 
04/wsj_0465:It was the first time anyone had showed that the loss of both copies of the same gene could lead to the eruption of a cancer. "It was extraordinarily satisfying," says Dr. Knudson, now at Fox Chase Cancer Research Center in Philadelphia. "I was convinced that what was true of retinoblastoma would be true for all cancers." 
04/wsj_0465:His was one of two research teams in 1984 to report dual chromosome losses for a rare childhood cancer of the kidney called Wilm's tumor. 
04/wsj_0465:It often is preceded by the development of polyps in the bowel, which in some cases become increasingly malignant in identifiable stages -- progressing from less severe to deadly -- as though a cascade of genetic damage might be occurring. 
04/wsj_0465:Dr. Vogelstein and a doctoral student, Eric Fearon, began months of tedious and often frustrating probing of the chromosomes searching for signs of genetic damage.
04/wsj_0465:They began uncovering a confusing variety of genetic deletions, some existing only in benign polyps, others in malignant cells and many in both polyps and malignant cells.
04/wsj_0465:Gradually, a coherent picture of cancer development emerged.
04/wsj_0465:If both copies of a certain gene were knocked out, benign polyps would develop.
04/wsj_0465:If both copies of a second gene were then deleted, the polyps would progress to malignancy.
04/wsj_0465:Their report galvanized other molecular biologists. "It was the confirming evidence we all needed that {gene} losses were critical to the development of a common tumor," says Ray White at Howard Hughes Medical Institute in Salt Lake City. 
04/wsj_0465:But Dr. Vogelstein had yet to nail the identity of the gene that, if damaged, flipped a colon cell into full-blown malignancy.
04/wsj_0465:For months the Johns Hopkins researchers, using gene probes, experimentally crawled down the length of chromosome 17, looking for the smallest common bit of genetic material lost in all tumor cells.
04/wsj_0465:Such a piece of DNA would probably constitute a gene. 
04/wsj_0465:Despite that, when the Johns Hopkins scientists compared the gene they had found in the human cancer cells with the Mr. Levine's p53 gene they found the two were identical; it turned out that in Mr. Levine's cancer studies, he had unknowingly been observing a damaged form of p53 -- a cancer-suppressing gene. 
04/wsj_0465:The discovery "suddenly puts an obscure gene right in the cockpit of cancer formation," says Robert Weinberg, a leader in cancer-gene research at Whitehead Institute in Cambridge, Mass. 
04/wsj_0465:Researchers in Edinburgh, Scotland, have found that in 23 of 38 breast tumors, one copy of chromosome 17 was mutated at the spot where gene p53 lies.
04/wsj_0465:The scientists say that since breast cancer often strikes multiple members of certain families, the gene, when inherited in a damaged form, may predispose women to the cancer. 
04/wsj_0465:There also are reports from several labs, as yet unpublished, of missing p53 genes in tissue taken from kidney, brain and skin cancers. 
04/wsj_0465:Ray White in Utah and Walter Bodmer, a researcher in Great Britain, are close to finding another gene involved with some types of colon cancer, thought to be on chromosome 5. 
04/wsj_0465:Dr. Minna believes people who inherit a defective gene somewhere on one of their two copies of chromosome 3 are especially prone to lung cancer.
04/wsj_0465:Already two major pharmaceutical companies, the Squibb unit of Bristol-Myers Squibb Co. and Hoffmann-La Roche Inc., are collaborating with gene hunters to turn the anticipated cascade of discoveries into predictive tests and, maybe, new therapies. 
04/wsj_0465:The idea would be to administer to patients the growth-controlling proteins made by healthy versions of the damaged genes.
04/wsj_0465:In any case, says Dr. Minna of the National Cancer Institute, "We're witnessing the discovery of one of the most important steps in the genesis of cancer." 
