05/wsj_0564:Sitting beside a banker at a luncheon in London, where he was working as a financial consultant, he learned that a large packet of Bally's shares was up for sale.
05/wsj_0564:Looking into Bally, he could hardly believe what he saw: a company with enormous real-estate holdings in major European cities and a market capitalization of 28 million Swiss francs; it had 7,000 employees. 
05/wsj_0564:Investing four million Swiss francs earned from his financial transactions and two million Swiss francs from his parents and his wife, Mr. Rey acquired 20% of Bally's shares. 
05/wsj_0564:But such tactics were alien to Switzerland in 1976, and still aren't common because of share restrictions that companies are allowed to maintain.
05/wsj_0564:In 1979, his career as an industrialist began with the acquisition of the Swiss metals works Selve, based in Thun.
05/wsj_0564:Three years later, machinery producer Ateliers de Constructions Mecaniques de Vevey S.A. was to become part of the Rey empire.
05/wsj_0564:A major boost to Mr. Rey's respectability among the Swiss came in 1986 when he sold 60% of his Phibro Bank to the conservative Swiss cantonal banks.
05/wsj_0564:In 1987, Mr. Rey bested leading publishing houses to take over Switzerland's Jean Frey AG, a major producer of magazines and newspapers. 
05/wsj_0564:And with the recent acquisition of 30% of Winterthur-based machinery manufacturer Gebrueder Sulzer AG, Mr. Rey has enjoyed the status of white knight.
05/wsj_0564:Meanwhile, as such strategic investments have mounted, the merchant-banking arm of Mr. Rey's Omni Holding has been busily buying and selling dozens of companies, often after a financial or corporate restructuring. 
05/wsj_0564:Today, this branch of Mr. Rey's empire runs under the name Omnicorp Offering Services and handles mergers and acquisitions, placement of securities and real estate.
05/wsj_0564:In its portfolio are such diverse companies as United Kingdom-based Air Europe; Checkrobot Inc., a U.S. company that makes supermarket checkout machines; Norment Industries, a U.S. manufacturer of securities systems; Com Systems Inc., a U.S. regional telephone company; and major real-estate projects in the U.S. and Europe. 
05/wsj_0564:For financial analysts, reading Omni's accounts is a tough challenge. "Companies move in and out," says Helga Kern of KK Swiss Investment. 
05/wsj_0564:Financial analysts note that Mr. Rey is attracted to companies that are undervalued on the basis of their real-estate interests.
05/wsj_0564:In August, Omni unexpectedly bought Inspectorate's 80% stake in Harpener AG of West Germany, a land-rich company.
05/wsj_0564:The internal transaction within the Rey empire puzzled Harpener's small shareholders, but analysts say it makes sense for Inspectorate-Adia to focus on its main businesses of product inspection and temporary help. 
05/wsj_0564:Mr. Rey says the move is yet another example of his conservatism.
