05/wsj_0589:Members of the audience gasped or laughed nervously; their industry has been unsettled recently by acquisitions.
05/wsj_0589:That acquisition, to be completed by year end, will include the Cover Girl and Clarion makeup lines, making P&G the top marketer of cosmetics in mass-market outlets. 
05/wsj_0589:It's not so much the idea of acquisitions that has agitated the cosmetics industry as the companies doing the acquiring: P&G and Unilever bring with them great experience with mundane products like soap and toilet paper, sparking disdain in the glitzy cosmetics trade; but they also bring mammoth marketing clout, sparking fear.
05/wsj_0589:But industry watchers expect them to blend the methodical marketing strategies they use for more mundane products with the more intuitive approach typical of cosmetics companies.
05/wsj_0589:Estee Lauder Inc., Revlon Inc. and other cosmetics houses traditionally have considered themselves fashion enterprises whose product development is guided by the creative intuition of their executives.
05/wsj_0589:"Just because upscale cosmetics look like packaged goods and smell like packaged goods, it doesn't mean they are packaged goods," says Leonard Lauder, chief executive of Estee Lauder. "They're really fashion items wrapped up in little jars." 
05/wsj_0589:In contrast to the more artistic nature of traditional cosmetics houses, Unilever and P&G are the habitats of organization men in gray-flannel suits.
05/wsj_0589:P&G already has shown it can meld some traditional packaged-goods techniques with the image-making of the cosmetics trade in the mass-market end of the business.
05/wsj_0589:Consider Oil of Olay, which P&G acquired as part of Richardson-Vicks International in 1985.
05/wsj_0589:The moisturizer, introduced in 1962, had a dowdy image. "Oil of Olay brought with it the baggage of being used basically by older women who had already aged," says David Williams, a consultant with New England Consulting Group. 
05/wsj_0589:It also redesigned Oil of Olay's packaging, stamping the traditional pink boxes with gold lines to create a more opulent look.
05/wsj_0589:Next year, Noxell plans to roll out a perfume called Navy, says George L. Bunting Jr., chairman of Noxell.
05/wsj_0589:The presence of Unilever and P&G is likely to increase the impact of advertising on cosmetics.
05/wsj_0589:While the two are among the world's biggest advertisers, most makers of upscale cosmetics spend relatively little on national ads.
05/wsj_0589:Estee Lauder, for example, spends only an estimated 5% of sales on advertising in the U.S., and Mr. Lauder says he has no plans to change his strategy. 
05/wsj_0589:Nearly 70% of cosmetics sales come through mass-distribution outlets such as drug stores and supermarkets, according to Andrew Shore, an analyst at Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
05/wsj_0589:This fall, for example, L'Oreal Group, ordinarily a high-end line, rolled out a drug-store line of skin-care products called Plenitude, which retail for $5 to $15. 
05/wsj_0589:The packaged-goods marketers may try filling that gap with a spate of new products.
05/wsj_0589:Sales of its Tide detergent soared earlier this year, for example, after P&G introduced a version that includes a bleach safe for all colors and fabrics. 
05/wsj_0589:That's led industry executives to speculate that future product development will be driven more by technological innovation than by fashion whims -- especially among mass-market brands. "There will be more emphasis on quality," says Guy Peyrelongue, chief executive of Cosmair Inc., the U.S. licensee of L'Oreal. "You'll see fewer gimmicks." 
05/wsj_0589:The ritzy world of department-store cosmetics retailing, where Unilever is concentrating its efforts, may prove even more treacherous.
05/wsj_0589:Because brand loyalty is weak and most cosmetics purchases are unplanned, careful training of store sales staffs by cosmetics companies is important.
05/wsj_0590:There may be a truce in the long war of nerves between the White House and Congress over how this country conducts secret intelligence operations abroad. 
05/wsj_0590:After years of mistrust born of Watergate, past misdeeds of the Central Intelligence Agency, and the Iran-Contra scandal, President Bush and the Senate Intelligence Committee appear ready -- for now, at least -- to trust each other when it comes to setting policy on covert activities.
05/wsj_0590:If that attitude lasts, it could infuse covert action planning with a level of care and confidence that hasn't been seen in years. 
05/wsj_0590:Over the past week, the president has agreed to keep the committee informed, usually in advance, of covert actions and to put key intelligence decisions in writing.
05/wsj_0590:Despite objections by the CIA, Mr. Bush also has agreed to the establishment of an inspector general at the CIA who would be independent of the CIA director. 
05/wsj_0590:In return, the Senate panel has dropped efforts to enact legislation requiring the administration to inform it within 48 hours of the launching of any covert activity.
05/wsj_0590:It also has removed a ban on CIA use of a contingency fund for covert acts and has agreed to wipe away some tortured and legalistic restrictions on coup planning put in place to ensure that the CIA didn't get back in the assassination game. 
05/wsj_0590:The new understanding didn't just spring to life in a spontaneous eruption of sweetness and light.
05/wsj_0590:It emerged after a rancorous display of old-style intelligence politics that followed this month's failed coup attempt in Panama. 
05/wsj_0590:Mr. Bush even disclosed privately that one Reagan-era deal with Congress required him to notify the odious Panamanian dictator, Manuel Noriega, if the U.S. learned of a coup plot that might endanger his life.
05/wsj_0590:Intelligence Committee Chairman David Boren (D., Okla.) and Vice Chairman William Cohen (R., Maine), for their part, angrily accused the White House of selectively leaking classified documents and trying unfairly to shift the blame to Congress for the bungled attempt to topple Gen. Noriega. 
05/wsj_0590:The White House got the better of the exchange but took care not to press its advantage to the kind of constitutional confrontation sought by conservative Republicans who don't want any congressional oversight of intelligence activities.
05/wsj_0590:Sen. Boren happily told reporters that there had been "a meeting of the minds" with the White House, and that the committee had given Mr. Bush "a clean slate," free of the impediments imposed during the Reagan years.
05/wsj_0590:And a pending Justice Department interpretation of the assassination ban could raise questions that would have to be settled. 
05/wsj_0590:Some conservatives will accuse the president of promising Congress too much.
05/wsj_0590:Boren and Cohen of wimping out, and they will warn that the lawmakers' concessions raise the specter of more internationally embarrassing covert operations like the mining of Nicaraguan harbors and the Iran arms sales. 
05/wsj_0591:Several of the New York Stock Exchange's own listed companies, led by giant Contel Corp., are joining for the first time to complain about program trading and the exchange's role in it. 
05/wsj_0591:The group will complain to Washington, to the heads of program-trading firms and to the heads of the Big Board itself, he said. 
05/wsj_0591:"They should call {the exchange} Trump East," charged Mr. Wohlstetter, the 79-year-old founder of Contel who's also a former investment banker and stock trader. "What is the mission of the financial community -- to help some scavengers or schemers, or help corporate America?" Contel is a $6 billion telephone and electronics company. 
05/wsj_0591:The market's Friday-the-13th plunge of 190 points in the Dow Jones Industrial Average, and the Big Board's understated response to it, galvanized some longstanding dissatisfaction among companies listed on the exchange.
05/wsj_0591:Last month, program trading accounted for a record 13.8% of average daily Big Board volume. 
05/wsj_0591:The focus of the outcry has been stock-index arbitrage, which accounts for about half the program trading that goes on.
05/wsj_0591:Privately, exchange officials worry that without a hospitable system for program trading at the Big Board, billions of dollars in trading will simply migrate to overseas exchanges such as London's.
05/wsj_0591:One intended customer of the new basket product is index arbitragers, according to the exchange. 
05/wsj_0591:The Big Board can't ban stock-index futures, of course, but it could ban use of its high-speed electronic trading system for program trading or at least encourage securities firms to back off.
05/wsj_0591:The exchange put a bit of a damper on program trading when, last year, it simply started to publish monthly statistics of each firm's program-trading volume. 
05/wsj_0591:Contel's Mr. Wohlstetter said the group of Big Board companies isn't ready to go public yet with its effort, and that he doesn't plan to be the leader once it is public.
05/wsj_0591:Among those Mr. Wohlstetter said he has been talking to are Sanford Weill of Primerica Corp., which is the parent of Smith Barney, Harris Upham & Co.; GTE Corp. 's James Johnson, and ITT Corp. 's Rand Araskog. 
05/wsj_0591:None of these chief executives were available for comment. 
05/wsj_0591:Among the targets of the Big Board companies' campaign will be some corporate pension funds that use program-trading strategies to maximize returns on their investments.
05/wsj_0591:For Contel's part, the company a month ago informed each of its money managers that it would drop them if they give business to program-trading firms. 
05/wsj_0591:It was just those kinds of ultimatums that last week succeeded in turning up the heat in the debate.
05/wsj_0591:All of the firms except Kidder, which is the second-biggest program trader on Wall Street, quickly announced pull-backs from index arbitrage. 
05/wsj_0591:Kidder officials stand by their aggressive use of program trading.
05/wsj_0591:Chief Executive Officer Michael Carpenter said that despite the outcry even by some of Kidder's own brokers, he believes index arbitrage doesn't have a "negative impact on the market as a whole." However, pressure on Kidder's parent, GE, could change Kidder's policy.
05/wsj_0592:As the air clears from last week's storm of resignations and reshufflings, the government faces a daunting job of rebuilding confidence in its policies.
05/wsj_0592:The prime minister and her new chancellor of the exchequer, the untested John Major, need to haul the country through something like a recession to bring down inflation and set the economy moving again.
05/wsj_0592:It sounds like the work of a decade, but the deadline is late 1991, when Mrs. Thatcher is expected to call another national election.
05/wsj_0592:What's worrying her supporters is that the economic cycle may be out of kilter with the political timetable.
05/wsj_0592:Though Mrs. Thatcher has pulled through other crises, supporters wonder if her steely, autocratic ways are the right formula today. "There's a rising fear that perhaps Mrs. Thatcher's style of management has become a political liability," says Bill Martin, senior economist at London brokers UBS-Phillips & Drew. 
05/wsj_0592:The prime minister's insistence on keeping a private coterie of advisers -- including an economic guru who openly criticized former Chancellor of the Exchequer Nigel Lawson -- confused the financial community.
