06/wsj_0676:(During its centennial year, The Wall Street Journal will report events of the past century that stand as milestones of American business history.) 
06/wsj_0676:Thomas Jefferson sold Congress on the idea of the decimal system for currency, thus saving Americans the headaches of pounds, shillings and pence.
06/wsj_0676:But he struck out with the decimal system of metric weights and measures the French had invented.
06/wsj_0676:In 1807, the Swiss mathematician who headed the U.S. Coast and Geodetic Survey made an "iron meter" that he had brought from Europe the standard of measure.
06/wsj_0676:By the end of the century scientists had embraced the system. 
06/wsj_0676:Today, though the public is barely aware, much of U.S. industry, particularly companies manufacturing or selling overseas, have made metrics routine.
