07/wsj_0700:But securities regulators now say privately that it isn't likely to start until the first quarter of next year. 
07/wsj_0700:Analysts and financial officials in the British colony consider the new contract essential to the revival of the Hong Kong Futures Exchange, which has never fully recovered from the October 1987 crash.
07/wsj_0700:It is almost a carbon copy of the Chicago Mercantile Exchange's Eurodollar contract, which is based on the three-month Eurodollar rate, the rate paid on U.S.-dollar deposits in London banks. 
07/wsj_0700:If the contract is as successful as some expect, it may do much to restore confidence in futures trading in Hong Kong. "The contract is definitely important to the exchange," says Robert Gilmore, executive director of the Securities and Futures Commission. 
07/wsj_0700:Two years ago, the futures exchange was the envy of other would-be futures centers.
07/wsj_0700:In the case of stock-index and interest-rate futures, the instruments are given an underlying cash value and are settled in cash.} 
07/wsj_0700:Volume for the entire month of September totaled only 21,687 contracts, compared with a daily average of 27,000 in the month before the 1987 crash. 
07/wsj_0700:Despite the thin trading, and after two painful years of restructuring, the futures market has shown itself to be resilient in two recent tests.
07/wsj_0700:"There was no problem at all," says Douglas Ford, chief executive officer of the futures exchange. 
07/wsj_0700:Most important to the contract's success is the commitment of Hong Kong's big financial institutions, especially the two leaders, Hongkong & Shanghai Banking Corp. and the local subsidiary of Britain's Standard Chartered Bank PLC.
07/wsj_0700:"If those two banks are there, then the balance of the banking institutions will be there," says Mr. Gilmore, the Securities and Futures Commission official. 
07/wsj_0700:Colony banks have a major stake in how interest rates move because of their enormous Hong Kong-dollar exposure.
07/wsj_0700:Even though the currency is pegged to the U.S. dollar, with a fixed exchange rate of HK$7.8 to the American currency, the U.S. and Hong Kong economies don't always move in lock step, making it difficult to predict where interest rates in the colony will go. 
07/wsj_0700:The Hibor contract "solves quite a bit of the problem of interest-rate risk in the interbank market," says Eric Cheng, a director of James Capel (Far East) Ltd., the Hong Kong arm of the British brokerage firm. 
07/wsj_0700:Companies and financial institutions familiar with Hong Kong remain wary of trading in its futures market. 
07/wsj_0700:Exchange officials also point out that Hibor futures were designed for institutions and corporations, not for the type of small individual investors who were very active in Hang Seng index futures and defaulted in the 1987 crash.
07/wsj_0700:Mr. Cheng says the low margin required for trading futures attracted a lot of small investors before the 1987 crash who didn't realize that their risk was virtually unlimited. 
07/wsj_0700:But many bankers remain nervous, especially as the start-up of the contract continues to be delayed. 
