07/wsj_0728:Contrary to what might be expected based on the headline on John R. Dorfman's recent Money Matters article ("Pros Hit Theorists Right Where It Hurts" Oct. 3), I was able to stand proudly before my undergraduate finance students and proclaim that the findings of your yearlong experiment on stock picking is completely consistent with what they have been taught in the classroom.
07/wsj_0728:In particular, I do not find the fact that your group of pros' monthly selections of four stocks outperforms the market in general to be inconsistent with market efficiency. 
07/wsj_0728:Accepted theories of asset pricing offer a perfectly legitimate explanation.
07/wsj_0728:If you asked me to select a stock with the highest expected return, I would select a stock with the greatest amount of undiversifiable risk, as I am sure your pros do.
07/wsj_0728:A four-stock portfolio is still exposed to a great deal of unnecessary risk.
07/wsj_0728:Mr. Dorfman provides confirming evidence of this phenomenon when he reports that your staff of dart throwers would have accumulated only $112,383 by randomly selecting four new stocks to be held in a portfolio each month. 
07/wsj_0728:The fact that stock pickers have bested a randomly selected portfolio in eight of 12 months has no bearing on the efficient-market theory. 
