07/wsj_0779:The stock market correction of Oct. 13, 1989, was a grim reminder of the Oct. 19, 1987 market collapse.
07/wsj_0779:The situation was like that of a skier who is thrown slightly off balance by an unexpected bump on the slope.
07/wsj_0779:His skis spread farther and farther apart -- just as buy-sell spreads widen during a financial panic -- and soon he is out of control.
07/wsj_0779:After the 1987 crash, and as a result of the recommendations of many studies, "circuit breakers" were devised to allow market participants to regroup and restore orderly market conditions.
07/wsj_0779:Instead, an appropriate institution should be charged with the job of preventing chaos in the market: the Federal Reserve.
07/wsj_0779:The availability of timely assistance -- of a backstop -- can help markets retain their resilience.
07/wsj_0779:The stock market is the only major market without a market-maker of unchallenged liquidity or a buyer of last resort. 
07/wsj_0779:Instead of flooding the entire economy with liquidity, and thereby increasing the danger of inflation, the Fed could support the stock market directly by buying market averages in the futures market, thus stabilizing the market as a whole. 
07/wsj_0779:The combined value of daily equity trading on the New York Exchange, the American Stock Exchange and the NASDAQ over-the-counter market ranges between $7 billion and $10 billion.
07/wsj_0779:And taking more direct action has the advantage of avoiding sharp increases in the money supply, such as happened in October 1987. 
07/wsj_0779:It should seek only to maintain the functioning of markets -- not to prop up the Dow Jones or New York Stock Exchange averages at a particular level.
07/wsj_0779:The Fed would eliminate the cause of the potential panic rather than attempting to treat the symptom -- the liquidity of the banks. 
07/wsj_0779:But since the member countries of the International Monetary Fund agreed to the "Guidelines to Floating" in 1974, such difficulties have been avoided.
07/wsj_0779:Thus, the mere existence of a market-stabilizing agency helps to avoid panic in emergencies. 
07/wsj_0779:Mr. Heller, now at VISA International, was a governor of the Federal Reserve Board from 1986 until earlier this year.
