07/wsj_0794:This is slightly adapted from remarks Oct. 7 by former Secretary of State George P. Shultz to an alumni gathering at the Stanford Business School, where he has returned to the faculty: 
07/wsj_0794:I was struck a couple of years ago by the drug-interdiction effort in the Bahamas.
07/wsj_0794:We had intercepted during the year an estimated $5 billion street value of cocaine.
07/wsj_0794:The GNP of the Bahamas is probably somewhere between one and two billion dollars.
07/wsj_0794:So you get an idea of the leverage there and elsewhere that our market for drugs has brought about. 
07/wsj_0794:The efforts to get to the people who are addicted, try to rehabilitate them; if they cannot be rehabilitated, at least to contain them; to educate people, to strongly discourage use of drugs by people who are casual users and first users, to stop this process among the young -- all of these things I think are extremely important. 
07/wsj_0794:But, I have to tell you that it seems to me that the conceptual base of the current program is flawed and the program is not likely to work.
07/wsj_0794:The conceptual base -- a criminal-justice approach -- is the same that I have worked through before, in the Nixon administration when I was budget director and secretary of the treasury with jurisdiction over the Customs.
07/wsj_0794:You're looking at a guy whose motorcade was attacked in Bolivia by the drug terrorists, so I'm personally a veteran of this war. 
07/wsj_0794:What we have before us now is essentially the same program but with more resources plowed into all of the efforts to enforce and control.
07/wsj_0794:It seems to me we're not really going to get anywhere until we can take the criminality out of the drug business and the incentives for criminality out of it.
07/wsj_0794:Frankly, the only way I can think of to accomplish this is to make it possible for addicts to buy drugs at some regulated place at a price that approximates their cost.
07/wsj_0794:If I am catching your attention, then read a bold and informative article in this September's issue of Science by Ethan Nadelmann on this subject.
07/wsj_0794:We need at least to consider and examine forms of controlled legalization of drugs. 
07/wsj_0794:But I feel that if somebody doesn't get up and start talking about this now, the next time around, when we have the next iteration of these programs, it will still be true that everyone is scared to talk about it.
07/wsj_0795:Personal spending, buoyed by a burst of automobile buying, was the main catalyst to the economy's expansion.
07/wsj_0795:But trade, one of the economy's main forces in the past few years, showed a sharp deterioration.
07/wsj_0795:Imports of goods and services soared, while exports were flat. 
07/wsj_0795:Although the economy showed no change of pace from the second quarter, many analysts expect it to slow considerably in the fourth quarter as demand for autos falls, partly because of higher prices on models introduced last month.
07/wsj_0795:Many economists think the rise in the value of the U.S. dollar this year will further crimp progress in trade, because it makes exports more expensive and imports cheaper.
07/wsj_0795:A sharp reduction in inflation was by far the brightest spot in the report on the real gross national product -- the inflation-adjusted market value of all the goods and services the economy produced. 
07/wsj_0795:An inflation gauge that measures the quarterly change in prices of an array of goods and services slowed its growth to a 2.9% annual rate in the third quarter from 5% in the second. 
07/wsj_0795:Much of the moderation came from declining energy prices, which have since turned up a bit, analysts said.
07/wsj_0795:Consequently, Michael Darby, undersecretary for economic affairs at the Commerce Department, said inflation probably will edge up from the third-quarter rate in the final three months of 1989.
07/wsj_0795:Generally, the Bush administration expressed satisfaction with the economy's progress as it heads into its eighth year of sustained growth next month. 
07/wsj_0795:But administration officials were concerned over the bleak trade report, which showed the deficit in the country's trade of goods and services swelling to a $74 billion annual rate in the third quarter from a $51 billion rate in the second quarter.
07/wsj_0795:"We were unprepared for the deterioration in net exports," said Daniel Van Dyke, vice president of U.S. forecasting at Bank of America in San Francisco. "I can't believe it will continue," he added, noting that the economies of the country's major trading partners are strong and prices of U.S. products are still competitive. 
07/wsj_0795:Some analysts also were disturbed by a pickup in the growth of business inventories.
07/wsj_0795:While a buildup of these stocks adds to GNP, it can hurt the economy because a pileup of unsold goods can lead to production cuts and layoffs. 
07/wsj_0795:According to the report, inventories outside the farm sector grew at an annual rate of $24.6 billion in the third quarter, up from a $19.5 billion pace in the second quarter.
