08/wsj_0800:The growing crowd of Japanese investors buying up foreign companies aren't all strait-laced businessmen in dark suits. 
08/wsj_0800:In Japan, he's known in racy weekly magazines as the "King of Shady Money." If nothing else, the 57-year-old's past has its share of dents. 
08/wsj_0800:Nearly 20 years ago, Mr. Morishita, founder and chairman of Aichi Corp., a finance company, received a 10-month suspended sentence from a Tokyo court for violating a money-lending law and an income tax law.
08/wsj_0800:He was convicted of charging interest rates much higher than what the law permitted, and attempting to evade income taxes by using a double accounting system. 
08/wsj_0800:He was arrested, though not indicted, on at least three other occasions in the '60s and '70s: for assault and unlawful confinement, for fraud and forgery of private documents, and for extortion. 
08/wsj_0800:Many of these financiers lend freely, often without demanding collateral.
08/wsj_0800:Aichi is a machikin, Mr. Utsunomiya says, and "one of the nasty ones." In describing that business in general, he says that when the client can't repay the loan, some machikin "clutch on like hyenas" and even take over the client's company.
