08/wsj_0800:In 30 years of collecting impressionist and Japanese paintings, he has acquired 600 items, he says, enough to persuade him to start a museum next year.
08/wsj_0800:The Asahi Shimbun, a Japanese daily, last month reported that Aichi revised its tax calculations after being challenged for allegedly failing to report all of its income to tax authorities over a two-year period.
08/wsj_0800:The Tokyo Regional Taxation Office declines to comment, and Mr. Kori, the tycoon's secretary, says the problem simply resulted from a difference of opinion over what was considered income. 
08/wsj_0800:The small, wiry Mr. Morishita comes across as an outspoken man of the world.
08/wsj_0800:Not many people know the details of Mr. Morishita's business, but it's a source of rumors about shady dealings.
08/wsj_0800:The seventh child of a store owner in Aichi prefecture, Mr. Morishita started out in the textile business.
08/wsj_0800:He spends most weekends flying his helicopter to one of his nine courses, he says, two of which were designed by Jack Nicklaus.
08/wsj_0800:Even in Denenchofu, one of Tokyo's richest neighborhoods, Mr. Morishita's splashy brick manor -- one of some 10 houses he owns -- outshines the neighbors'.
