09/wsj_0909:Surviving scandal has become a rite of political passage at a time when a glut of scandal has blunted this town's sensibility.
09/wsj_0909:Let the president demand strict new ethics rules: With four sitting House members accused of sexual misdeeds, amid the unfolding HUD scandal and after the Wright debacle, "people are slightly dulled by scandal," says political humorist Art Buchwald. "It now takes something really weird to inspire public outrage." 
09/wsj_0909:But many have. "These people bounce back more resiliently than regular people," says Washington writer Suzanne Garment, who is working on a history of post-Watergate scandal. 
09/wsj_0909:Given their own penchant for book writing, it is surprising that none of the masters of scandal survival have yet published a guide to the art.
09/wsj_0909:As if he were still in his old job, Mr. Wright, by resigning with his title instead of being forced from his job, by law enjoys a $120,000 annual office expense allowance, three paid staffers, up to $67,000 for stationery and telephones and continued use of the franking privilege.
09/wsj_0909:There is also a busy schedule of speaking engagements at $10,000 a pop, at tony places including the Yale Political Union. 
09/wsj_0909:On the edge of fashionable Georgetown, in a chic office with a river view and a number of corporate clients whom he won't name, Mr. Deaver is trying to reclaim his reputation as one of the savviest image makers in town. 
09/wsj_0909:There are few mementos of his days as White House deputy chief of staff and confidant of Ronald and Nancy Reagan.
09/wsj_0909:The former $3 million-a-year lobbyist now frequents shelters for the homeless and devotes a third of his time counseling other recovering alcoholics. "I feel better than I ever have in my life," he says. 
09/wsj_0909:One sign of Mr. Deaver's renaissance: an appearance on ABC's "Nightline" for a show on pack journalism.
09/wsj_0909:Host Ted Koppel introduced him as "the media master of the Reagan Administration," with nary a mention of Mr. Deaver's conviction in 1987 on perjury charges. 
09/wsj_0909:He is now in solo law practice in Washington, but his fees have been meager and he failed in efforts to win a chunk of his ex-wife's royalties on her tell-all book.
