09/wsj_0932:The amount of blood surgical patients can donate and store before surgery can be increased by the new genetically engineered drug, EPO. 
09/wsj_0932:EPO, or erythropoietin, is a protein the human body makes to stimulate the growth of red blood cells.
09/wsj_0932:A genetically engineered version of the human protein developed by Amgen Corp. of Thousand Oaks, Calif., recently has been marketed by the Ortho Pharmaceuticals division of Johnson & Johnson.
09/wsj_0932:A competing version of EPO is being developed by Genetics Institute Inc. in Cambridge, Mass.
09/wsj_0932:A new experiment, reported in this week's New England Journal of Medicine, involved giving injections of Amgen's EPO to 23 patients who wanted to store units of their own blood. 
09/wsj_0932:If tests indicated a low number of red cells, blood wasn't taken. 
09/wsj_0932:The EPO-treated patients donated an average of 5.4 units of blood each compared with only 4.1 units donated by a similar group of surgical patients who received a placebo injection.
09/wsj_0932:The volume of red cells donated by the EPO-treated patients was 41% higher per donor, the research team representing a number of hospitals and blood banks reported. 
09/wsj_0933:(During its centennial year, The Wall Street Journal will report events of the past century that stand as milestones of American business history.) 
09/wsj_0933:In 1972, then Treasury Secretary George Shultz, with the key support of Sen. Carl Curtis, sought some form of pensions for the uncovered.
09/wsj_0933:That year a four-man group headed by William Lieber in the Legislation and Regulations division of the Office of the Chief Counsel for the Internal Revenue Service, was assigned the task of designing a plan. 
09/wsj_0933:This caused an explosion of IRA promotions by brokers, banks, mutual funds and others.
09/wsj_0933:But in 1986 Congress sharply reduced the number of people who could qualify for its benefits and IRA tax-deductions slowed their roaring growth. 
09/wsj_0934:The Soviet State Bank announced a 90% devaluation of the ruble against the dollar for private transactions, in an apparent attempt to curb the nation's rapidly growing black market for hard currency. 
09/wsj_0934:Commercial transactions will continue to be based on the official rate of about 0.63 rubles to the dollar.
09/wsj_0934:The current ruble rate has long been out of line with the black market.
09/wsj_0934:Even at such rates, black marketeers have been able to make big profits because of the dire shortage of consumer goods here.
09/wsj_0934:Even a pack of 20 Western cigarettes can fetch 20 rubles or more.
09/wsj_0934:Moscow has already tacitly admitted that the ruble isn't worth much, announcing in August that it will pay Soviet farmers in hard currency for grain and other produce that they grow in excess of state-plan quotas. 
09/wsj_0934:"The absurdity of the official rate should seem obvious to everyone," the afternoon newspaper Izvestia wrote in a brief commentary on the devaluation. 
09/wsj_0934:The State Bank's move is part of a drive to iron out exchange-rate discrepancies as Moscow moves toward making the ruble convertible -- a goal that Soviet bankers and economists say is still far away.
09/wsj_0934:Rumors of an impending devaluation have been circulating in Moscow for weeks, but the size of the cut took many Western bankers by surprise. "It's much bigger than we expected," said one German banker, who asked not to be named. 
09/wsj_0934:The next step, which could have a larger effect on businesses, will come early next month, when the Bank for Foreign Economic Affairs is to hold its first auction of foreign currency.
09/wsj_0934:Plans for the auction, which was supposed to take place last spring and become a regular event, have been thwarted by a lack of hard currency.
09/wsj_0934:The Kremlin also has been unwilling to provide hard currency for the auction, using a lot of it instead to finance emergency imports of consumer goods. 
09/wsj_0934:If foreign tourists and businesses could sell their currencies freely at the new, better exchange rate, that would enable the State Bank to increase its dollar reserves and would mop up some of the excess rubles in the economy at the same time.
