10/wsj_1017:The 231-191 roll call illustrates the limits of power a resurgent abortion-rights movement still faces.
10/wsj_1017:It continues to gain strength in the chamber but remains far short of the two-thirds majority required to prevail over Mr. Bush. 
10/wsj_1017:Democrats voted to override by a 3-1 margin, but Republicans were equally firm in support of the president, who has threatened to make abortion a decisive issue on at least three separate fiscal 1990 spending bills. 
10/wsj_1017:Yesterday's vote dealt with the largest of these bills, an estimated $156.7 billion measure funding the departments of Labor, Education, and Health and Human Services.
10/wsj_1017:The package is more than $1 billion above the recommendations of Budget Director Richard Darman this week.
10/wsj_1017:But given the political importance of California, the administration was content to use its influence to prevent any Senate amendments adding further new appropriations.
10/wsj_1017:The $2.85 billion measure comes on top of $1.1 billion appropriated after Hugo struck the Carolinas and Caribbean last month, and these totals don't reflect the additional benefit of low-interest disaster loans. 
10/wsj_1017:In the Senate, Majority Whip Alan Cranston used his position to win not only the expanded credit but also more generous treatment than the House had permitted in the distribution of highway funds in the next six months.
10/wsj_1017:The emergency assistance wouldn't be counted against a state's normal allocation of annual highway funds, and the bill circumvents existing restrictions that otherwise would prevent the use of federal aid to repair a toll road, such as the San Francisco-Oakland Bay Bridge damaged in last week's earthquake. 
10/wsj_1017:The standoff over abortion is certain to contribute to further delays and, apart from the health and education measure vetoed by Mr. Bush, bills funding the District of Columbia and the entire U.S. foreign-aid budget are in jeopardy because of related abortion or family-planning issues. 
10/wsj_1017:At a recent White House meeting, Rep. Silvio Conte (R., Mass.), the ranking minority member of the House Appropriations Committee, argued with his friend Mr. Bush against a veto, and though Mr. Conte and Minority Leader Robert Michel of Illinois stood with the president yesterday, they are plainly uncomfortable with his position. 
10/wsj_1017:But after years of using the issue for its benefit, the GOP finds its candidates on the defensive.
10/wsj_1017:In an extraordinary mix of cultures and church-state powers, Rep. Robert Dornan (R., Calif.) lectured his fellow Roman Catholics -- including Mr. Florio -- for having the "chutzpah" to disagree with the hierarchy of their church on abortion.
10/wsj_1017:Rep. Les AuCoin was as blunt on behalf of the abortion-rights movement. "This may not make George Bush a one-term president," said the Oregon liberal, addressing the Republican side of the House. "But if you support him over rape victims, this may be your last term." 
