10/wsj_1019:The Big Board this morning plans to begin trading its Exchange Stock Portfolio "basket" product, the first program-trading vehicle carrying the exchange's seal of approval.
10/wsj_1019:ESPs will allow institutional investors to buy or sell all 500 stocks in Standard & Poor's index in a single trade of a minimum of $5 million. "Customized" baskets of fewer stocks will also be available. 
10/wsj_1019:The basket products are "an evolutionary step" in solving problems in trading big blocks of stock that came to light in the 1987 market crash, said SEC Commissioner Joseph Grundfest. 
10/wsj_1019:The Big Board argues that its new product will help rather than hurt the situation by possibly drawing business from more-volatile forms of program trading. 
10/wsj_1019:ESPs are also an attempt by the Big Board to head off the exodus of program trading business to overseas markets such as London.
10/wsj_1019:Already, many of the Big Board's own floor traders are warning that the ESP baskets are risky and not in the best interests of the investing public.
10/wsj_1019:The 400-member Alliance of Floor Brokers said the new product, with the $5 million minimum, will benefit only big institutional investors and could lead to "wild spasms of volatility." 
10/wsj_1019:Stockbrokers who cater to individual investors said the Big Board's new product confirms the exchange doesn't want to curtail program trading, which last month accounted for a record 13.8% of the exchange's average daily volume. 
10/wsj_1019:"The New York Stock Exchange is losing its cool here," said James Andrews, head of institutional trading at Janney Montgomery Scott Inc. in Philadelphia.
10/wsj_1019:And it's going to be done more frequently as the result of having more access to it at different places." 
