10/wsj_1057:CBS will add 25 1/2 hours to that load in 1992, and ratings could be hurt by a lack of live events.
10/wsj_1057:All prime-time fare will be on tape-delay because of time differences with Norway, so the results can be announced on the 6 o'clock news. (Turner Broadcasting will pay CBS $25 million to air 50 hours of CBS coverage plus 50 hours of additional events.) 
10/wsj_1057:Moreover, sports has "claimed its place" as a guaranteed ratings-getter, says David J. Stern, the commissioner of the National Basketball Association. "This isn't outlandish bidding; this is a situation of very careful businessmen making judgments about the worth of product and acting on it. . . . I would tend to trust their judgment." 
10/wsj_1057:Although sports officials predict jumps of 50% to 100% in the major contracts coming up for renewal, ad rates may rise only 20%.
10/wsj_1057:CBS hopes to save money by ordering fewer episodes of regular series because sports will fill up a few weeks of prime time.
10/wsj_1057:Each hour of Olympics and baseball in prime time will cost CBS $2.6 million to $2.8 million; an hour-long drama costs only $900,000, and it is aired twice. 
10/wsj_1057:But media-stock analyst Richard J. MacDonald of MacDonald Grippo Riely says Wall Street won't take kindly to that. "On a stand-alone basis, the network ought to make money," he says. 
10/wsj_1058:Eavesdropping -- both corporate and private -- is on the rise, thanks to the proliferation of surveillance technologies.
10/wsj_1058:And while sellers of the equipment and companies "monitoring" employees have few qualms, right-to-privacy advocates and some lawmakers are alarmed. 
10/wsj_1058:"New technologies are changing the way we deal with each other and the way we work," says Janlori Goldman, a staff attorney at the American Civil Liberties Union. "Our expectation of confidentiality is being eroded." 
10/wsj_1058:The Communications Workers of America, which opposes such monitoring, says supervisors listen in on an estimated 400 million calls each year.
10/wsj_1058:Among companies saying they monitor employees are United Airlines, American Airlines, United Parcel Service, Nynex Corp., Spiegel Inc., and the circulation department of this newspaper.
10/wsj_1058:Businesses "want to verify information and ensure accuracy," says John Hiltunen, Dictaphone's manager of media relations.
10/wsj_1058:The state of Alaska recently bought the Veritrac system, he says, "to monitor the Exxon cleanup effort." 
10/wsj_1058:Shearson says it has taped some of its institutional trading desks, such as commodities and futures, for about four years.
10/wsj_1058:The most common use of spying devices is in divorce cases, say private investigators.
10/wsj_1058:Concerned with the increased availability of surveillance technology and heavier use of it, lawmakers have proposed laws addressing the issue.
10/wsj_1058:Nine states have introduced bills requiring that workers and customers be made aware of monitoring.
10/wsj_1058:"I'm sympathetic with workers who feel under the gun," says Richard Barton of the Direct Marketing Association of America, which is lobbying strenuously against the Edwards beeper bill. "But the only way you can find out how your people are doing is by listening." The powerful group, which represents many of the nation's telemarketers, was instrumental in derailing the 1987 bill. 
10/wsj_1058:Laura Dale, center manager at the catalog company's customer order center in Reno, Nev., defends monitoring. "We like to follow up and make sure operators are achieving our standards of company service," says Ms. Dale, who supervises 350 operators. 
10/wsj_1058:Federal wiretap statutes recognize the right of employers to monitor employees' for evaluation purposes.
10/wsj_1058:But opponents, led by the CWA, say new laws are needed because monitoring is heavily concentrated in service industries and 81% of monitored workers aren't represented by unions.
10/wsj_1058:"Nine to Five," a Cleveland-based office workers organization that supports the beeper bill, six months ago started a privacy hot line to receive reports of alleged monitoring abuses. 
10/wsj_1058:Meanwhile, supporters of the Dellums two-party consent bill say it is needed because of a giant loophole in the one-party consent law.
10/wsj_1058:Currently, if the person taping is a party to the conversation, it's all right to record without the knowledge of the other person on the line. (Intercepting other people's private conversations is illegal and punishable by five years in prison and fines of $10,000.) 
10/wsj_1058:Some marketers of surveillance gear -- including Communication Control System Ltd., which owns the Counter Spy Shop and others like it -- already put warning labels in their catalogs informing customers of the one-party law.
10/wsj_1058:Radio Shack says it has a policy against selling products if a salesperson suspects they will be used illegally. "Everything sold at Radio Shack has a legal purpose," says Bernard Appel, president of the Tandy Corp. subsidiary.
10/wsj_1058:Still, Radio Shack is aware that some of its products are controversial.
