11/wsj_1105:The results underscore Sears's difficulties in implementing the "everyday low pricing" strategy that it adopted in March as part of a broad attempt to revive its retailing business.
11/wsj_1105:Sears officials insist they don't intend to abandon the everyday pricing approach in the face of the poor results.
11/wsj_1105:Instead, a spokesman blames the dismal third-quarter showing on "an environment that is being distorted by a very harsh climate for sales of durable goods," which account for roughly two-thirds of Sears's annual merchandise volume. 
11/wsj_1105:Sears has been counting on growth coming from the large displays of brand-name merchandise it is adding to its stores over the next two years in what it calls "power formats." 
11/wsj_1105:But analysts say Sears faces an especially daunting challenge on the eve of the Christmas shopping season. "I believe everyday pricing in the current environment doesn't work," says Walter Loeb of Morgan Stanley & Co., pointing to soft durable-goods sales. "Sears is likely to be unsuccessful if it continues with its pricing policy when everyone else is offering unusual values." 
11/wsj_1105:Recent surveys by Leo J. Shapiro & Associates, a market research firm in Chicago, suggest that Sears is having a tough time attracting shoppers because it hasn't yet done enough to improve service or its selection of merchandise.
11/wsj_1105:The number of people who said they were more likely to shop at Sears fell in September to 37% from 66% in March, when Sears blanketed the airwaves with ads about its new pricing strategy. 
11/wsj_1105:Moreover, the number of people who spontaneously cited lower prices as the reason for their interest in Sears declined to 16% in September from 33% in March.
11/wsj_1105:Just 5% of the respondents mentioned brands in September, up slightly from 2% in March.
11/wsj_1105:Only 2% of the people in September cited Sears's "friendly personnel." 
11/wsj_1105:"The power of price as an appeal, which was very considerable in driving traffic in March and April, has diminished," says George Rosenbaum, president of Shapiro & Associates. "You see some improvement in these other areas, but it's a very small and slow process." 
