11/wsj_1131:From 1980 to 1988, while federal budget deficits totaled $1.41 trillion, the government issued $394 billion of new direct loans and an additional $756 billion of new primary loan guarantees.
11/wsj_1131:These figures omit secondary guarantees, deposit insurance, and the activities of Government-Sponsored Enterprises (a huge concern in its own right, as detailed on this page May 3). 
11/wsj_1131:Since the 1950s, federal lending has experienced extraordinary growth in credit volume, subsidy rates, and policy applications, spurred on by the growth of government in general and budget gimmicks and deceptive management in particular.
11/wsj_1131:As we will see, many of these obligations don't show up as part of the federal deficit. 
11/wsj_1131:But recent events indicate that federal credit is out of control.
11/wsj_1131:Student loan defaults remain high at about 12%, and the program has been rocked by allegations of fraud and mismanagement.
11/wsj_1131:GAO's findings are particularly troubling because the FHA has about $300 billion in obligations outstanding and had previously been considered one of the most financially secure credit programs. 
11/wsj_1131:Scores of other credit programs, subsidizing agriculture, small business, exporters, defense, energy, transportation and others, are less visible but in no better shape.
11/wsj_1131:If the programs continue their present path, the potential government losses are staggering: The federal government holds $222 billion in direct loans outstanding and backs an additional $550 billion in primary guarantees. (Secondary guarantees of pools of FHA- and VA-backed loans by the agency known as Ginnie Mae currently exceed $330 billion.) 
11/wsj_1131:Although external events have contributed to the morass, the principal causes of the current crisis are internal and generic to all programs.
11/wsj_1131:Use credit to improve the operation of capital markets, not to provide subsidies. 
11/wsj_1131:There is a fundamental conflict between providing a subsidy and maintaining the integrity of a credit program.
11/wsj_1131:In contrast, credit programs can be appropriate tools to improve the operation of capital markets.
11/wsj_1131:For example, legal restrictions on interstate banking once inhibited the supply of credit to the agricultural sector.
11/wsj_1131:Farm lending was enacted to correct this problem by providing a reliable flow of lendable funds.
11/wsj_1131:High default rates, a low interest rate, and government coverage of all interest costs while the student is in school make program costs extremely high.
11/wsj_1131:In contrast, a student loan program that was meant solely to correct capital-market imperfections would allow loans for any student, regardless of family income, at market or near-market rates.
11/wsj_1131:Given the structure of most credit programs, it is surprising that default rates are not even higher.
11/wsj_1131:Since the government has a dismal record of collecting bad debts, the costs to the borrower of defaulting are usually low.
11/wsj_1131:Record the true costs of credit programs in the federal budget. 
11/wsj_1131:Since the budget measures cash flow, a new $1 direct loan is treated as a $1 expenditure, even though at least part of the loan will be paid back.
11/wsj_1131:By converting an expenditure or loan to a guarantee, the government can ensure the same flow of resources and reduce the current deficit.
11/wsj_1131:The true budgetary cost of a credit subsidy is the discounted value of the net costs to government.
11/wsj_1131:Neither technique is perfect, but both are better than the current system, which misstates the costs of new credit programs by amounts that vary substantially and average about $20 billion annually, according to the Congressional Budget Office.
11/wsj_1131:A budget that reflected the real costs of lending would eliminate incentives to convert spending or lending programs to guarantees and would let taxpayers know what Congress is committing them to. 
11/wsj_1131:Creative accounting is a hallmark of federal credit.
11/wsj_1131:More seriously, FmHA has carried several billion dollars of defaulted loans at face value.
11/wsj_1131:The administration of federal credit should closely parallel private lending practices, including the development of a loan loss reserve and regular outside audits.
11/wsj_1131:Establishing these practices would permit earlier identification of emerging financial crises, provide better information for loan sales and budgeting decisions, and reduce fraud. 
11/wsj_1131:Mr. Gale is an assistant professor of economics at UCLA. 
