11/wsj_1158:Medieval philosophers used to hold the sensible belief that it was more perfect to exist than not to exist, and that to exist as a matter of necessity was most perfect of all.
11/wsj_1158:Now, only God exists as a matter of absolute necessity; it is built into His nature.
11/wsj_1158:But since the time of Darwin, we humans could at least claim a sort of natural necessity for the existence of our species.
11/wsj_1158:Aren't we, after all, the inevitable culmination of that stately pageant called evolution?
11/wsj_1158:If mutation and natural selection slowly but surely give rise to more and more advanced forms of life, then it was only a matter of eons before splendid beings endowed with reason, self-awareness and taste shimmered onto the scene. 
11/wsj_1158:Star lecturer at Harvard, author of numerous popular books on science, and scourge of the creationist lobby, Mr. Gould is perhaps the world's most eminent evolutionary theorist.
11/wsj_1158:For him, natural history is anything but a gradual, predictable march from primordial slime to human consciousness; it is a careening, chaotic affair in which the emergence of a featherless biped was a one-in-a-million shot. 
11/wsj_1158:In "Wonderful Life: The Burgess Shale and the Nature of History" (Norton, 326 pages, $19.95), Mr. Gould makes his case for "the awesome improbability of human evolution." The argument turns on the discovery in 1909 of an amazing fossil quarry high in the Canadian Rockies called the Burgess Shale.
11/wsj_1158:Here, in an area smaller than a city block, lay buried traces of countless weird creatures that had frolicked more than 500 million years ago -- creatures whose anatomical variety far exceeded what can be found in all the world's oceans today. 
11/wsj_1158:Such an embarrassment of riches was inconceivable to the man who discovered the Burgess Shale, one Charles Doolittle Walcott.
11/wsj_1158:The received Darwinian wisdom of the day said that animals living so long ago must be simple in design, limited in scope and ancestral to contemporary species.
11/wsj_1158:Harry Whittington and two sharp graduate students began to publish a reinterpretation of the Burgess Shale.
11/wsj_1158:By making clever inferences about how the squashed and distorted fossil remains corresponded to three-dimensional structures, this trio was able to piece together a series of wondrous beasties quite unlike anything currently on the planet.
11/wsj_1158:Would that Mr. Gould's minute descriptions of these creatures was always so colorful.
11/wsj_1158:A good deal of the book is boring, particularly the endless allusions to high and pop culture and the frequent jokes festooning the text.
11/wsj_1158:Interest picks up, though, when Mr. Gould gets around to discussing the meaning of the Burgess oddities for the theory of evolution.
11/wsj_1158:Not long after the appearance of life, evidently, there was an explosive proliferation in the number of animal designs seen on the earth.
11/wsj_1158:The vast majority of them, however, were wiped out by a succession of environmental upheavals that were too sudden and catastrophic for the normal rules of natural selection to operate.
11/wsj_1158:Consequently, the winnowing process was like a lottery "in which each group {held} a ticket unrelated to its anatomical virtues." So much for survival of the fittest. 
11/wsj_1158:Back when the Burgess fauna were flourishing, it seems, human evolutionary hopes hung on the survival of a little worm with a backbone called Pikaia.
11/wsj_1158:Mr. Gould finds this oddly exhilarating; like an existentialist of old, he views our contingency as "a source of both freedom and consequent moral responsibility." I, by contrast, cannot help feeling that if some other curiosity from the Burgess Shale had survived instead, beings at once wiser and less boorish than Homo sapiens might have eventually gained earthly dominion.
11/wsj_1158:But even if no conscious life had evolved here at all, the universe is a big place, and given the right conditions, sympathetic to creating some form of life.
11/wsj_1158:Surely at some other cosmic address a Gouldoid creature would have risen out of the ooze to explain why, paleontologically speaking, "it is, indeed, a wonderful life." 
11/wsj_1159:The Justice Department scrambled to play down the significance of its new guidelines concerning prosecutions under the federal racketeering law. 
11/wsj_1159:They discourage prosecutors, under certain circumstances, from seeking court orders seizing the assets of racketeering defendants prior to trial.
11/wsj_1159:Use of the Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt Organizations law against white-collar defendants, as opposed to alleged organized-crime figures, has come under attack from some defense lawyers and legal scholars.
11/wsj_1159:Critics have complained that the law unfairly strips defendants of assets before a jury determines they have committed a crime and that aggressive use of the forfeiture provisions can ruin corporate defendants or force them into unfavorable plea bargains. 
11/wsj_1159:In the new guidelines, the Justice Department says that in attempting to freeze disputed assets before trial, "the government will not seek to disrupt the normal, legitimate business activities of the defendant" and "will not seek. . .to take from third parties assets legitimately transferred to them." 
11/wsj_1159:Mr. Runkel declined to speculate on whether the guidelines would curb racketeering prosecutions against corporate defendants. "The impact, if there is any, will be impossible to judge ahead of time because the decision whether to use {racketeering charges} is made in individual cases" by Justice Department officials in Washington, he said. 
11/wsj_1159:In a memorandum describing the guidelines, Assistant Attorney General Edward Dennis Jr. said that government efforts to freeze defendants' assets pending racketeering prosecutions "have been the subject of considerable criticism in the press." But Mr. Runkel said the government isn't "backing off on these kinds of matters at all." 
11/wsj_1160:The talk of a sales tax rise follows a rebuff from Congress on the question of how much the federal government is willing to spend to aid in California's earthquake relief efforts.
11/wsj_1160:The state had sought as much as $4.1 billion in relief, but yesterday the House approved a more general scaled-back measure calling for $2.85 billion in aid, the bulk of which would go to California, with an unspecified amount going to regions affected by Hurricane Hugo. 
11/wsj_1160:According to the state department of finance, a one-penny increase in the state's six-cent per dollar sales tax could raise $3 billion. 
11/wsj_1160:Willie Brown, speaker of California's Assembly, said that Gov. George Deukmejian has agreed to schedule a special session of the legislature within two weeks. 
11/wsj_1160:According to a spokesman, the governor is also studying the possibility of raising state gasoline taxes.
11/wsj_1160:One immediate source of money is an emergency fund set up by Gov. Deukmejian.
11/wsj_1160:The fund has about $1 billion and is set up to handle "precisely the kind of emergency" the state faces, said Tom Beermann, the Governor's deputy press secretary.
11/wsj_1160:And then it will be required to lower taxes by a corresponding amount during a three-year period after the temporary tax increase ends, said Cindy Katz, assistant director of the state department of finance. 
11/wsj_1160:A sales tax increase would require two-thirds approval in both houses of the state's legislature.
11/wsj_1160:But observers expect broad support. "If there's an emergency and there aren't sufficient funds from elsewhere, I think the attitude will be supportive," said Kirk West, president of the California Chamber of Commerce. 
11/wsj_1160:But others think property owners ought to pay a higher portion of the state's earthquake relief tab.
11/wsj_1160:Since the late 1970s, California property owners have benefited from a tax rollback as a result of a state ballot initiative known as Proposition 13. 
11/wsj_1160:But Gov. Deukmejian and others are reluctant to do anything to harm the state's chances of sharply raising gasoline taxes on a permanent basis. 
11/wsj_1160:Not everyone is convinced the state must raise new revenue to meet its earthquake needs. "It's possible, though not probable," that the state could get by with its existing resources and federal help, said Quentin Kopp, chairman of the state senate's transportation committee. 
11/wsj_1160:The claims, which were filed with the State Board of Control but will probably end up in court, are the first arising out of the collapse of the so-called Cypress structure viaduct. 
11/wsj_1160:The men can defeat immunities that states often assert in court by showing that officials knew or should have known that design of the structure was defective and that they failed to make reasonable changes. 
11/wsj_1160:A Board of Control spokesman said the board had not seen the claim and declined to comment. 
