13/wsj_1302:At Lloyd's of London, underwriters still scratch out policies using fountain pens and blotting paper.
13/wsj_1302:Visitors are ushered into the premises by red-frocked doormen known as waiters, a reminder of the insurance market's origins in a coffeehouse in 17th century London. 
13/wsj_1302:Such trappings suggest a glorious past but give no hint of a troubled present. 
13/wsj_1302:Lloyd's, once a pillar of the world insurance market, is being shaken to its very foundation.
13/wsj_1302:The 301-year-old exchange is battered by enormous claims from a decade-long run of unprecedented disasters, the most recent of which is last week's earthquake in California's Bay Area.
13/wsj_1302:At the same time, Lloyd's is besieged by disgruntled investors and hamstrung by inefficient but time-honored ways of conducting business.
13/wsj_1302:The exchange is gradually being squeezed into narrow, less-profitable segments of the market by less hidebound competitors. 
13/wsj_1302:Most troublesome is the shrinking pool of "names," the well-heeled investors (some of them royal) who, as members of about 360 syndicates, underwrite policies.
13/wsj_1302:Some 1,750 members quit the exchange last year, more than triple the number of resignations in 1987.
13/wsj_1302:Many of the 31,329 investors who remain are beginning to question one of the exchange's most basic tenets, the concept of unlimited personal liability.
13/wsj_1302:Investors may reap huge profits when premiums exceed claims, but they are liable to their last pound or dollar in the event of a catastrophe.
13/wsj_1302:During the five-year period ended 1986, roughly 80% of the names had money tied up in money-losing syndicates, according to Chatset consultants.
13/wsj_1302:The peril of unlimited liability looms large for a number of them now. "I have wished I could die and be out of it -- that's how bad it is," Betty Atkins, a secretary from suburban London, says. 
13/wsj_1302:Ms. Atkins, who underwrote #20,000, or about $32,000, of insurance coverage on that syndicate, now faces potential losses of roughly #70,000, or $111,000. "If Lloyd's wants #70,000 out of me they will have to take everything I've got -- and even then I don't know if it will be enough," she says. 
13/wsj_1302:Unease is widespread among exchange members. "I can't think of any reason to join Lloyd's now," says Keith Whitten, a British businessman and a Lloyd's member since 1979. "The downside is very considerable, and at the moment the upside is very marginal." If profits don't improve, Mr. Whitten says he may quit the exchange. 
13/wsj_1302:Lloyd's is being squeezed out of low-margin but more consistently profitable product lines such as primary property and marine insurance.
13/wsj_1302:Over the past decade, competitors have chipped away at the exchange's share of the #2.5 billion marine market in London, where half the world's ships are insured. 
13/wsj_1302:Lloyd's 66% stake in that market has shrunk to 50% in that period, according to an official at the Institute of London Underwriters, a Lloyd's competitor. (The official asked not to be named.) Much of the business has gone to the institute, an association of more than 100 insurers, including Cigna Corp., Allianz Versicherungs AG of West Germany and Britain's Commercial Union Assurance PLC. 
13/wsj_1302:Lloyd's has endured decades of genteel decline.
13/wsj_1302:At the peak of its power and influence a century ago, Lloyd's dominated the insurance world with a 50% stake.
13/wsj_1302:Today, Lloyd's share of the world market, excluding life insurance, is about 2%. (Its stake is even smaller if life insurance is included.) Bigger rivals, such as Aetna and Allianz, backed by armies of statisticians using computers in hundreds of branches, operate more efficiently and often can offer lower rates, brokers say.
13/wsj_1302:Though Lloyd's pioneered such now-standard policies as worker's compensation insurance, burglary insurance for homeowners and businesses, and bankers' liability insurance, competitors now underwrite most of that business. 
13/wsj_1302:Beyond that, many big oil, chemical and airline companies are siphoning off big chunks of the market by insuring themselves through "captive" offshore companies for industry-specific coverage.
13/wsj_1302:Only 10 years ago, for instance, Lloyd's was the pre-eminent insurer of thoroughbred horses.
13/wsj_1302:But since 1981, Kirk Horse Insurance Inc. of Lexington, Ky. has grabbed a 20% stake of the market. 
13/wsj_1302:Thus, he asserts, Lloyd's can't react quickly to competition. "Lloyd's has lost control of the situation," he says. "They aren't controlling their destiny like they used to." 
13/wsj_1302:Lloyd's, he says, is cut off from "the vast body of premium down at the bottom end which acts as a steadying influence" against catastrophic losses.
13/wsj_1302:By that, he means low-margin but low-risk products such as certain types of primary property insurance.
13/wsj_1302:Three years ago, the exchange took up residence in a space-age tower of steel and glass -- evocative of the kind of modern architecture that Britain's Prince Charles has denounced. (Some exchange wags call the building "the oil rig.") But along with such treasured artifacts as Lord Nelson's spyglass, Lloyd's also brought its outmoded ways of doing business. 
13/wsj_1302:Lloyd's vast trading hall houses a warren of well-polished desks.
13/wsj_1302:Sandwiched between desks, underwriters sit on benches surrounded by stacks of policies.
13/wsj_1302:A broker may have to approach as many as 20 underwriters who insure the endeavors on behalf of the syndicates.
13/wsj_1302:The magnitude of the exchange's problems may not become known for some time because of Lloyd's practice of leaving the books open for three years to allow for the settlement of claims.
13/wsj_1302:That year, it posted record pretax profit of #650 million, a gain it attributes to higher rates and fewer claims. 
13/wsj_1302:Insurance analysts say the exchange's downturn in profitability is likely to be aggravated by more than $600 million in aviation losses (including the 1988 Pan Am airline disaster over Lockerbie, Scotland) and a still-uncalculated chunk of claims from September's Hurricane Hugo. 
13/wsj_1302:Lloyd's says the departures of names isn't likely to hurt its underwriting capacity, currently about #11 billion.
13/wsj_1302:Mr. Lawrence says the drain of funds has been offset by an increase in investments by the remaining names.
13/wsj_1302:Mr. Wetherell, the underwriter, reckons half of his business could be transacted by computer, cutting costs at least 10%.
13/wsj_1302:But such changes must be cleared by four internal committees and dozens of underwriters, brokers and administrators before being implemented.
13/wsj_1303:Yoshitoki Chino retains his title of chairman of Daiwa, Japan's second-largest securities firm.
13/wsj_1303:In Japanese firms, the president usually is in charge of day-to-day operations, while the chairman's role is more a ceremonial one.
13/wsj_1303:The title of chief executive officer isn't used. 
13/wsj_1303:While people within Daiwa, particularly internationalists, expected that Mr. Dozen, 52, would eventually become Daiwa's president, the speed of his promotion surprised many.
13/wsj_1303:Mr. Dozen is taking over the reins of a securities company that does very well in its domestic market but that is still seeking to realize its potential in global investment banking and securities dealing. 
13/wsj_1303:Daiwa is one of the world's largest securities firms.
13/wsj_1303:As of March 31, the Daiwa group had shareholder equity of 801.21 billion yen ($5.64 billion).
13/wsj_1303:For the six months ended Sept. 30, Daiwa reported unconsolidated (parent company) net income of 79.03 billion yen ($556.5 million) on revenue of 332.38 billion yen ($2.34 billion).
13/wsj_1303:Several observers interpreted Mr. Dozen's appointment as an attempt by Daiwa to make its international operations more profitable while preparing the firm for the effects of the continuing deregulation of Japan's domestic markets, which should mean increased competition. 
13/wsj_1303:All of Japan's so-called Big Four securities firms -- Nomura Securities Co. Ltd., the world's largest, Nikko Securities Co. Ltd., Yamaichi Securities Co. Ltd. and Daiwa -- have suffered setbacks in their attempts to break into foreign markets.
13/wsj_1303:And while the Japanese have stepped up their purchases of U.S. shares in the past several months, they have shown themselves in the past to be fickle investors. 
13/wsj_1303:When he arrived in the U.S. in 1969 -- the start of an eight-year tour -- he tried selling Japanese yen-denominated bonds to U.S. investors. "He made desperate efforts, using the yellow pages from beginning to end," said Koji Yoneyama, president of Daiwa's U.S. unit. "But not a single piece of paper was sold." 
13/wsj_1303:In an interview a few months ago, he recalled how after some training at Salomon Brothers Inc., he successfully bid for the opportunity to sell portions of 20 U.S. corporate bond issues.
13/wsj_1303:In his climb to the top, Mr. Dozen also headed the company's stock-exchange division, its fixed-income units and its international operations. "He was constantly picking up new things to fill out his experience; he is very well-balanced," said Takuro Isoda, chairman of Daiwa's U.S. unit in New York. 
13/wsj_1303:Commission income from domestic stock and bond sales accounts form a large portion of Japanese securities companies' earnings.
13/wsj_1303:And anybody who lacked the backing of the retail sales force "would be fragile," said a Daiwa executive. 
13/wsj_1303:If Mr. Dozen has a weakness, it may be his golf game. "He digs in the sand instead of hitting the ball, like a farmer," said Mr. Yoneyama. 
