13/wsj_1391:China could exhaust its foreign-exchange reserves as early as next year, a Western government report says, unless imports are cut drastically to help narrow the balance-of-payments deficit. 
13/wsj_1391:According to the report, completed last month, if China's trade gap continues to widen at the pace seen in the first seven months of this year, the reserves would be wiped out either in 1990 or 1991.
13/wsj_1391:A country is considered financially healthy if its reserves cover three months of its imports.
13/wsj_1391:The $14 billion of reserves China had in June would cover just that much. 
13/wsj_1391:According to Chinese customs figures, import growth has slowed in recent months, dropping to 16% in July and 7.1% in August from the year-earlier periods, compared with an average growth rate of 26% in the first half. 
13/wsj_1391:The $14 billion level in June marked a drop from $19 billion at the end of April.
13/wsj_1391:But this time, China faces a more difficult battle because of economic forces that have come into play since the Tiananmen Square killings June 4. 
13/wsj_1391:Because of this and the huge trade gap, the deficit in China's current account, which measures trade in goods and services plus certain unilateral transfers of funds, is expected to widen sharply from the $3.8 billion deficit last year. 
13/wsj_1391:The Western government report suggests a number of scenarios for China's current-account balance, two of which are considered most likely. 
13/wsj_1391:In one, imports and exports continue to grow at the respective average rates of 25% and 5% recorded during the first seven months, and the current-account deficit widens to $13.1 billion.
13/wsj_1391:In 1985, China had a record deficit of $11.4 billion. 
13/wsj_1391:In this case, China would still finish the year with a current-account deficit of $8.7 billion, based on projections that imports for all of this year grow 20% and exports 10%. 
13/wsj_1391:In addition, economists are forecasting a slowdown in foreign direct investments as businessmen become increasingly wary of China's deteriorating political and economic environment.
13/wsj_1391:On top of all this, foreign-debt repayments are expected to peak in 1991 to 1992. 
13/wsj_1391:With less capital coming in, China's balance of payments would suffer.
13/wsj_1391:But in either case, the report says, China's balance of payments would rapidly dry up foreign reserves, which are used to finance the imbalance.
