14/wsj_1442:On Friday, Los Angeles-based First Interstate Bancorp said it expects a net loss of $16 million for the third quarter of 1989 because of hemorrhaging at its First Interstate Bank of Arizona unit.
14/wsj_1442:It charged off an estimated $200 million of Arizona loans, leaving the unit with a reserve for future losses of $255 million, about 61% of its $416 million of troubled loans and repossessed real estate. 
14/wsj_1442:The action capped a spurt of grim Arizona banking news for the third quarter, and emphatically signaled that Arizona is challenging Texas's long reign as banking's busiest graveyard.
14/wsj_1442:Security Pacific Corp. said third-quarter credit losses surged a third to $109 million, mainly because of sour Arizona real-estate loans.
14/wsj_1442:Examiners from the Office of the Comptroller of the Currency had been combing through First Interstate's real-estate portfolio since last month; they first recommended that First Interstate take a provision that was less than the eventual $350 million third-quarter hit.
14/wsj_1442:"At that point, {First Interstate} decided it was the better part of valor not to negotiate further," said one industry official close to the talks.
14/wsj_1442:Thomas P. Marrie, chief financial officer, wouldn't comment about the details of the negotiations.
14/wsj_1442:At least six of Arizona's 12 savings and loan institutions have either been taken over by the government's conservatorship program or are essentially insolvent; they are sitting on enormous unrecognized losses. 
14/wsj_1442:For example, Western Savings & Loan Association, which is now in conservatorship, had tangible capital-assets minus liabilities -- of a negative $357.4 million at June 30.
14/wsj_1442:Yet it still held $916.3 million of repossessed real estate, for which it maintains no reserves whatsoever.
14/wsj_1442:It also had $479.7 million of past-due loans; its level of reserves against those wasn't immediately available, though it is believed to be small. 
14/wsj_1442:The rapid deterioration of the Arizona thrifts only adds to the ever-swelling cost of the government's massive thrift bailout, officially estimated at about $166 billion.
14/wsj_1442:Together, the six government-controlled or essentially insolvent Arizona thrifts have tangible capital of a negative $1.5 billion, foreclosed property of $1.8 billion and pastdue loans of $1.63 billion. 
14/wsj_1442:They have no reserves against the real estate, and their reserves against the loans are miniscule compared with the levels of reserves banks are moving to set up.
14/wsj_1442:The thrifts had a combined loss of $487.8 million in the second quarter.
14/wsj_1442:All this havoc is the result of one of the worst busts in Arizona's boom-and-bust history, compounded by some of the usual suspects in 1980s banking debacles: greed, fraud and plain bad banking.
14/wsj_1442:In the late 1970s and early 1980s, lenders and developers poured money into office buildings, condominiums and massive tracts of raw desert land, confident that Arizona's population would grow at annual rates of 4% to 6% for years to come.
14/wsj_1442:Now, annual population growth is running at about 2% a year, some desert tracts bought three years ago for $90,000 an acre are being sold at $25,000 an acre and Phoenix has a seven-year supply of unoccupied office space. 
14/wsj_1442:"It's horrible to say, but it's unfortunate that earthquake wasn't in Phoenix -- it might have knocked out some of our empty buildings," said C.W. Jackson, a prominent Arizona businessman with interests in real estate, banking and many other businesses. 
14/wsj_1442:Ralph Shattuck, publisher of Foreclosure Update newsletter, said foreclosures have climbed to about 1,482 a month just in Maricopa County, where Phoenix is located.
14/wsj_1442:Moreover, Mr. Shattuck and others said residential real estate, which had remained fairly strong through most of the downturn, is beginning to comprise more and more of the foreclosures.
14/wsj_1442:And the generally frail condition of Arizona's lenders means there is little capital available in the state to shore up the economy and slow down the slide. 
