14/wsj_1450:The Bakersfield Supermarket went out of business last May.
14/wsj_1450:Nor was there a shortage of customers in the area, the residential Inwood section of northern Manhattan.
14/wsj_1450:The owner was Israel Ortiz, a 29-year-old entrepreneur and father of two.
14/wsj_1450:In his first year of operating the store he bought for $220,000, Mr. Ortiz was robbed at least twice at gunpoint.
14/wsj_1450:Israel Ortiz is only one of the thousands of entrepreneurs and their employees who will be injured or killed by crime this year.
14/wsj_1450:The U.S. Bureau of Justice Statistics reports that almost 2% of all retail-sales workers suffer injuries from crime each year, almost twice the national average and about four times the rate for teachers, truck drivers, medical workers and door-to-door salespeople.
14/wsj_1450:Only a few other occupations have higher reported rates of criminal injury, such as police, bartenders and taxi drivers. 
14/wsj_1450:Yet these figures show only the most visible part of the problem.
14/wsj_1450:Recent data from New York City provide more of the picture.
14/wsj_1450:While by no means the highest crime community in the country, New York is a prime example of a city where crime strangles small-business development.
14/wsj_1450:A survey of small businesses there was conducted this spring by Interface, a policy research organization.
14/wsj_1450:The survey found that over a three-year period 22% of the firms said employees or owners had been robbed on their way to or from work or while on the job.
14/wsj_1450:More than one-third of the responding businesses said they suffer from drug dealing and loitering near their premises.
14/wsj_1450:In Brooklyn and the Bronx, one out of four commercial firms is burglarized each year.
14/wsj_1450:Albert Reiss's landmark study of crime against 2,500 small businesses drawn from national IRS records.
14/wsj_1450:He found that monetary crime losses, as a proportion of gross receipts, were 37 times higher for small businesses than for large ones. 
14/wsj_1450:The costs of crime may also be enough to destroy a struggling business. 
14/wsj_1450:Whatever the monetary crime losses, they may not be nearly as important to entrepreneurs as the risk of personal injury.
14/wsj_1450:After repeated gun robberies, some entrepreneurs may give up a business out of fear for their lives.
14/wsj_1450:These findings illustrate the vicious cycle that National Institute of Justice Director James K. Stewart calls "crime causing poverty." Underclass neighborhoods offer relatively few employment opportunities, contributing to the poverty of local residents.
14/wsj_1450:This may help explain why small businesses create 65% of all jobs nationally, but only 22% of jobs in a crime-ridden city like New York. 
14/wsj_1450:Bigger business can often better afford to minimize the cost of crime.
14/wsj_1450:The New York study found that the cost of security measures in firms with fewer than five employees was almost $1,000 per worker, compared with one-third that amount for firms with more than 10 employees. 
14/wsj_1450:The shift of retailing to large shopping centers has created even greater economies of scale for providing low-crime business environments.
14/wsj_1450:Private security guards and moonlighting police can invoke the law of trespass to regulate access to these quasi-public places.
14/wsj_1450:Since 1984, in fact, revenues of the 10 largest guard companies, primarily serving such big businesses, have increased by almost 62%. 
14/wsj_1450:The number one proposal for reducing crime in the New York survey was to put more police on foot or scooter patrol, suggested by more than two-thirds of the respondents.
14/wsj_1450:A second problem is the persistent frustration of false alarms, which can make urban police less than enthusiastic about responding to calls from small businesses.
14/wsj_1450:Another solution cities might consider is giving special priority to police patrols of small-business areas.
14/wsj_1450:Increased patrolling of business zones makes sense because urban crime is heavily concentrated in such "hot spots" of pedestrian density.
14/wsj_1450:With National Institute of Justice support, the Minneapolis police and the Crime Control Institute are currently testing the effects of such a strategy, comparing its deterrence value with traditional random patrols. 
14/wsj_1450:It might even have saved the life, and business, of Israel Ortiz. 
14/wsj_1450:Mr. Sherman is a professor of criminology at the University of Maryland and president of the Crime Control Institute in Washington, D.C. 
