14/wsj_1455:A 20-story mesh spire will stand atop 50 stories of commercial space.
14/wsj_1455:To the extent that the $150 million budget will allow it, Mr. McDonough will rely on solid wood, rather than plywood or particle board, to limit the emission of formaldehyde. 
14/wsj_1455:If Mr. McDonough has his way, the Poles will compensate for the trade center's emissions of carbon dioxide, a prime suspect in the global atmospheric warming many scientists fear.
14/wsj_1455:The Poles would plant a 10-square-mile forest somewhere in the country at a cost of $150,000, with the center's developer footing the bill. 
14/wsj_1455:All architects want to be aware of the ecological consequences of their work, says John Burgee, whose New York firm is designing the redevelopment of Times Square, "but we can't all carry it to that extreme." Karen Nichols, senior associate at Michael Graves's architecture firm in Princeton, N.J., says: "We're really at the mercy of what the construction industry can and will do readily." 
14/wsj_1455:The son of a Seagram's executive who was stationed in many countries around the world, Mr. McDonough was born in Tokyo and attended 19 schools in places ranging from Hong Kong to Shaker Heights, Ohio, before entering Dartmouth College.
14/wsj_1455:At Yale, he designed one of the first solarheated houses to be built in Ireland. 
14/wsj_1455:Mr. McDonough's first professional project fully to reflect his environmental ardor was his 1986 design for the headquarters of the Environmental Defense Fund in New York.
14/wsj_1455:The offices took 10,000 square feet of a building with 14-foot ceilings and big, operable windows. 
14/wsj_1455:To reduce it at the fund's building, workers rubbed beeswax instead of polyurethane on the floors in the executive director's office.
14/wsj_1455:Jute, rather than a synthetic material, lies under the tacked-down carpets, and the desks are of wood and granite instead of plastic. 
14/wsj_1455:The fund's lawyers work in an Athenian grove of potted trees.
14/wsj_1455:"We proved a healthy office doesn't cost more," says Frederic Krupp, executive director of the fund. 
14/wsj_1455:Neither the Quilted Giraffe nor the Paul Stuart renovation reflects much of Mr. McDonough's environmental concern.
