15/wsj_1502:Freight rates, declining for most of the decade because of competition spurred by deregulation, are bottoming out, turning upward and threatening to fuel inflation. 
15/wsj_1502:"Demand has caught up with the supply of certain types of freight transportation, and rates are starting to move up" at a rate "close to or slightly more than the inflation rate," said Clifford Sayre, director of logistics at Du Pont Co. 
15/wsj_1502:Only 10% of the 250 shippers polled expected their freight-transport costs to decrease, compared with 30% who had looked to freight transport to reduce costs in past years. "This is the first year since transportation deregulation in 1980 that we have had such a dramatic and broad-based upturn in perceived transportation rates," said Bernard LaLonde, a transportation logistics professor at Ohio State in Columbus. 
15/wsj_1502:The deregulation of railroads and trucking companies that began in 1980 enabled shippers to bargain for transportation.
15/wsj_1502:Shippers cut about $35 billion from their annual, inter-city truck and rail costs, to about $150 billion, or about 6.4% of gross national product, down from 8% of GNP in 1981.
15/wsj_1502:But with much of the inefficiency squeezed out of the freight-transport system, rising costs are likely to be reflected directly in higher freight rates. 
15/wsj_1502:Transport rates won't be an opportunity for offsetting cost increases in other segments of the economy." 
15/wsj_1502:Robert Delaney, a consultant at Arthur D. Little Inc., Cambridge, Mass., said "We've gotten all the benefits of deregulation in freight-cost reductions.
15/wsj_1502:You'll see carriers try to recoup some of the price cutting that occurred previously." 
15/wsj_1502:Not everyone believes that the good times are over for shippers. "There's still a lot of pressure on rates in both rail and truck," said Gerard McCullough, lecturer in transportation at Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
15/wsj_1502:Less-than-truckload companies, which carry the freight of several shippers in each truck trailer, discounted away a 4.7% rate increase implemented last April.
15/wsj_1502:Such rate increases "will increase the total cost of U.S. products and slow down the rate of increase of U.S. exports," said Richard Connors, a senior vice president of Yusen Air & Sea Service U.S.A. Inc., the U.S. air-freight-forwarding subsidiary of Nippon Yusen Kaisha of Japan. 
15/wsj_1502:Ship companies carrying bulk commodities, such as oil, grain, coal and iron ore, have been able to increase their rates in the last couple of years.
15/wsj_1503:MGM Grand Inc. said it filed a registration statement with the Securities and Exchange Commission for a public offering of six million common shares. 
15/wsj_1504:Mr. Stone thought the discipline was unfair; he believed that his manager wanted to get rid of him for personal reasons.
15/wsj_1504:After the three members of the court introduced themselves, the chairman of the panel said: "Go ahead and tell us what happened.
15/wsj_1504:The only extra people were a couple of personnel specialists, one of whom knew Mr. Stone's case intimately and would help fill in any facts needed to give the court the full picture. 
15/wsj_1504:Over a cup of coffee, Mr. Stone told his story.
15/wsj_1504:The court is called the Management Appeals Committee, or just "MAC," and it is likely to hear a couple of dozen cases a year. 
15/wsj_1504:Alter some details of this example and it could be taking place today at Federal Express in Memphis, the Defense and Underseas Systems divisions of Honeywell in Minneapolis, a General Electric plant in Columbia, Md., or a number of other companies.
15/wsj_1504:These firms are pioneers in a significant new trend in the corporate world: the rise of what I call corporate due process.
15/wsj_1504:Although corporate due process is practiced today in few companies -- perhaps 40 to 60 -- it is one of the fastest developing trends in industry.
15/wsj_1504:In the coming decade a majority of people-oriented companies are likely to adopt it. 
15/wsj_1504:Corporate due process appeals to management for a variety of reasons.
15/wsj_1504:It must be able to handle most of the complaints that cannot be solved in the trenches by managers and their subordinates, else the company court or adjudicators will be inundated with cases.
15/wsj_1504:At Polaroid, the Personnel Policy Planning Committee may hear only about 20 cases a year; the rest of the many hundreds of complaints are resolved at earlier stages.
15/wsj_1504:At TWA, the System Board of Adjustment hears 50 to 75 cases a year, only a fraction of the complaints brought to personnel specialists.
15/wsj_1504:At Citicorp, the Problem Review Board may hear only 12 or so cases because of personnel's skill in complaint-resolution. 
15/wsj_1504:In a typical year, up to 20% of the work force goes to personnel specialists with complaints of unfair treatment.
15/wsj_1504:In a large company that means many hundreds of complaints for personnel to handle. 
15/wsj_1504:In case managers and personnel specialists are unsuccessful and subordinates take their complaints to a company court or adjudicator, teach managers to accept reversals as a fact of business life, for in a good due-process system they are bound to happen.
15/wsj_1504:International Business Machines and Bank of America are among the companies using the single-adjudicator approach. 
15/wsj_1504:Most managements hesitate to go all out in advertising their due-process systems for fear of encouraging cranks and chronic soreheads to file complaints.
15/wsj_1504:Naturally, one of the best ways to guarantee visibility for your due-process system is for top management to support it.
15/wsj_1504:At IBM, the company's Open Door system is sometimes the subject of memorandums from the chief executive.
15/wsj_1504:Federal Express goes further in this respect than any company I know of with both Frederick Smith and James Barksdale, chief executive and chief operating officer, respectively, sitting in on the Appeals Board almost every Tuesday to decide cases. 
15/wsj_1504:Mr. Ewing is a consultant based in Winchester, Mass., and author of "Justice on the Job: Resolving Grievances in the Nonunion Workplace" (Harvard Business School Press, 1989). 
