16/wsj_1622:The "seismic" activity of a financial market bears a resemblance to the seismic activity of the earth.
16/wsj_1622:That structural lack is crucial because investors are the only source of market liquidity.
16/wsj_1622:And when any component of the market -- cash, futures or options -- loses liquidity, the price discovery system (the way prices are determined) becomes flawed or is lost entirely for a time. 
16/wsj_1622:When that happened, "seismic" tremors of fear -- much like the shock waves created by an earthquake -- coursed through the market and increased the market's volatility.
16/wsj_1622:Lack of important, needed information can cause fear.
16/wsj_1622:Fear is the father of panic.
16/wsj_1622:Because of a lack of information and access, many investors -- including the very ones whose buying power could restore stability and damp volatility -- are forced to stand on the sidelines when they are most needed, because of their ignorance of important market information.
16/wsj_1622:Contrary to some opinions, the trading activities of specialists and other market makers do not provide liquidity to the market as a whole.
16/wsj_1622:It is a market attribute -- the ability to absorb selling orders without causing significant price changes in the absence of news. 
16/wsj_1622:As a result, while any one customer may purchase immediacy by selling to a market maker (which is micro-liquidity for the investor), the market as a whole remains in the same circumstances it was before the transaction: The unwanted position is still an unwanted position; only the identity of the seller has changed.
16/wsj_1622:In fact it can be argued that increasing capital commitments by market makers (a result of some post-1987 crash studies) also increases market volatility, since the more securities are held by market makers at any given time, the more selling pressure is overhanging the market. 
16/wsj_1622:Current quotations would reflect the combined financial judgment of all market participants -- not just those of intermediaries who become extremely risk-averse during times of crisis. 
16/wsj_1622:Investors and professionals alike would compete on the level playing field Congress sought and called a "national market system" (not yet achieved) almost 15 years ago when it passed the Securities Reform Act of 1975. 
16/wsj_1622:Mr. Peake is chairman of his own consulting company in Englewood, N.J. 
16/wsj_1623:For the past seven years, investors have had the wind at their backs, in the form of a generally growing economy.
16/wsj_1623:In a nutshell, pros advise investors who expect a slowdown to hold fewer stocks than usual and to favor shares of big companies in "defensive" industries.
16/wsj_1623:A heavy dose of cash is prescribed, along with a heavier-than-usual allotment to bonds -- preferably government bonds. 
16/wsj_1623:When they do hit, they hit fast," says David A. Wyss, chief financial economist at the Data Resources division of McGraw-Hill Inc. 
16/wsj_1623:The reason is simple, Mr. Wyss says: "Interest rates almost always decline during recession." As surely as a seesaw tilts, falling interest rates force up the price of previously issued bonds.
16/wsj_1623:This hurts the price of corporate bonds.
16/wsj_1623:That means that a corporation, after a specified amount of time has passed, can buy back its bonds by paying investors the face value (plus, in some cases, a sweetener).
16/wsj_1623:If corporate bonds are bad in recessions, junk bonds are likely to be the worst of all.
16/wsj_1623:It's an "absolute necessity" to get out of junk bonds when a recession is in the offing, says Avner Arbel, professor of finance at Cornell University. "Such bonds are very sensitive to the downside, and this could be a disaster." 
16/wsj_1623:One of these is Jeffrey L. Beach, director of research for Underwood Neuhaus & Co., a brokerage house in Houston, who thinks that "we're either in a recession or about to go into one." What's more, he thinks this could be a nastier recession than usual: "Once the downturn comes, it's going to be very hard to reverse." 
16/wsj_1623:Because he sees a "5% to 6% base rate of inflation in the economy," he doubts that interest rates will fall much any time soon. 
16/wsj_1623:Instead, Mr. Beach says, investors "probably should be carrying a very high level of cash," by which he means such so-called cash equivalents as money-market funds and Treasury bills.
16/wsj_1623:Greg Confair, president of Sigma Financial Inc. in Allentown, Pa., also recommends that investors go heavily for cash.
16/wsj_1623:And, in a sense, that's the kind of task individuals face in deciding what to do about stocks -- the mainstay of most serious investors' portfolios.
16/wsj_1623:It comes down to a question of whether to try to "time" the market. 
16/wsj_1623:Most studies show that buy-and-hold investors historically have earned an annual return from stocks of 9% to 10%, including both dividends and price appreciation.
16/wsj_1623:Moreover, because no one knows for sure just when a recession is coming, some analysts think investors shouldn't even worry too much about timing. "Trying to time the economy is a mistake," says David Katz, chief investment officer of Value Matrix Management Inc. in New York.
16/wsj_1623:Mr. Katz adds that people who jump in and out of the stock market need to be right about 70% of the time to beat a buy-and-hold strategy.
16/wsj_1623:And the in-and-outer might miss the sudden spurts that account for much of the stock market's gains over time. 
16/wsj_1623:According to Ned Davis, president of Ned Davis Research Inc. in Nokomis, Fla., the average drop in the Dow Jones Industrial Average was about 21%, and the decrease began an average of six months before a recession officially started. 
16/wsj_1623:By the time a recession is "official" (two consecutive quarters of declining gross national product), much of the damage to stocks has already been done-and, in the typical case, the recession is already half over.
16/wsj_1623:But whatever their advice about timing, none of these experts recommend jettisoning stocks entirely during a recession.
16/wsj_1623:For the portion of an investor's portfolio that stays in stocks, professionals have a number of suggestions.
16/wsj_1623:And in any case, he argues, stocks of small companies are "almost as overpriced as they were Sept. 30, 1987, just before the crash." 
16/wsj_1623:For example, Mr. Arbel says, stocks of small companies are selling for about 19 times cash flow. (Cash flow, basically earnings plus depreciation, is one common gauge of a company's financial health.) That ratio is dangerously close to the ratio of 19.7 that prevailed before the 1987 stock-market crash, Mr. Arbel says.
16/wsj_1623:George Putnam III, editor of Turnaround Letter in Boston, offers one final tip for recession-wary investors. "Keep some money available for opportunities," he says. "If the recession does hit, there will be some great investment opportunities just when things seem the blackest." 
