16/wsj_1625:Figuring that their money would more likely go toward a bottle of Night Train Express, most people have little trouble saying no to propositions like this.
16/wsj_1625:In a distressing number of cases, no.
16/wsj_1625:While the vast bulk of it was indeed spent by reputable organizations on the good works it was raised for, it's equally true that a sizable hunk was consumed in "expenses" claimed by other operators, including fraudulent expenses.
16/wsj_1625:In many cases the costs claimed were so high that only a dribble of cash was left for the purported beneficiaries. 
16/wsj_1625:It's impossible to say exactly how much of the total charity intake is devoured by stratospheric fund-raising costs, high-living operators, and downright fraud.
16/wsj_1625:State law enforcers can barely keep up with charity scams, and reports from watchdog groups such as the Council of Better Business Bureaus are not encouraging. 
16/wsj_1625:The Philanthropic Advisory Service of the BBB reviews hundreds of new charities every year, measuring them against minimum standards for accountability; for accuracy and honesty in solicitation; and for percentage of funds actually going to work for which the charity was supposedly established.
16/wsj_1625:The Service figures at least half of the money taken in should be spent on program.
16/wsj_1625:Roughly a third of the charities reviewed flunk the test. 
16/wsj_1625:Which, it should be added, doesn't prevent the charities from raking in a lot of money anyway.
16/wsj_1625:On this basis, "there's no way the average person can know a good charity from a bad one," says David Ormstedt, an assistant attorney general in Connecticut. "A lot of donors just get taken." 
16/wsj_1625:Including those, he contends, who put about $1 million into the kitty for the Connecticut Association of Concerned Veterans and the Vietnam Veterans Service Center.
16/wsj_1625:The state has sued these charities in state court, complaining that much of the money was grossly misspent; 82%, says Mr. Ormstedt, went to fund raisers and most of the rest to the people who ran the charities and to their relatives -- for fur coats, trips to Florida, Lucullan restaurant tabs.
16/wsj_1625:Running a charity does cost money, but reputable organizations manage to get the lion's share of donations out to where they are really needed.
16/wsj_1625:The Arthritis Foundation, the American Cancer Society and the United Way of America all say that they spend roughly 90% of their income on programs, not overhead.
16/wsj_1625:The state of Illinois is suing the charity for fraud in Chicago, along with Telesystems Marketing Inc., its Houston-based fund raiser. 
16/wsj_1625:Michael Burns, president of Telesystems, says his concern has only benefited from the publicity surrounding the case, noting that three other charities have signed on as clients because they were impressed with the amount he raised for National Children's.
16/wsj_1625:Enforcers can't put charities out of business simply because they spend the lion's share of their income on fund raising.
16/wsj_1625:State laws previously used as a yardstick minimum percentages of income -- usually half -- that had to be spent on the program rather than overhead, but these have been overturned by the U.S. Supreme Court.
16/wsj_1625:It has ruled that such laws might work to stifle fund raising, which would amount to limiting the charities' first-amendment right to freedom of expression. 
16/wsj_1625:This puts upon enforcers the burden of proving outright fraud or misrepresentation, and such actions have been brought against hundreds of charities recently.
16/wsj_1625:The attorney general's office in Connecticut alone has put seven of them out of business over the past couple of years, and the enforcement drive is continuing there and elsewhere. 
16/wsj_1625:Illinois, for instance, currently has under investigation 10 of the 30 companies drumming up funds for charities soliciting there. 
16/wsj_1625:Attorneys general in several states, including Illinois, are already suing Watson & Hughey Co., an Alexandria, Va.-based outfit that they say has used deceptive sweepstakes ads to solicit donations for the American Heart Disease Foundation and the Cancer Fund of America. 
16/wsj_1625:According to the Illinois attorney general's suit, Watson & Hughey sent mailings indicating that recipients were guaranteed cash prizes, and could win up to an additional $1,000 on top of them, if they contributed as little as $7.
16/wsj_1625:But the total value of the prizes was only $5,000 and most "winners" will receive just 10 cents, according to the attorney general's office.
16/wsj_1625:While they can target some of the most obvious miscreants, enforcers concede that they are only scratching the surface.
16/wsj_1625:"All too often this will merely be a statement on the solicitation such as, `Don't smoke!' or `Wear suntan lotion, ' " says William Webster, attorney general of Missouri. "By putting these pithy statements on the solicitations, hundreds of thousands of dollars are claimed to have been spent on education to consumers when in fact this represents the costs of sending the newsletters." 
16/wsj_1625:Many fly-by-night charities ride the coattails of the biggest, best-known and most reputable ones by adopting names similar to theirs.
16/wsj_1625:The established charities are bothered by this but say they can do little about it. "We can't police the many organizations that have sprung up in the last few years using part of our name.
16/wsj_1625:Most of them don't last for long, but in the meantime all we can do is tell people they aren't connected with us," says a spokeswoman for the American Heart Association.
