16/wsj_1635:The assets backing the securities come from some of the country's biggest -- and most secure -- institutions.
16/wsj_1635:Their yields are higher than those of U.S. Treasury issues.
16/wsj_1635:And the booming market has already attracted many of the nation's biggest institutional investors. 
16/wsj_1635:The concept may be simple: Take a bunch of loans, tie them up in one neat package, and sell pieces of the package to investors.
16/wsj_1635:"A lot of this stuff really is in untested waters," says Owen Carney, director of the investment securities division of the U.S. comptroller of the currency. "We don't know how this whole market will work in a serious economic downturn." 
16/wsj_1635:Such concerns, however, haven't stopped asset-backed securities from becoming one of Wall Street's hottest new products.
16/wsj_1635:Since the spring of 1985, financial alchemists have transformed a wide variety of debt into these new securities. 
16/wsj_1635:They have offered bundles of homeequity loans, as well as packages of loans used to buy vacation time-shares.
16/wsj_1635:Last year, there was an issue of "death-backed bonds" -- securities backed by loans to life-insurance policyholders.
16/wsj_1635:"This is the heyday of debt," says James Grant, editor of Grant's Interest Rate Observer, a newsletter. "Before the sun sets on the '80s, it seems nothing will be left unhocked." 
16/wsj_1635:That includes more than $9.5 billion issued through August of this year, up sharply from $6.5 billion in the comparable 1988 period -- and more than in all of 1987. 
16/wsj_1635:The entry fee is affordable: Issues typically are sold in minimum denominations of $1,000. 
16/wsj_1635:"We expect additional offerings" of asset-backed securities targeted toward individual investors, says Bill Addiss, a senior vice president at Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. 
16/wsj_1635:The process typically begins when an institution, such as Citibank or Sears, Roebuck & Co., takes a pool of credit-card or other receivables and sells them to a specially created trust.
16/wsj_1635:Issues typically come with "credit enhancements," such as a bank letter of credit, and thus have received high credit ratings. 
16/wsj_1635:Enthusiasts say the booming market has opened up a valuable new source of funds to issuers, while providing a valuable new investment for individuals and institutions.
16/wsj_1635:Asset-backed securities "are an attractive investment compared to bank certificates of deposit or other corporate bonds," says Craig J. Goldberg, managing director and head of the asset-backed securities group at Merrill Lynch Capital Markets. 
16/wsj_1635:Consider a $500 million offering of 9% securities issued last spring and backed by Citibank credit-card receivables.
16/wsj_1635:The triple-A-rated issue offered a yield of only about 0.5 percentage point above four-year Treasury issues.
16/wsj_1635:On a $10,000 investment, that's a difference of only $50 a year. 
16/wsj_1635:That kind of spread can be critical for money managers who buy bonds in large quantities and whose livelihood depends on outperforming the money manager across the street.
16/wsj_1635:"If you're in the bond business playing the relative-performance derby, then even an extra 25 basis points (0.25 percentage point) becomes an important consideration on a career basis," says Mr. Grant. "But if you're an individual investing money and trying to get it back again, then that isn't of overwhelming importance." 
16/wsj_1635:That's why some investment managers, such as Alex Powers, a vice president of Chase Manhattan Bank's private banking division, don't recommend most asset-backed issues for individuals in high-tax states, such as New York or California. 
16/wsj_1635:That's particularly true, analysts say, for certain of the securities, such as those backed by time-share loans. "You could see massive gyrations here because it's such a thinly traded market," says Jonathan S. Paris, a vice president of European Investors Inc., a New York investment-management firm. 
16/wsj_1635:In addition, an investor who wants to know the daily value of Treasury bonds, or corporate bonds traded on the New York Stock Exchange, can simply check newspaper listings.
16/wsj_1635:The front cover of the prospectus for the Citibank credit-card receivables offering points out in bold capital letters that the certificates represent an interest only in the specially created trust and "do not represent interests in or obligations of the banks, Citibank N.A., Citicorp or any affiliate thereof." In other words, if there's a problem, don't expect Citibank to come to the rescue.
16/wsj_1635:That means investors have to focus on the quality of the debt that lies beneath the securities, as well as on the credit enhancement for the issue and the credit ratings the issue has received.
16/wsj_1635:Take the "credit enhancements," which typically include a bank letter of credit or insurance from a bond-insurance company.
16/wsj_1635:The letter of credit typically is not offered by the bank selling the assets to back the securities.
16/wsj_1635:Details of credit enhancements vary widely from issue to issue.
16/wsj_1635:If a bank's credit rating was lowered because of, say, its loans to Third World nations, that could also affect the ratings, liquidity and prices of the asset-backed issues that the bank supports. 
16/wsj_1635:Some analysts are especially wary of credit-card issues.
16/wsj_1635:"A day of reckoning is coming where we think the market will place a high premium on the highest-quality debt issues, and therefore we think the best debt investment is U.S. government bonds," says Craig Corcoran of Davis/Zweig Futures Inc., an investment advisory firm. 
16/wsj_1635:And it reminds Raymond F. DeVoe Jr., a market strategist at Legg Mason Wood Walker Inc., of what he calls "DeVoe's Unprovable but Highly Probable Theory No. 1: 
16/wsj_1635:"More money has been lost reaching for yield than in all the stock speculations, scams and frauds of all time." 
16/wsj_1635:Volume of asset-backed securities issued annually 
16/wsj_1635:**As of August 30 
16/wsj_1636:Judging by a poll of Wall Street Journal readers conducted this summer by Erdos & Morgan Inc., serious investors have taken that advice to heart.
16/wsj_1636:For example, about 88% of Journal readers owned stock (down slightly from 91% in a similar poll last year).
16/wsj_1636:Similarly, 57% of respondents own shares in a money-market mutual fund, and 33% own municipal bonds.
16/wsj_1636:But only 6% to 7% of the investors were committing more than half their funds to either of those alternatives. 
16/wsj_1636:The poll, conducted Aug. 7-28, also provides a glimpse into the thinking of serious investors on a variety of other topics.
16/wsj_1636:Of 1,500 people sent a questionnaire, 951 replied.
16/wsj_1636:The response rate, more than 63%, allows the results to be interpreted with a high degree of confidence.
16/wsj_1636:Journal readers are relatively affluent, with a median household income of between $75,000 and $99,000.
16/wsj_1636:Nearly half of the respondents (47%) said their investment portfolio was worth $250,000 or more, and 17% said it was worth $1 million or more. 
16/wsj_1636:For example, 12% of this year's respondents said they expect a recession within 12 months.
16/wsj_1636:An additional 56% of this year's respondents expect the economy to slow down during the next 12 months.
16/wsj_1636:Only 42% of last year's respondents anticipated slowing growth. 
