17/wsj_1737:(During its centennial year, The Wall Street Journal will report events of the past century that stand as milestones of American business history.) 
17/wsj_1737:Options lost some of their mystery in 1973 when the Chicago Board of Trade set up a special exchange to deal in them.
17/wsj_1737:The Chicago Board of Trade, the No. 1 U. S. grain market, had long chafed under the attention won by its innovative archrival, the livestock-dealing Mercantile Exchange.
17/wsj_1737:So the men who ran the grain pits listened when Joseph Sullivan, a 35-year-old former Wall Street Journal newsman, offered them the idea of all-options trading.
17/wsj_1737:After four year of tinkering and $2.4 million in seed money, the board set up the new marketplace, titled it the Chicago Board Options Exchange, and named Sullivan its first president. 
17/wsj_1737:The CBOE opened for business on April 26, 1973, in what had been a Board of Trade lunchroom.
17/wsj_1737:It listed just 16 options to buy a "pilot list" of stocks on the New York Stock Exchange. (Puts, or sell options, would not be added until 1977.) The 282 members had paid $10,000 apiece for seats. (The 1989 price: $250,000.) 
17/wsj_1737:The first day's business was 911 contracts (each for 100 shares of one of the listed stocks).
17/wsj_1737:By the end of 1973, the number of "underlying" Big Board stocks had been increased to 50 and the options exchange had run up volume of 1.1 million contracts.
17/wsj_1737:Last year, more than 1,800 traders on the CBOE bought and sold 112 million contracts on 178 listed stocks, 60% of all U.S. listed options trading. 
