17/wsj_1789:President Carlos Salinas de Gortari used the army to oust La Quina, who reigned for 28 years over a graft-riddled empire that made state-run Petroleos Mexicanos, or Pemex, one of the world's most inefficient oil companies.
17/wsj_1789:In recent contract negotiations with Pemex management, Mr. Guzman Cabrera accepted major concessions that greatly curtail the union's role in subcontracting, long a source of millions of dollars in illicit earnings.
17/wsj_1789:And with the quiet pragmatism of Mr. Guzman Cabrera replacing the prickly populism of La Quina, government technocrats have been given a free hand to open the petrochemical sector to wider private and foreign investment. 
17/wsj_1789:Leftist leader Cuauhtemoc Cardenas publicly questioned Mr. Guzman Cabrera's "moral quality," suggesting he is part of a conspiracy to turn over the country's oil, a symbol of Mexican nationalism, to foreigners. 
17/wsj_1789:The 61-year-old Mr. Guzman Cabrera takes such criticisms in stride. "This isn't a new kind of union leadership, it's a new Mexico.
17/wsj_1789:We're no longer afraid of associating with private or foreign capital," he says. 
17/wsj_1789:Pemex, which produces 40% of government revenue, desperately needs new investment.
17/wsj_1789:A bloated payroll and pervasive graft caused Pemex's operating costs to balloon to 95 cents of each $1 in sales, far above the industry norm. 
17/wsj_1789:Some projections show Mexico importing crude by the end of the century, barring an overhaul of operations. "Whatever you tried to change, whether it was cutting costs or attracting new partners, the big obstacle was the old union leadership," says oil consultant George Baker. 
17/wsj_1789:Enter Mr. Guzman Cabrera, who has a clear understanding of where union leaders fit in the pro-enterprise regime of President Salinas. "I'm the secretary-general, if there is one," he says, greeting a visitor to his office.
17/wsj_1789:Though he also long benefited from the system built by La Quina, Mr. Guzman Cabrera says union perks had simply gotten out of hand.
17/wsj_1789:They are "at the base of all of the problems of corruption," he says. 
17/wsj_1789:Thus, in recent contract negotiations, Mr. Guzman Cabrera gave up the union's right to assign 40% of all of Pemex's outside contracts -- an enormous source of kickbacks.
17/wsj_1789:The new contract also eliminates the $15 monthly coupon, good only at union-owned grocery stores, that was part of the salary of every worker, from roughneck to chief executive.
17/wsj_1789:Also, because of its reduced capital budget, Pemex has phased out about 50,000 transitory construction workers, reducing the work force to about 140,000, the union leader says.
17/wsj_1789:But Pemex managers are the ones most thrilled by the contract. "We are retaking the instruments of administration," says Raul Robles, a Pemex subdirector.
17/wsj_1789:This year, for the first time, Desc and other customers were consulted well in advance of the Pemex plant's shutdown to ensure minimal inconvenience. 
17/wsj_1789:But Pemex's courtship with private companies, and especially foreign ones, is controversial in a country where oil has been a symbol of national sovereignty since foreign oil holdings were nationalized in 1938. "They are preparing the workers for what's coming: foreign control," wrote Heberto Castillo, a leftist leader. 
17/wsj_1789:But the new union leader makes no apologies for Pemex's more outward-looking attitude. "If we do not integrate into this new world of interdependence, sooner or later we're going to become victims of our own isolation," he says. 
