17/wsj_1790:Power of Suggestion 
17/wsj_1790:HERE'S ONE more explanation for why Japan is a tough industrial competitor: Two of three Japanese employees submit suggestions to save money, increase efficiency and boost morale, while only 8% of American workers do. 
17/wsj_1790:Data for 1987 from the National Association of Suggestion Systems and the Japan Human Relations Association also indicate that Japanese employers adopt four of five suggestions, while their U.S. counterparts accept just one in four. 
17/wsj_1790:U.S. companies tend to favor suggestions "that go for the home runs," says Gary Floss, vice president of corporate quality at Control Data Corp. 
17/wsj_1790:That helps explain why American employers grant an average award of $604.72 per suggestion, while Japan's payment is $3.23.
