18/wsj_1815:Per capita income, a widely used measure of a nation's economic health, hit a record in 1988, rising 1.7% after inflation adjustment to $13,120.
18/wsj_1815:But the median income of American families fell 0.2%, the first time it has failed to rise since 1982. 
18/wsj_1815:Mr. Butz said the divergence in the two measures reflects changes in family size and structure, including the rising number of female-headed families and a sharp increase in income reported by Americans who aren't living in families. 
18/wsj_1815:As a result of last year's decline, the government's estimate for the number of people living below the poverty line declined by about 500,000.
18/wsj_1815:The poverty threshold, defined as three times food expenses as calculated by the Agricultural Department, last year was $12,092 for a family of four.
18/wsj_1815:Thanks largely to the continued growth of the U.S. economy, the poverty rate is now substantially lower than the 1983 peak of 15.3%, but the improvements have been modest in the past couple of years. 
18/wsj_1815:In 1988, 31.6% of blacks lived in poverty, compared with 10.1% for whites and 26.8% for Hispanics.
18/wsj_1815:But two-thirds of all poor Americans were white.
18/wsj_1815:More than half of poor families were headed by women living without men, the bureau said.
18/wsj_1815:More than three-fourths of poor black families were headed by women. 
18/wsj_1815:The poverty rate of children under 18 years old dropped last year to 19.7% from 20.5% in 1987, but remained far higher than a decade ago.
18/wsj_1815:-- Some 17.2% of all money income received by families in 1988 went to the wealthiest 5% of all families, up from 16.9% in 1987.
18/wsj_1815:-- The top fifth of all families got 44% of the income, up from 41.5% a decade earlier.
18/wsj_1815:The bottom fifth of all families got 4.6% of the income, down from 5.2% a decade earlier. 
18/wsj_1815:-- Confirming other government data showing that wages aren't keeping pace with inflation, earnings of year-round, full-time male workers fell 1.3% in 1988 after adjusting for higher prices, the first such drop since 1982.
18/wsj_1815:Earnings of female workers were unchanged. 
18/wsj_1815:-- Per capita income of blacks, though still only 60% that of whites, rose 3.9% in 1988, while per capita income of whites rose only 1.5%. 
18/wsj_1815:-- Among married couples, the gap between blacks and whites narrowed sharply, as income of black families shot up 6.8% while income of whites didn't budge. 
18/wsj_1815:The bureau said some 3.5 million fewer people would have fallen below the poverty line in 1988 -- and the poverty rate would have been 10.5% instead of 13.1% -- under the alternative calculation. 
18/wsj_1815:Critics on the left and right have been calling for all sorts of revisions to the measure for years.
18/wsj_1815:A report by the staff of the Joint Economic Committee of Congress released yesterday concluded, "It is misleading to make this change without adjusting for other changes." 
18/wsj_1815:The official poverty threshold is set by the Office of Management and Budget. 
18/wsj_1817:The space shuttle Atlantis boosted the Galileo spacecraft on its way to Jupiter, giving a big lift as well to an ambitious U.S. program of space exploration. 
18/wsj_1817:Seven years late in the launching, $1 billion over budget and a target of anti-nuclear protestors, Galileo has long been a symbol of trouble for the National Aeronautics and Space Administration.
18/wsj_1817:But yesterday, as Atlantis rumbled into a patch of clear sky above Florida with storm clouds closing in on it, NASA sought to turn Galileo into a symbol of triumph. 
18/wsj_1817:Jupiter is so enormous -- its mass is 318 times that of Earth -- that its gravity may have trapped these primordial gases and never let them escape. 
18/wsj_1817:Investigating Jupiter in detail may provide clues to what astronomer Tobias Owen calls the "cosmic paradox" of life: Jupiter and other bodies in the outer solar system are rich in elements such as hydrogen that are essential for life on Earth, but these planets are lifeless; Earth, on the other hand, has a diminished store of such material but is rich in life.
18/wsj_1817:Some scientists have suggested that comets and asteroids may have brought enough of this kind of material from the outer solar system to Earth to spawn life. 
18/wsj_1817:Beginning in December 1995, Galileo will begin a two-year tour of the Jovian moons.
18/wsj_1817:In 1979, two Voyager spacecraft sent back stunning photos of Jovian moons Io and Europa that showed them to be among the most intriguing bodies in the solar system.
18/wsj_1817:The photos showed active geysers on Io spewing sulfurous material 190 miles into its atmosphere and indicated that Europa may have an ocean hidden under a thick sheet of ice. 
18/wsj_1817:Galileo's photos of Europa will be more than 1,000 times as sharp as Voyager's, according to Torrence Johnson, Galileo's project scientist, and may show whether it actually has the only known ocean other than those on Earth. 
18/wsj_1817:Atlantis lifted Galileo from the launch pad at 12:54 p.m. EDT and released the craft from its cargo bay about six hours later. "Galileo is on its way to another world in the hands of the best flight controllers in this world," Atlantis Commander Donald Williams said. "Fly safely." 
18/wsj_1817:The Galileo project started in 1977, and a number of project veterans were on hand to watch the launch.
18/wsj_1817:An ebullient Mr. Johnson, wearing a NASA baseball cap and carrying a camera and binoculars, called the launch "fantastic." Benny Chin, manager of the Galileo probe, compared it to watching a child leave home. "I'm happy and sad," he said. 
18/wsj_1817:Having argued that Galileo's plutonium power source could have released lethal doses of radiation if the shuttle exploded yesterday, they weren't quieted by yesterday's successful launch.
18/wsj_1817:Voyager 2 sent back spectacular photos of Neptune and its moon, Triton, this summer. 
18/wsj_1817:Next month, NASA plans to launch a satellite to study cosmic rays dating from the birth of the universe.
18/wsj_1817:In December, the shuttle Columbia will try to retrieve a satellite that's been in orbit for nearly five years measuring the deleterious effects of space on materials and instruments.
18/wsj_1817:Not all of NASA's space-science work will be so auspicious, though.
18/wsj_1817:NASA won't attempt a rescue; instead, it will try to predict whether any of the rubble will smash to the ground and where. 
