18/wsj_1849:Natural upheavals, and most particularly earthquakes, are not only horrible realities in and of themselves, but also symbols through which the state of a society can be construed.
18/wsj_1849:The extent of the disaster stemmed from years of chicanery and bureaucratic indifference. 
18/wsj_1849:The larger parallel after the earthquake centered south of San Francisco is surely with the state of the U.S. economy.
18/wsj_1849:Did the stock-market tremors of Friday, Oct. 13, presage larger fragility, far greater upheavals?
18/wsj_1849:Are the engineering and architecture of the economy as vulnerable as the spans of the Bay Bridge? 
18/wsj_1849:The eerie complacency of the Reagan-Bush era has produced Panglossian paeans about the present perfection of U.S. economic and social arrangements.
18/wsj_1849:A licensed government intellectual, Francis Fukuyama, recently announced in The National Interest that history is, so to speak, at an end since the course of human progress has now culminated in the glorious full stop of American civilization.
18/wsj_1849:But we are, in reality, witnessing the continuing decline of the political economy of capitalism: not so much the end of history but the history of the end. 
18/wsj_1849:The financial equivalent of the sand used by those Armenian contractors is junk bonds and the leveraged buy-outs associated with them.
18/wsj_1849:Corresponding to the fall in profit rates was -- in the early 1980s -- the drop in the number arrived at if you divide the market value of firms by the replacement costs of their assets, the famous Q ratio associated with Prof.
18/wsj_1849:In theory, the value attached to a firm by the market and the cost of replacing its assets should be the same.
18/wsj_1849:But of course the market could decide that the firm's capital stock -- its assets -- means nothing if the firm is not producing profits.
18/wsj_1849:By 1982 the ratio was 43.5%, meaning that the market was valuing every dollar's worth of the average firm's assets at 43 cents. 
18/wsj_1849:From the history of capitalism we can take it as a sound bet that if it takes only 43 cents to buy a dollar's worth of a firm's capital stock, an alert entrepreneur won't look the other way.
18/wsj_1849:Result: a landscape littered with lemons, huge debt burdens crushing down upon the arch and spans of corporate America. 
18/wsj_1849:But there were enough promoters announcing the end of history (in this case suspension of normal laws of economic gravity) for society to continue shielding its eyes.
18/wsj_1849:Mainstream economists and commentators, craning their necks up at the great pyramids of junk financing, swiveling their heads to watch the avalanche of leveraged buy-outs, claimed the end result would be a leaner, meaner corporate America, with soaring productivity and profits and the weaker gone to the wall.
18/wsj_1849:But this is not where the rewards of junk financing were found.
18/wsj_1849:The beneficiaries were those financiers whose icon was the topic figure of '80s capitalism, Michael Milken's $517 million salary in one year. 
18/wsj_1849:Left-stream economists I associate with -- fellows in the Union of Radical Political Economists, most particularly Robert Pollin of the economics faculty at the University of California at Riverside -- were not hypnotized in the manner of their pliant colleagues.
18/wsj_1849:The consequences of building empires with sand are showing up.
18/wsj_1849:In contrast to previous estimates reckoning the default rate on junk bonds at 2% or 3%, a Harvard study published in April of this year (and discussed in a lead story in The Wall Street Journal for Sept. 18) found the default rate on these junk bonds is 34%. 
18/wsj_1849:What is the consequence of a high-interest burden, high default rates and continued low profitability?
18/wsj_1849:Corporations need liquidity, in the form of borrowed funds.
18/wsj_1849:Without liquidity from the junk-bond market or cash flow from profits, they look to the government, which obediently assists the natural motions of the capitalist economy with charity in the form of cuts in the capital-gains tax rate or bailouts.
18/wsj_1849:The consequence can be inflation, brought on as the effect of a desperate bid to avoid the deflationary shock of a sudden crash. 
18/wsj_1849:Attacks on inflation come with another strategy of capital of a very traditional sort: an assault on wages.
18/wsj_1849:Mr. Fukuyama, peering through binoculars at the end of history, said in his essay that "the class issue has actually been successfully resolved in the West . . . the egalitarianism of modern America represents the essential achievement of the classless society envisioned by Marx." 
18/wsj_1849:Mr. Fukuyama might want to consult some American workers on the subject of class and egalitarianism.
18/wsj_1849:From its peak in 1972 of $198.41, the average American weekly wage had fallen to $169.28 in 1987 -- both figures being expressed in 1977 dollars.
18/wsj_1849:In other words, after the glory boom of the Reagan years, wages had sunk from the post World War II peak by 16% as capitalists, helped by the government, turned down the screws or went offshore. 
18/wsj_1849:Governments have become sophisticated in handling moments of panic (a word the London Times forbade my father to use when he was reporting the Wall Street crash in 1929).
18/wsj_1849:Capitalism may now be engineered to withstand sudden shocks, but there are fault lines -- the crisis in profits, the assault on wages, the structural inequity of the system -- that make fools of those who claim that the future is here and that history is over. 
