18/wsj_1875:East Germany yesterday removed Erich Honecker, one of the staunchest holdouts against the reform rumbling through the Communist world, in an effort to win back the confidence of its increasingly rebellious citizens.
18/wsj_1875:But while it was a move that stunned the East bloc, it hardly ushers in an era of reform -- at least anytime soon. 
18/wsj_1875:For the Politburo replaced Mr. Honecker, who had led East Germany for 18 years and before that headed its security apparatus, with a man cut of the same cloth: Egon Krenz, the most recent internal-security chief and a longtime Honecker protege.
18/wsj_1875:It raises the long-cherished hopes of many Germans for reunification -- a prospect that almost equally alarms political leaders in Moscow, Washington and Western Europe. 
18/wsj_1875:Although the East German news agency ADN claimed Mr. Honecker had asked to be relieved of his duties for "health reasons," West German government sources said the 26-man Politburo had asked for his resignation at a separate meeting late Tuesday. (Mr.
18/wsj_1875:Honecker was twice hospitalized this summer for a gall bladder ailment and his physical condition has been the subject of intense speculation in the Western media.) 
18/wsj_1875:ADN said Mr. Honecker, a hard-line Stalinist who in 1961 supervised the construction of the Berlin Wall, also was relieved of his title as head of state and his position as chief of the military.
18/wsj_1875:Mr. Honecker's ignoble fall culminates nearly two decades of iron-handed leadership during which Mr. Honecker, now 77 years old, built East Germany into the most economically advanced nation in the Soviet bloc.
18/wsj_1875:His grip on power unraveled this summer as thousands of his countrymen, dissatisfied by the harshness of his rule, fled to the West.
18/wsj_1875:Thousands more have taken to the streets in the last month in East Germany's largest wave of domestic unrest since a workers' uprising in 1953. 
18/wsj_1875:In Washington, the Bush administration took a characteristically cautious and skeptical view of the leadership change.
18/wsj_1875:Because Mr. Krenz has been very much in accord with the policies of Honecker." One top U.S. expert on East Germany added: "There is no clear-cut champion of reform, that we know of, in the East German leadership." 
18/wsj_1875:Indeed, Mr. Krenz said on East German television last night that there will be no sharing of power with pro-democracy groups.
18/wsj_1875:The removal of Mr. Honecker was apparently the result of bitter infighting within the top ranks of the Communist party.
18/wsj_1875:Those allies included Politburo members Guenter Mittag, who has long headed economic affairs, and Joachim Hermann, chief of information policy.
18/wsj_1875:Both men were also relieved of their duties yesterday. 
18/wsj_1875:Born in 1937 in a Baltic Sea town now part of Poland, he was eight years old when World War II ended.
18/wsj_1875:In fact, the two men have had strikingly similar career paths, both having served as chief of internal security before their rise to the top party position. 
18/wsj_1875:Notably, one of Mr. Krenz's few official visits overseas came a few months ago, when he visited China after the massacre in Beijing.
18/wsj_1875:East German Protestantism in particular fears Mr. Krenz, in part because of an incident in January 1988 when he was believed to have ordered the arrest of hundreds of dissidents who had sought refuge in the Church. 
18/wsj_1875:Indeed, according to West German government sources, he was one of the leaders in the power struggle that toppled Mr. Honecker.
18/wsj_1875:"He doesn't want to have the image of the gun man," says Fred Oldenburg, an expert at the Bonn-sponsored Institute of East European and International Studies in Cologne. "He's not a reformer -- he wants to have the image of a reformer." 
18/wsj_1875:As part of his image polishing, Mr. Krenz is expected to take modest steps toward reform to rebuild confidence among the people and reassert the party's authority.
18/wsj_1875:At the same time, the expectations of the East German people are great and will continue to grow.
18/wsj_1875:Says one West German official: "What's necessary now is the process of democratization.
18/wsj_1875:Chancellor Kohl, meanwhile, has invited Mr. Krenz to open discussions with Bonn on a wide range of subjects.
18/wsj_1875:The selection of Mr. Krenz may also disappoint Moscow.
18/wsj_1875:According to the Soviet news agency Tass, "Gorbachev expressed the conviction that the leadership of the Socialist Unity Party of {East} Germany, being sensitive to the demands of the time, . . . will find solutions to complicated problems the GDR {German Democratic Republic} encountered." 
18/wsj_1875:A force of younger pro-Gorbachev members in the East German bureaucracy has for some time been pushing for relaxation within their country.
18/wsj_1875:The older generation has been torn between a fear of tampering with the status quo and a fear of what might happen if they didn't. 
18/wsj_1875:From the perspective of East Germany's old guard, reforms that smack of capitalism and Western-style democracy could eliminate their country's reason for being.
18/wsj_1875:Unlike the other nations of the bloc, East Germany is a creature of the Cold War.
18/wsj_1875:Erasing the differences still dividing Europe, and the vast international reordering that implies, won't endanger the statehood of a Poland or a Hungary.
18/wsj_1875:But it could ultimately lead to German reunification and the disappearance of East Germany from the map.
18/wsj_1875:Up to now, that recipe has consisted of a dogged effort by former leader Walter Ulbricht to establish the country's international legitimacy, followed by Mr. Honecker's campaign to build the East bloc's only successful Stalinist economy into a consumer paradise.
18/wsj_1875:Mr. Honecker spoke of "generally valid objective laws of socialism" and left no room for debate. 
18/wsj_1875:Politburo member Joachim Herrman confessed to a "grave concern" over Hungarian democracy. "Under the banner that proclaims the `renewal of socialism, '" he said, "forces are at work that are striving to eliminate socialism." 
18/wsj_1875:Some loyal voices, in and out of the East German Communist party, saw the nation's unrest coming.
18/wsj_1875:Some writers in theoretical journals even raised the notion of introducing democracy, at least in the workplace.
18/wsj_1875:Their proclaimed purpose is to cleanse East Germany of its Stalinist muck, not to merge with the West.
18/wsj_1875:One of their pastors has envisioned a "new utopia" of "creative socialism." 
18/wsj_1875:Imprisoned by the Nazis during World War II for his political beliefs, Mr. Honecker typified the postwar generation of committed Communist leaders in Eastern Europe who took their cues from Moscow. 
18/wsj_1875:He was a "socialist warrior" who felt rankled by West Germany's enormous postwar prosperity and the Bonn government's steadfast refusal to recognize the legitimacy of his state.
18/wsj_1875:Finally, during his first and only state visit to Bonn two years ago, he won some measure of the recognition he had long sought.
18/wsj_1875:Mr. Honecker's removal "was bound to happen," says one aide to Chancellor Kohl. "It was only a matter of time." 
18/wsj_1875:The European Community Commission increased its forecast for economic growth in the EC in 1989 to 3.5%, slightly higher than its June projection of 3.25%. 
18/wsj_1875:At the other end of the spectrum, West German inflation was forecast at 3% in 1989 and 2.75% in 1990. 
