18/wsj_1881:With airline deals in a tailspin, legendary Wall Street trader Michael Steinhardt could have trouble parachuting out of USAir Group, traders say. 
18/wsj_1881:Now, in the wake of UAL's troubles in financing its buy-out, the airline raiding game has been grounded.
18/wsj_1881:Instead of hoping to sell his USAir stake at analysts' estimated buy-out price of $80 a share, Mr. Steinhardt is stuck with roughly 3.7 million USAir shares that cost him $45, on average, but yesterday closed at 40 1/2, up 1/4, in New York Stock Exchange composite trading. 
18/wsj_1881:At the current price, the USAir holding represents 9% of all the assets that Mr. Steinhardt manages.
18/wsj_1881:"If USAir is worth 80 as a takeover and the stock went to 52, the market was saying Steinhardt's presence wasn't worth anything, in terms of getting a deal done," says a veteran takeover speculator. 
18/wsj_1881:Mr. Steinhardt, who runs about $1.7 billion for Steinhardt Partners, made his name as a gunslinging trader, moving in and out of stocks with agility -- enriching himself and his investment clients.
18/wsj_1881:In recent days, traders say USAir has been buying its own shares, as part of a program to retire about eight million USAir shares, though the carrier won't discuss its buy-back program. 
18/wsj_1881:While USAir isn't considered absolutely takeover-proof, its defenses, including the sale in August of a 12% stake in the company to Mr. Buffett's Berkshire Hathaway, are pretty strong. 
18/wsj_1881:USAir's deal with Mr. Buffett "wasn't exactly a shining example of shareholder democracy," Mr. Steinhardt says.
18/wsj_1881:Such disclosures of big holdings often are used by raiders to try to scare a company's managers, and to stir interest in the stock.
18/wsj_1881:But of course it would be highly unusual for an investment fund such as Steinhardt Partners to take over a company. 
18/wsj_1881:By the second half of 1990, USAir stock could hit 60, says Helane Becker of Shearson Lehman Hutton.
18/wsj_1881:Mr. Steinhardt adds that he bought USAir stock earlier this year as "part of a fundamental investment in the airline group." 
18/wsj_1881:In 1989, Mr. Steinhardt says he made money trading in Texas Air, AMR and UAL. Overall, his investments so far this year are showing gains of about 20%, he adds. 
