19/wsj_1924:HONECKER WAS OUSTED as leader of East Germany amid growing unrest. 
19/wsj_1924:The 77-year-old official, who oversaw the building of the Berlin Wall, was removed during a meeting of the 163-member Communist Party Central Committee in East Berlin.
19/wsj_1924:He was succeeded by internal-security chief Egon Krenz, 52, a hard-liner who quickly ruled out any sharing of power with pro-democracy groups. 
19/wsj_1924:Honecker's departure came after weeks of street protests and an exodus to the West of East Germans who had become disenchanted with his rule. 
19/wsj_1924:At a nationally televised legislative session in Budapest, the Parliament overwhelmingly approved changes formally ending one-party domination in the country, regulating free elections by next summer and establishing the office of state president to replace a 21-member council.
19/wsj_1924:The country was renamed the Republic of Hungary.
19/wsj_1924:The voting for new laws followed dissolution of Hungary's Communist Party this month and its replacement by a Western-style Socialist Party. 
