19/wsj_1939:If the tax on any gain to those assets was doubled, wouldn't the value fall to the owners of the assets?
19/wsj_1939:Isn't it reasonable to assume that the asset you own would be worth more if the government suddenly announced that if you sold it, you would be able to keep 30% more of its gain than you previously believed?
19/wsj_1939:Instead, the press corps readily accepted the notion that a snag in the takeover financing of United Airlines instantly knocked 7% off the value of the nation's capital stock and caused convulsions around the world.
19/wsj_1939:For one thing, quite a number of the leading spokesmen on Wall Street are not portfolio managers, who understand that the value of assets is greatly affected by how government taxes those assets.
19/wsj_1939:That is, with capital gains cut, the glue of the 1986 accord will be gone, and political realities will push up income-tax rates.
19/wsj_1939:The counter-argument, which he has heard, is that if he and his fellow Democrats are successful in killing the president's proposal, the revenue gap will open up tremendously in 1990 because of the weakened economy.
19/wsj_1939:In this atmosphere, there would be no serious consideration of tax increases.
