19/wsj_1961:THE STOCK of Applied Power Inc., which split 2-for-1 in May, has risen since August 1988.
19/wsj_1962:The stock market's dizzying gyrations during the past few days have made a lot of individual investors wish they could buy some sort of insurance. 
19/wsj_1962:But while they want to be on the alert for similar buying opportunities now, they're afraid of being hammered by another terrifying plunge. 
19/wsj_1962:Because a put option gives its owner the right, but not the obligation, to sell a fixed number of shares of the stock at a stated price on or before the option's expiration date, the investor is protected against a sudden drop in the stock's price. 
19/wsj_1962:That's because the cost of buying put options eats into an investor's profit when stock prices rise. 
19/wsj_1962:"This is the type of fire insurance you only buy when the nearby woods are on fire," says Mr. Roth. "You always want your house insured, but you don't always feel the need for your investments to be insured." 
19/wsj_1962:The investor will be out the cost of the put, which is called the "premium," and this loss will reduce the stock-market profit. 
19/wsj_1962:-- If the stock stays at the same price between now and the put's expiration date, the investor's loss will be limited to the cost of the put, less any amount realized from a closing sale of the put.
19/wsj_1962:-- If the price of the stock declines, the put will increase in value.
19/wsj_1962:Once the stock price is less than the exercise price, or "strike price," of the put, the gain will match the loss on the stock dollar for dollar.
19/wsj_1962:Though not reflected in the table, an investor should know that the cost of the option insurance can be partially offset by any dividends that the stock pays. 
19/wsj_1962:For example, Tenneco Inc. pays a quarterly dividend of 76 cents, which would be received before the February option expires and, thus, reduce the cost of using the technique by that amount.
19/wsj_1962:In this case, the investor's risk wouldn't exceed 3.6% of the total investment.
19/wsj_1962:They can do this by purchasing "index puts," which are simply put options on indexes that match broad baskets of stocks.
19/wsj_1962:As a result, the OEX insurance may or may not fully protect an investor's holdings in the event of a market decline. 
19/wsj_1962:So an investor who wanted to realize a profit on OEX puts after the trading suspension would have been out of luck.
19/wsj_1962:On the other hand, only a handful of individual issues were suspended from trading on Friday.
19/wsj_1962:Ultimately, whether the insurance provided by purchasing puts is worthwhile depends on the cost of the options.
19/wsj_1962:That cost rises in times of high market volatility.
19/wsj_1962:That's because it reduces the cost of the stock by the amount of premium received from the sale of the call.
19/wsj_1962:But if the price of the stock rises above the strike price of the option, the stock is almost certain to be called away.
19/wsj_1962:These calculations exclude the effect of commissions paid and dividends received from the stock.
19/wsj_1962:All prices are as of Monday's close. 
