20/wsj_2013:When Maj. Moises Giroldi, the leader of the abortive coup in Panama, was buried, his body bore several gunshot wounds, a cracked skull and broken legs and ribs.
20/wsj_2013:They were the signature of his adversary, Panamanian leader Manuel Antonio Noriega. 
20/wsj_2013:The rebel officer's slow and painful death, at the headquarters of Panama's Battalion-2000 squad, was personally supervised by Gen. Noriega, says a U.S. official with access to intelligence reports.
20/wsj_2013:Leaping into rages, sinking into bouts of drunkenness and mistrust, Mr. Noriega has put to death some 70 of his troops involved in the coup, according to U.S. officials monitoring crematoriums and funeral parlors in Panama City. 
20/wsj_2013:And he is collecting the names of those who telephoned the coup-makers to congratulate them during their brief time in control of his headquarters.
20/wsj_2013:America's war on the dictator over the past two years, following his indictment on drug charges in February 1988, is the legacy of that relationship.
20/wsj_2013:Before American foreign policy set out to destroy Noriega, it helped create him out of the crucible of Panama's long history of conspirators and pirates. 
20/wsj_2013:For most of the past 30 years, the marriage was one of convenience.
20/wsj_2013:From that point on, the U.S. would make a practice of overlooking the Panamanian's misadventures. 
20/wsj_2013:The 55-year-old Mr. Noriega isn't as smooth as the shah of Iran, as well-born as Nicaragua's Anastasio Somoza, as imperial as Ferdinand Marcos of the Philippines or as bloody as Haiti's Baby Doc Duvalier.
20/wsj_2013:Yet he has proved more resilient than any of them.
20/wsj_2013:And out of necessity: The U.S. can make mistakes and still hope to remove him from power, but a single error on his part could cost him his life. 
20/wsj_2013:"The U.S. underestimated Noriega all along," says Ambler Moss, a former Ambassador to Panama. "He has mastered the art of survival." 
20/wsj_2013:In keeping with America's long history of propping up Mr. Noriega, recent U.S. actions have extended rather than shortened his survival.
20/wsj_2013:Mr. Noriega might have fallen of his own weight in 1988 because of Panama's dire economic situation, says Mr. Moss, but increasing external pressure has only given him additional excuses for repression, and a scapegoat for his own mismanagement. 
20/wsj_2013:Perhaps most important, Mr. Noriega's allies have intervened to encourage -- in some cases, to demand -- that the dictator maintain his grip of the throne.
20/wsj_2013:His chief advantage in the fight: his intimate knowledge of American ways and weaknesses.
20/wsj_2013:Luis Carlos, knowing that helping the Americans could advance the career of any Panamanian officer, relayed Tony's reports on the leftist tendencies he observed among his fellow students and, more important, among his officers and instructors.
20/wsj_2013:Born the illegitimate son of his father's maid, he was raised on the mean streets of the central market district of Panama City.
20/wsj_2013:Tony was four years older than most of his fellow cadets, and gained admission to the academy because his brother had falsified his birth certificate.
20/wsj_2013:He considered himself intellectually superior to his Peruvian peers, many of whom were wayward sons sent by their well-off families to the highly disciplined, French-modeled academy as a sort of reform school. 
20/wsj_2013:In his peaked military cap and neatly pressed, French-made uniform, Noriega felt more respected and powerful than ever in his underprivileged life, friends from the period say. "He had an elegant uniform with gold buttons in a country where there was a cult of militarism, where officers were the elite with special privileges," recalls Darien Ayala, a fellow student in Peru and a lifelong friend. 
20/wsj_2013:United Fruit was one of the two largest contributors to Panama's national income.
20/wsj_2013:Mr. Noriega's initial retainer was only $50 to $100 a month, plus occasional gifts of liquor or groceries from the American PX, a former intelligence official says.
20/wsj_2013:A National Guard job assumed by Capt. Noriega in 1964 -- as chief of the transit police in David City, capital of the Chiriqui Province -- was tailor-made for an aspiring super-spy.
20/wsj_2013:By pressuring taxi and bus drivers who needed licenses, he gained a ready cache of information.
20/wsj_2013:Mr. Noriega had learned that a local union leader was sleeping with the wife of his deputy.
20/wsj_2013:So he splashed the information on handbills that he distributed throughout the banana-exporting city of Puerto Armuelles, which was ruled by United Fruit Co.
20/wsj_2013:He signed up for intelligence and counter-intelligence training under American officers at Fort Gulick in Panama in July 1967, according to a copy of a 1983 resume with details Mr. Noriega has since classified as secret.
20/wsj_2013:He flew to Fort Bragg, N.C., in September of that year for a course in psychological operations, returning to the School of the Americas in Panama for a two-month course called "military intelligence for officers." 
20/wsj_2013:Some American officers interpreted his eagerness and studiousness as a sign of loyalty, but they did so falsely.
20/wsj_2013:He rose to chief of intelligence in Panama's socalled G-2 in 1970 after providing populist dictator Torrijos the critical support to defeat a coup attempt against him a year earlier.
20/wsj_2013:He became Gen. Torrijos's inseparable shadow, and the holder of all Panama's secrets.
20/wsj_2013:When U.S. diplomats complained to the CIA of Col. Noriega's moonlighting, intelligence experts always insisted that his allegiance was first to the Americans. 
20/wsj_2013:"Early on in the State Department, we took to calling him the rent-a-colonel, in tribute to his ability to simultaneously milk the antagonistic intelligence services of Cuba and the United States," recalls Francis J. McNeil, who, as deputy assistant secretary of state for inter-American affairs, first ran across reports about Mr. Noriega in 1977. "Some of us wondered how our intelligence people could put so much stock in his information when he was just as close to the Cubans." 
20/wsj_2013:During the Nixon administration, the Drug Enforcement Administration became dismayed at the extent of the G-2's connections to arrested drug traffickers.
20/wsj_2013:One DEA agent drew up a list of five options for dealing with Col. Noriega, one of which was assassination. 
20/wsj_2013:The head of the DEA at the time, John Ingersoll, scotched the assassination plan.
20/wsj_2013:But he did fly to Panama to scold dictator Torrijos on the drug ties of Panamanian officials, including Mr. Noriega.
20/wsj_2013:Mr. Ingersoll later recalled that Gen. Torrijos seemed afraid to act on the concerns of the U.S. "Everybody was afraid of him," Mr. Ingersoll says. 
20/wsj_2013:Mr. Noriega became an even greater threat in 1976, when U.S. intelligence services discovered that he had been buying recordings of electronically monitored conversations from three sergeants working for the U.S. Army's 470th Military Intelligence Group.
20/wsj_2013:The tapes included wiretaps of Gen. Torrijos's own phone, according to American intelligence officials. 
20/wsj_2013:For the first time, the U.S. considered cutting Mr. Noriega from its intelligence payroll -- and the deliberations were intense, Mr. Turner says. "In the world of intelligence, if you want to get information, you get it from seedy characters.
20/wsj_2013:Mr. Turner was troubled enough to cancel the U.S. contract with the rent-a-colonel at the beginning of the Carter administration. 
20/wsj_2013:Prosecutors in Southern Florida indicted five Panamanians on charges of illegally running arms to Sandinista rebels trying to overthrow the Nicaraguan government of Mr. Somoza.
20/wsj_2013:They included one of Mr. Noriega's closest friends and business partners, Carlos Wittgreen.
20/wsj_2013:Their original indictment against Mr. Wittgreen, the friend of Mr. Noriega, and the other four was dismissed on a technicality.
20/wsj_2013:But now, along with reindicting Mr. Noriega's pal, they intended to charge Mr. Noriega himself, on allegations that he was involved in the illegal trading of some $2 million in arms. 
