20/wsj_2034:"We were being overrun," says Steve Fiala, trails coordinator of the East Bay Regional Park District.
20/wsj_2034:From about 200,000 six years ago, the number of mountain bikes in the U.S. is expected to grow to 10 million in 1990.
20/wsj_2034:The controversy kicked up by the proliferation of these all-terrain bicycles is one of the most divisive storms to blow through the national conservation movement in recent memory. 
20/wsj_2034:Bikers -- many of them ardent environmentalists -- proclaim their sport an efficient, safe, fitness-promoting way to get back to nature, while asserting a right, as taxpayers, to pedal on public lands.
20/wsj_2034:Key to the issue is that the bikes, in skillful hands, can go virtually anywhere, and in reckless hands can become vehicles of terror.
20/wsj_2034:An adept bicyclist can leap from a dead stop to the top of a picnic table without losing balance.
20/wsj_2034:Such skills allow riders to fly down treacherous mountain grades at speeds of up to 40 miles an hour -- a thrill for the cyclist but a nightmare for unsuspecting hikers or equestrians. 
20/wsj_2034:The state of California, following the lead of some regional parks, recently adopted regulations that closed nearly all hiking paths in state parks to mountain bicycles.
20/wsj_2034:Even the U.S. Forest Service, whose lenient "multiple-use" philosophy permits motorized vehicles on thousands of miles of its trails across the U.S., has begun to close some lands to the bikes, including major portions of the popular Pacific Crest Trail, which stretches from California to Canada. 
20/wsj_2034:Sierra has been instrumental in securing a number of the California bans.
20/wsj_2034:Yet Sierra's hard-line stance has created something of a rift in the organization, which estimates that 17% of its 500,000 members own mountain bikes.
20/wsj_2034:But the club still insists that public lands ought to be closed to the bikes unless studies indicate the bikes won't injure the environment or other users. "I have a mountain bike, yet as a hiker I've been run off the road by kids careening down a fire trail on them," says Gene Coan, an official at Sierra's headquarters in San Francisco, echoing the concerns of many members. 
20/wsj_2034:"People who feel that cyclists should be banned from an area aren't looking at the whole picture," complains Mark Langton, associate editor of Mountain and City Biking magazine in Canoga Park, Calif. 
20/wsj_2034:Mr. Langton is among the legions of bikers who got their first taste of wilderness as hikers or backpackers.
20/wsj_2034:Biking groups in Montana, Idaho, Michigan and Massachusetts have won similar concessions, says Tim Blumenthal, mountain bike editor of Bicycling magazine. 
20/wsj_2034:Even staunch anti-bike Sierra members concede that 10% of all riders cause most of the problems.
20/wsj_2034:While some are renegade riders who simply scorn regulations, much bad riding simply reflects ignorance that can be corrected through "education and peer pressure," says Jim Hasenauer, a director of the International Mountain Biking Association. "I think we're making progress." 
20/wsj_2034:Last year, 25% of the 10 million bicycles sold in the U.S. were mountain bikes.
20/wsj_2034:In California, a bellwether market, they accounted for more than 80% of all bike sales.
20/wsj_2034:The majority of the bikes never even make it into the high country.
20/wsj_2034:Crested Butte, population 1,200, is a bastion of the sport.
20/wsj_2034:The town is home to the Mountain Bike Hall of Fame and it hosts the annual Fat Tire Bike Week.
20/wsj_2034:This summer, the jamboree attracted more visitors than the busiest week of the town's winter ski season. 
