20/wsj_2063:Meanwhile, the average yield on six-month CDs of more than $90,000 fell to 7.93% in the latest week, according to Banxquote, from 8.10% the week before.
20/wsj_2063:A six-month, broker-sold CD, for example, was yielding an average 8.09% in the latest week, a fifth of a percentage point lower than the week before.
20/wsj_2063:CD yields are generally expected to fall further in coming weeks. "What happened in the stock market and the bigger trade deficit" reported yesterday "make it unlikely that short-term interest rates will rise" any time soon, said Mr. Mehl of Banxquote. 
20/wsj_2064:At the recent meetings of the World Bank and International Monetary Fund, the Bush administration announced its intention to decide by yearend the size of the next increase in the IMF's capital base.
20/wsj_2064:While the U.S. share of the increase probably will not reach the $12 billion or more implicit in the IMF's request for a doubling of its $90 billion capital, the administration probably will agree to a multibillion-dollar increase.
20/wsj_2064:Its role in the economies of developing countries has grown steadily since the 1970s.
20/wsj_2064:The size and pace of disbursements will accelerate further under the Brady Plan, which promises larger and earlier disbursements to approved countries. 
20/wsj_2064:Opponents of the increase argue that the IMF practices central planning while supporting ineffective governments.
20/wsj_2064:They question whether the IMF has any role in developing countries, given its original mandate to assist industrial countries in balance-of-payments emergencies. 
20/wsj_2064:They worry that new IMF funding of developing countries will simply end up substituting IMF debt for reschedulable commercial bank debt, a bad trade all around.
20/wsj_2064:They believe microeconomics, which addresses the problems of markets, investment climate and management practices, is the key to developing-country growth, not the IMF's Keynesian focus on trade deficits, quarterly targets and government debt.
20/wsj_2064:The politics of the 1990 congressional authorization are likely to be similar to those of previous authorizations.
20/wsj_2064:Liberals may support the stabilizing, quasi-governmental role of the IMF on two conditions: that the administration give assurances that liberal Democrats' support will not be used against them in congressional re-election campaigns; and that the legislation address -- with dollars -- social and environmental concerns.
20/wsj_2064:Conservative Republicans will be given the choice of supporting or fighting their party's popular president in an election year. 
20/wsj_2064:Commentators would fret over the implications for the G-7 coordination process and the stability of world financial markets.
20/wsj_2064:Because commercial banks and the developing-country governments believe they will get a piece of any capital increase, a scaled-down IMF mission would leave both feeling shortchanged.
20/wsj_2064:Furthermore, a U.S. rejection of the capital increase (and transfer of shares to Japan) would give Japan an argument against future calls for economic burden-sharing. 
20/wsj_2064:On the other hand, a decision to increase the IMF's capital would reinforce the central economic role of multilateral institutions in developing countries.
20/wsj_2064:Upping the ante could slow economic development even further, as countries delay market-opening steps in anticipation of richer multilateral support. 
20/wsj_2064:The issues are too important to be left to the financial and budget ministries fighting over the size of the capital increase, rather than its purpose.
