21/wsj_2184:The only transplants to drop below 1988 levels are owned by Mazda and Honda Motor Co. Part of the Mazda decline reflects "trying to anticipate what sales" are going to be, said a spokesman.
21/wsj_2184:The overall decline in car production is matched by an almost equal drop of 10.6% in expected truck output at GM, Ford, Chrysler and Nissan Motor Corp. Car and truck sales are expected to soften during the remainder of the year from unusually high, incentive-buoyed levels in August and September. 
21/wsj_2184:"None of it is a surprise," said Edward Sullivan, vice president of automotive consulting at the WEFA Group, a market analysis firm in Bala Cynwyd, Pa. "Strong third-quarter sales stole from fourth-quarter sales." He said schedules at GM, in particular, are still too high given market expectations, which will likely mean some trimming.
21/wsj_2184:But "if the cuts are going to come, they'll have to come pretty soon," he added. "Once you get into November there's not a whole lot of flexibility." 
21/wsj_2184:Much of the difference in Chrysler's car output compared with a year ago comes from having two fewer plants; Chrysler's now-shuttered facilities in Kenosha, Wis., turned out 51,000 subcompacts and mid-size cars in the 1988 fourth-quarter before it closed in December. 
21/wsj_2184:More than half the decline in Ford's expected car output comes from closing its Escort plant in Wayne, Mich., as of Nov. 22 to prepare for production of the next generation of the popular subcompact.
