22/wsj_2250:After years of fading into the background, two-tone photography is coming back. 
22/wsj_2250:Trendy magazine advertisements feature stark black-and-white photos of Hollywood celebrities pitching jeans, shoes and liquor.
22/wsj_2250:What's happening in photography mirrors the popularity of black and white in fashion, home furnishings and cinematography.
22/wsj_2250:And classic black-and-white movies are enjoying a comeback on videocassette tapes, spurred, in part, by the backlash against colorization of old films. 
22/wsj_2250:"The pendulum is swinging back to black and white," says Richard DeMoulin, the general manager of Eastman Kodak Co. 's professional photography division. 
22/wsj_2250:Until two years ago, sales of black-and-white film had been declining steadily since the 1960s.
22/wsj_2250:At Kodak, which largely ignored the market for years, black-and-white film sales now account for nearly 15% of the company's $3 billion in film and paper sales annually, up from 10% three years ago. 
22/wsj_2250:The Rochester, N.Y., photographic giant recently began marketing T-Max 3200, one of the fastest and most sensitive monochrome films.
22/wsj_2250:Aimed at commercial photographers, the film can be used in very low light without sacrificing quality, says Donald Franz of Photofinishing Newsletter. 
22/wsj_2250:Also trying to snare a portion of the $2 billion-a-year industry is Agfa Corp., a unit of Bayer AG. Agfa recently signed Olympic gold medalist Florence Griffith-Joyner to endorse a new line of black-and-white paper that's geared to consumers and will compete directly with Kodak's papers.
22/wsj_2250:Slated for market by the end of the year, the paper "could have been introduced a long time ago but the market wasn't there then," says an Agfa spokesman. 
22/wsj_2250:The biggest beneficiary of the black-and-white revival is likely to be International Paper Co. 's Ilford division, known in the industry for its premium products.
22/wsj_2250:Sales of Ilford's four varieties of black-and-white film this year are outpacing growth in the overall market, although the company won't say by exactly how much. "We hope the trend lasts," says Laurie DiCara, Ilford's marketing communications director. 
22/wsj_2250:For baby boomers who grew up being photographed in color, black and white seems eye-catching and exotic. "It has an archival, almost nostalgic quality to it," says Owen B. Butler, the chairman of the applied photography department at Rochester Institute of Technology. "You can shift out of reality with black and white," he adds. 
22/wsj_2250:Such features have been especially attractive to professional photographers and marketing executives, who have been steadily increasing their use of black and white in advertising.
22/wsj_2250:Processing of black-and-white commercial film jumped 24% last year to 18.7 million rolls. 
22/wsj_2250:Consider Gap Inc., whose latest ad campaign features black-and-white shots of Hollywood stars, artists and other well-known personalities modeling the retailer's jeans and T-shirts.
22/wsj_2250:Richard Crisman, the account manager for the campaign, says Gap didn't intentionally choose black and white to distinguish its ads from the color spreads of competitors. 
22/wsj_2250:Typically, it must be mailed to a handful of processors and may take a week or more to be processed and returned. 
22/wsj_2250:Intent on wooing customers, the company is also increasing its sponsorship of black-and-white photography classes. 
22/wsj_2250:Similarly, Agfa is sponsoring scores of photography contests at high schools and colleges, offering free black-and-white film and paper as prizes.
22/wsj_2250:Charles Beseler Co., a leading maker of photographic enlargers, introduced last month a complete darkroom starter kit targeted at teen-agers who want to process their own black-and-white photographs.
22/wsj_2250:The kit, which has a suggested retail price of $250 and has already become a bestseller, was introduced after retailers noticed numerous requests from parents for children's photography equipment. "It seems computers as hobbies have waned," says Ian Brightman, Beseler's chairman and chief executive officer. 
22/wsj_2250:But some industry observers believe the resurgence of black and white is only a fad.
22/wsj_2250:They cite the emergence of still electronic photography, more newspapers turning to color on their pages and measurable improvements in the quality of color prints. 
22/wsj_2250:"Black and white hasn't made the same quantum leaps in technological development as color," says Mr. Butler of the Rochester Institute. "The color print today is far superior to prints of 10 years ago.
22/wsj_2250:But when Popular Photography, a leading magazine for photographers, selected 15 of the greatest photos ever made for its latest issue celebrating photography's 150th anniversary, all were black and white. "It's got a classic spirit and carries over emotionally," says Alfred DeBat of Professional Photographers of America. "That's the appeal." 
22/wsj_2252:A. and Societe National Elf Aquitaine, the state oil companies of Italy and France, respectively, submitted an offer to buy Gatoil Suisse S.A.
22/wsj_2252:Gatoil Suisse owns an oil refinery in Switzerland with a capacity of 70,000 barrels a day, along with a network of gasoline retailing outlets. 
22/wsj_2253:The barometer, developed by analysts at Columbia University's Center for International Business Cycle Research here, reached a record high of 223.0 in August, the latest month available, and the Columbia researchers estimate that it has moved even higher since then. 
22/wsj_2253:The latest reading of 223.0 was up from 222.3 in July and 215.3 as recently as March.
22/wsj_2253:The August rise marked the fifth straight monthly gain for the indicator, which uses the 1967 average as a base of 100. 
22/wsj_2253:In contrast, the Commerce Department's widely followed index of leading indicators, while up in August, has fallen repeatedly since reaching a high early this year.
22/wsj_2253:Its ragged behavior through much of 1989 has prompted some forecasters to anticipate the start of a new recession perhaps before year's end. 
22/wsj_2253:But the far stronger showing of the Columbia index "makes a recession any time soon highly unlikely," says Geoffrey H. Moore, the director of the Columbia facility. 
22/wsj_2253:A leading authority on the business cycle, Mr. Moore also is a member of the Business Cycle Dating Group, the panel of private economists that decides for the government when expansions and recessions begin and end.
22/wsj_2253:"No meeting is scheduled because the expansion shows no sign of going off the tracks," Mr. Moore reports. 
22/wsj_2253:Based largely on the recent strength in their index, called the long leading indicator, the Columbia analysts foresee uninterrupted economic growth through the rest of this year and next year as well.
22/wsj_2253:Underlying this optimism is the index's longstanding ability to signal recessions or recoveries, as the case may be, by substantially greater periods than the Commerce Department's index of leading indicators.
22/wsj_2253:Over the full post-World War II era, the Columbia index, on the average, has entered sustained declines 14 months before the onset of recessions and turned up eight months before recoveries. 
22/wsj_2253:A major source of the recent strength in the long leading indicator has been the performance of the Dow Jones corporate bond-price index, which is not a part of the Commerce index.
22/wsj_2253:Other components of the long leading indicator include a ratio of prices to unit labor costs in manufacturing industries, the M2 version of the money supply, adjusted for inflation, and the volume of new home-building permits. 
22/wsj_2253:Notably absent from the Columbia index is the stock market, which Mr. Moore says "is simply no longer such a good indicator of the economy's long-range prospects, though it still is useful for anticipating some short-run twists and turns." 
22/wsj_2253:As recently as 1975, the stock market -- as reflected in the Standard & Poor's index of 500 common stocks -- was rated by the National Bureau of Economic Research as the best of the 12 leading indicators that then made up the Commerce index.
22/wsj_2253:It was assigned a mark of 80 out of a possible 100, compared with scores ranging as low as 69 for the other components. 
22/wsj_2253:The stock market has lost some precursory power, analysts at the Columbia center claim, because of the growing impact of international developments. 
22/wsj_2253:"Stocks have become more sensitive to factors not directly tied to the domestic economy," Mr. Moore says, citing the exchange rate for the dollar on currency markets, the foreign-trade balance and inflows of foreign capital.
22/wsj_2253:He also feels that the rise of such computer-based practices as program trading has diminished the stock market's relevancy to the economic outlook. 
22/wsj_2254:The value of the acquisition wasn't disclosed. 
22/wsj_2254:The move is in line with BSN's strategy of gradually building its share of the European pasta market through external growth.
22/wsj_2254:Birkel is West Germany's second-biggest producer of pasta, with sales of 250 million marks ($133.4 million) in 1988.
