22/wsj_2284:After a long day tending the searing, blackened furnaces of the Panzhihua Iron & Steel Co., Li Wankui would like to relax away from the factory.
22/wsj_2284:Nestled in the remote mountains of southern Sichuan province about 1,200 miles southwest of Beijing, it is virtually cut off from the rest of China.
22/wsj_2284:Factory officials estimate that more than 10% of the work force here is redundant, but layoffs aren't allowed.
22/wsj_2284:A muscular 38-year-old, he rises each morning at 6 a.m. to prepare for his shift. (He is entitled to one day off after each seven days of work.) 
22/wsj_2284:Throwing on sweat pants and a T-shirt, he pops downstairs to a food shop, one of dozens run by the factory in Panzhihua's residential area.
22/wsj_2284:Mr. Li, whose pay is the equivalent of about $80 a month, buys steamed buns and rice porridge for his family.
22/wsj_2284:At the gate of the factory, a huge sign greets Mr. Li and his co-workers: "Happily, happily come to work!" 
22/wsj_2284:At lunchtime, Mr. Li walks to one of the 59 cafeterias the factory operates.
22/wsj_2284:Scraps of meat and bones litter the bare concrete floor.
22/wsj_2284:For about 30 cents, Mr. Li buys a bowl of pork, vegetables and rice. 
22/wsj_2284:At the end of Mr. Li's workday, as a new shift prepares to take over, the factory's propaganda officials go to work.
22/wsj_2284:For half an hour they relate to groups of workers the latest news and views from the Communist Party.
22/wsj_2284:They read speeches from top leaders and slam U.S. sanctions on China imposed after the June 4 massacre of pro-democracy protesters in Beijing. "We want to make sure that workers have a correct opinion about events," says Yuan Changyong, the local Party chief. 
22/wsj_2284:Teams of officials track the contraceptive methods their workers employ and even chart menstrual cycles of female employees.
22/wsj_2284:They work by persuasion and coercion, alternating doses of propaganda with threats of financial penalties for "unplanned" second births. 
22/wsj_2284:Zhang Shanyun, one of Mr. Li's bosses, knows the system well.
22/wsj_2284:Whenever Mr. Zhang wants to return to his farm, he must fill out a form detailing what kind of birth-control device he and his wife will use.
22/wsj_2284:Most of the food comes to him via the factory, which buys 80 million tons of produce a year.
22/wsj_2284:The factory sells to workers at cost, which means prices are about 50% below what the handful of independent local merchants charge. 
22/wsj_2284:It turned out that few workers here in the hills of Sichuan had ever seen them, so the factory TV station ran a broadcast on the correct way to eat Guangdong crabs. 
22/wsj_2284:There are few prospects for upward mobility, and Mr. Li's daughter, seven-year-old Li Shu, is certain to toil at the factory too someday, as are more than 10,000 of the workers' children. 
22/wsj_2284:Li Shu is in the second grade at the Xiangyang Village Elementary School for Workers' Children, one of 31 schools subsidized by the factory at a cost of more than half a million dollars a year.
22/wsj_2284:But he concedes that the pressures of the all-powerful factory sometimes are tough to bear.
22/wsj_2284:Most evenings after the news, he leaves his wife in front of the TV set and wanders restlessly around his quiet neighborhood.
22/wsj_2284:The center, built and run by Panzhihua Iron & Steel, is the beginning and end of social life in this town. 
22/wsj_2284:Mr. Li walks upstairs to the center's second-floor library, a poorly lit room where he spends many hours leafing through a thin selection of state-controlled periodicals.
22/wsj_2284:He pulls out a newspaper: The Panzhihua Iron & Steel Co. Daily. "It's a good read," Mr. Li says. "Quite informative." Today's lead story: "Manager Zhao Inspects Operation of No. 4 Furnace." 
22/wsj_2284:Not surprisingly in this remote outpost, many of the single factory workers here fall in love with each other. "We have a very small social circle," says Ma Yongjian, the company secretary general. "A lot of the young workers end up getting married." To facilitate such productive arrangements, the factory organizes dances each night, often outdoors on a concrete promenade along the banks of the Jinshajiang River. 
22/wsj_2284:On this evening, the dancers seem reluctant, as a sour eight-piece band plods through a series of Chinese pop songs.
22/wsj_2284:Immediately, hundreds of couples leap to their feet and rush onto the floor, dancing their well-rehearsed three-step, cheek-to-cheek.
22/wsj_2284:The factory, one of Chairman Mao's oddest follies, dates to 1965.
22/wsj_2284:Like tens of thousands of others, Mr. Li was ordered to go to Panzhihua, in 1971. "I lived in a straw-and-mud house at the time," he says. "But I was happy to be here, to carry on the fight against the imperialists and the revisionists." Today the perceived threat has passed, but the factory is thriving. 
22/wsj_2284:The Li family could apply for permission to do so, but hasn't tried. "I expect I'll be in Panzhihua for the rest of my life," Mr. Li says. "The No. 1 high school is pretty good, and I have to think of my daughter's future." 
22/wsj_2284:When the opportunity finally arose, thousands of workers departed, including virtually all of the factory's college graduates and senior engineers. 
22/wsj_2284:Ma Zhijie, deputy general manager of the factory's trading department, wants his eight-year-old son to have broader horizons, and believes education is the best ticket out of Panzhihua.
22/wsj_2284:What the factory's workers know of the world comes filtered through the propaganda machine of official newspapers and television, as well as political study sessions.
22/wsj_2284:At one point, Mr. Li repeats the theme of a recent political study class and harangues his American visitor about U.S. sanctions against China. "The Chinese and American people have great warmth for each other," Mr. Li says, "but I must tell you frankly that I disagree with President Bush's policy toward China." 
22/wsj_2284:Many of these Americans were incensed by the killings in Beijing and denounced the Chinese government. "Well, I certainly didn't know any of that," Mr. Li says, and abruptly closes the conversation. 
22/wsj_2284:As Mr. Li begins his walk back home, he displays a slight limp, the result of a back injury.
22/wsj_2284:Mr. Zhong motions to the wriggling bundles. "These," he says, "are the future workers of Panzhihua Iron & Steel." 
22/wsj_2284:Four of Britain's biggest banks said they plan to sell jointly owned Yorkshire Bank Group in an auction that could raise between #850 million ($1.33 billion) and #1 billion ($1.57 billion). 
22/wsj_2284:National Westminster Bank PLC, Yorkshire Bank's biggest holder with a 40% stake, said it, Barclays PLC, Lloyds Bank PLC and Royal Bank of Scotland Group PLC decided to sell the 250-branch U.K. bank after receiving "a number of approaches" from potential purchasers.
22/wsj_2284:Yorkshire Bank, which had pretax profit of #100.4 million and #3.19 billion in assets last year, has Britain's ninth-largest branch network.
22/wsj_2284:It is viewed by market analysts as a potential target for banks aiming to boost their U.K. presence prior to the 1992 development of a single market in financial services in the European Community.
22/wsj_2284:Analysts have said the bank could fetch a price of between 8.5 and 10 times pretax profit -- or between #850 million and #1 billion. 
22/wsj_2284:Bill Barron, a NatWest general manager, said the banks decided to push ahead with the sale despite yesterday's sharp stock-market fall in London because the decision was strategic and independent of market valuations. 
22/wsj_2284:The consortium-ownership arrangement, which dates from a financial reconstruction of Yorkshire Bank in 1911, is outmoded for the increasingly competitive U.K. market, analysts say.
22/wsj_2284:Barclays owns 32%, Lloyds owns 20% and Royal Bank of Scotland owns 8% of Yorkshire Bank. 
