22/wsj_2286:It isn't given much chance of passing, but its mere existence is cause for anxiety. 
22/wsj_2286:The U.S. and the world are not in need of new doubts about the future soundness of the dollar.
22/wsj_2286:Attempts in late September to drive the dollar down through central bank interventions were ill-timed, particularly since we now know that the dollar was then in the process of taking another dive relative to oil and other producer goods.
22/wsj_2286:But all that was a long time ago and politicians have a way of forgetting such things.
22/wsj_2286:The 1970s inflation yielded great benefits to some producer interests, including Arab sheiks, at the expense of the American middle class.
22/wsj_2286:It was a classic example of how inflation transfers income to the wealthy from the middle class.
22/wsj_2286:In some countries, Argentina for example, those interests have overwhelmed the government and what remains of a middle class. 
22/wsj_2286:It was only after Mr. Volcker killed inflation, at the cost of a sharp but brief recession, that growth and productivity started rising once more.
22/wsj_2286:Producers were forced by the discipline of sound money to slash away organizational fat and acquire more efficient equipment.
22/wsj_2286:Many corporate executives don't understand or don't want to understand that their own companies eventually become victims of such policies.
22/wsj_2286:That was reflected in the stagnant stock market of the 1970s.
22/wsj_2286:All of which explains why stock and foreign exchange markets get jittery when the Fed comes under political pressure.
22/wsj_2286:When it tightened up last spring, the price indexes fell and the economy began to pick up speed again, which is of course exactly counter to the "inflation-fuels-growth" theory. 
