23/wsj_2306:As small investors peppered their mutual funds with phone calls over the weekend, big fund managers said they have a strong defense against any wave of withdrawals: cash. 
23/wsj_2306:At Fidelity Investments, the nation's largest fund company, telephone volume was up sharply, but it was still at just half the level of the weekend preceding Black Monday in 1987.
23/wsj_2306:As of yesterday afternoon, the redemptions represented less than 15% of the total cash position of about $2 billion of Fidelity's stock funds. 
23/wsj_2306:"Two years ago there were massive redemption levels over the weekend and a lot of fear around," said C. Bruce Johnstone, who runs Fidelity Investments' $5 billion Equity-Income Fund. "This feels more like a one-shot deal.
23/wsj_2306:Mario Gabelli, for instance, holds cash positions well above 20% in several of his funds.
23/wsj_2306:Even Peter Lynch, manager of Fidelity's $12.7 billion Magellan Fund, the nation's largest stock fund, built up cash to 7% or $850 million.
23/wsj_2306:One reason is that after two years of monthly net redemptions, the fund posted net inflows of money from investors in August and September. 
23/wsj_2306:Not all funds have raised cash levels, of course.
23/wsj_2306:As a group, stock funds held 10.2% of assets in cash as of August, the latest figures available from the Investment Company Institute.
23/wsj_2306:That was modestly higher than the 8.8% and 9.2% levels in August and September of 1987.
23/wsj_2306:But a strong level of investor withdrawals is much more unlikely this time around, fund managers said.
23/wsj_2306:A major reason is that investors already have sharply scaled back their purchases of stock funds since Black Monday.
23/wsj_2306:"There's not nearly as much froth," said John Bogle, chairman of Vanguard Group Inc., a big Valley Forge, Pa., fund company. 
23/wsj_2306:Vincent Bajakian, manager of the $1.8 billion Wellington Fund, added to his positions in Bristol-Myers Squibb, Woolworth and Dun & Bradstreet Friday.
23/wsj_2306:If the market drops further today, he said he'll be buying blue chips such as Bristol-Myers and Kellogg. "If they croak stocks like that," he said, it presents an opportunity that is "the kind of thing you dream about." 
