23/wsj_2313:The partnership, Kaufman & Broad Land Development Venture Limited Partnership, is a 50-50 joint venture with a trust created by institutional clients of Heitman Advisory Corp., a unit of Heitman Financial Corp., a real estate advisory, management and development company with offices in Chicago and Beverly Hills, Calif.
23/wsj_2313:The land to be purchased by the joint venture hasn't yet received zoning and other approvals required for development, and part of Kaufman & Broad's job will be to obtain such approvals. 
23/wsj_2313:The partnership runs the risk that it may not get the approvals for development, but in return, it can buy land at wholesale rather than retail prices, which can result in sizable savings, said Bruce Karatz, president and chief executive officer of Kaufman & Broad. 
23/wsj_2313:Typically, developers option property, and then once they get the administrative approvals, they buy it," said Mr. Karatz, adding that he believes the joint venture is the first of its kind. "We usually operate in that conservative manner." 
23/wsj_2313:By setting up the joint venture, Kaufman & Broad can take the more aggressive approach of buying raw land, while avoiding the negative impacts to its own balance sheet, Mr. Karatz said.
23/wsj_2313:The company is putting up only 10% of the capital, although it is responsible for providing management, planning and processing services to the joint venture. 
23/wsj_2313:"This is one of the best ways to assure a pipeline of land to fuel our growth at a minimum risk to our company," Mr. Karatz said. 
23/wsj_2314:When the price of plastics took off in 1987, Quantum Chemical Corp. went along for the ride. 
23/wsj_2314:The timing of Quantum's chief executive officer, John Hoyt Stookey, appeared to be nothing less than inspired, because he had just increased Quantum's reliance on plastics.
23/wsj_2314:The company outpaced much of the chemical industry as annual profit grew fivefold in two years.
23/wsj_2314:Mr. Stookey said of the boom, "It's going to last a whole lot longer than anybody thinks." 
23/wsj_2314:Some securities analysts are looking for no better than break-even results from the company for the third quarter, compared with year-earlier profit of $99.8 million, or $3.92 a share, on sales of $724.4 million.
23/wsj_2314:The stock, having lost nearly a quarter of its value since Sept. 1, closed at $34.375 share, down $1.125, in New York Stock Exchange composite trading Friday. 
23/wsj_2314:To a degree, Quantum represents the new times that have arrived for producers of the so-called commodity plastics that pervade modern life.
23/wsj_2314:Having just passed through one of the most profitable periods in their history, these producers now see their prices eroding. 
23/wsj_2314:And the financial decline of some looks steep only in comparison with the heady period that is just behind them. "We were all wonderful heroes last year," says an executive at one of Quantum's competitors. "Now we're at the bottom of the heap." 
23/wsj_2314:Once known as National Distillers & Chemical Corp., the company exited the wine and spirits business and plowed more of its resources into plastics after Mr. Stookey took the chief executive's job in 1986.
23/wsj_2314:Mr. Stookey, 59 years old, declined to be interviewed for this article, but he has consistently argued that over the long haul -- across both the peaks and the troughs of the plastics market -- Quantum will prosper through its new direction. 
23/wsj_2314:When the price of polyethylene moves a mere penny a pound, Quantum's annual profit fluctuates by about 85 cents a share, provided no other variables are changing.
23/wsj_2314:In recent months the price of polyethylene, even more than that of other commodity plastics, has taken a dive.
23/wsj_2314:Meanwhile, the price of ethylene, the chemical building block of polyethylene, hasn't dropped nearly so fast.
23/wsj_2314:That discrepancy hurts Quantum badly, because its own plants cover only about half of its ethylene needs. 
23/wsj_2314:By many accounts, an early hint of a price rout in the making came at the start of this year.
23/wsj_2314:Kenneth Mitchell, director of Dow's polyethylene business, says producers were surprised to learn how much inventories had swelled throughout the distribution chain as prices spiraled up. "People were even hoarding bags," he says. 
23/wsj_2314:They recently announced increases of a few cents a pound to take effect in the next several weeks.
23/wsj_2314:Noting others' estimates of when price increases can be sustained, he remarks, "Some say October.
23/wsj_2314:At the same time, its annual payments on long-term debt will more than double from a year ago to about $240 million, largely because of debt taken on to pay a $50-a-share special dividend earlier this year. 
23/wsj_2314:Whether a cash crunch might eventually force the company to cut its quarterly dividend, raised 36% to 75 cents a share only a year ago, has become a topic of intense speculation on Wall Street since Mr. Stookey deflected dividend questions in a Sept. 29 meeting with analysts. 
23/wsj_2314:In any case, on the day of the meeting, Quantum's shares slid $2.625 to $36.625 in Big Board trading. 
23/wsj_2314:On top of everything else, Quantum confronts a disaster at its plant in Morris, Ill.
23/wsj_2314:After an explosion idled the plant in June, the company progressed in September to within 12 hours of completing the drawn-out process of restarting it.
23/wsj_2314:"You say you could have sold X percent of this product and Y percent of that," recalls Theodore Semegran, an analyst at Shearson Lehman Hutton who went through this exercise during his former career as a chemical engineer. "And then you still have to negotiate." 
23/wsj_2314:The plant usually accounts for 20% to 25% of Quantum's polyethylene production and 50% of its ethylene production. 
23/wsj_2314:Through a venture with its investment banker, First Boston Corp., Quantum completed in August an acquisition of Petrolane Inc. in a transaction valued at $1.18 billion.
23/wsj_2314:Asked about a bid for Quantum, a BP spokesman says, "We pretty much have a policy of not commenting on rumors, and I think that falls in that category." 
