23/wsj_2316:The U.S., which is finalizing its steel-import quotas, is allocating a larger share of its steel market to developing and newly industrialized countries which have relatively unsubsidized steel industries. 
23/wsj_2316:Brazil, similar to Mexico and South Korea, is expected to negotiate a somewhat bigger share of the U.S. market than it had under the previous five-year steel quotas, which expired Sept. 30.
23/wsj_2316:In recent years, U.S. steelmakers have supplied about 80% of the 100 million tons of steel used annually by the nation.
23/wsj_2316:Of the remaining 20% needed, the steel-quota negotiations allocate about 15% to foreign suppliers, with the difference supplied mainly by Canada -- which isn't included in the quota program.
23/wsj_2316:Some of these countries have in recent years made informal agreements with the U.S. that are similar to quotas. 
23/wsj_2316:Mexico, which was one of the first countries to conclude its steel talks with the U.S., virtually doubled its quota to 0.95% of the U.S. steel market from 0.48% under the previous quotas.
23/wsj_2316:That increase rises to slightly more than 2% of the U.S. market if a joint Korean-U.S. steel project is included.
23/wsj_2316:The EC steel industry, which has been coping with strong European demand, has been supplying about 5% of the U.S. market compared with recent quotas of about 6.7%.
23/wsj_2316:Japan has been shipping steel to total about 4.5% of the U.S. market compared with a quota of 5.9%. 
23/wsj_2316:In the recent talks, the EC had its quota increased about 300,000 tons, to 7% of the U.S. market from 6.7% in 1988.
23/wsj_2316:Japan, the EC, Brazil, Mexico and South Korea provide about 80% of the steel imported to the U.S. under the quota program.
23/wsj_2316:The balance is supplied by a host of smaller exporters, such as Australia and Venezuela. 
23/wsj_2316:The U.S. had about an extra 2% of the domestic steel market to give to foreign suppliers in its quota talks.
23/wsj_2316:That was essentially made up of a 1% increase in the overall quota program and 1% from cutting Japan's allowance. 
23/wsj_2316:Negotiators from the White House trade office will repeat these quota negotiations next year when they will have another 1% of the U.S. steel market to allocate. 
