23/wsj_2330:While corn and soybean prices have slumped well below their drought-induced peaks of 1988, wheat prices remain stubbornly high.
23/wsj_2330:And if rain doesn't fall soon across many of the Great Plains' wheat-growing areas, yields in the crop now being planted could be reduced, further squeezing supplies.
23/wsj_2330:By next May 31, stocks of U.S. wheat to be carried over into the next season -- before the winter wheat now being planted is harvested -- are projected to drop to 443 million bushels.
23/wsj_2330:Stocks were 698 million bushels on May 31 of this year. 
23/wsj_2330:In response to dwindling domestic supplies, Agriculture Secretary Clayton Yeutter last month said the U.S. government would slightly increase the number of acres farmers can plant in wheat for next year and still qualify for federal support payments.
23/wsj_2330:But the full effect on prices of the winter wheat now being planted won't be felt until the second half of next year.
23/wsj_2330:On the Chicago Board of Trade Friday, wheat for December delivery settled at $4.0675 a bushel, unchanged. 
23/wsj_2330:Such a situation can wreak havoc, as was shown by the emergency that developed in soybean futures trading this summer on the Chicago Board of Trade. 
23/wsj_2330:A. to liquidate futures positions equal to about 23 million bushels of soybeans.
23/wsj_2330:Unseasonably hot, dry weather across large portions of the Great Plains and in wheat-growing areas in Washington and Oregon is threatening to reduce the yield from this season's winter wheat crop, said Conrad Leslie, a futures analyst and head of Leslie Analytical in Chicago.
23/wsj_2330:For example, in the Oklahoma panhandle, 40% or more of the topsoil is short of moisture.
23/wsj_2330:That figure climbs to about 47% in wheat-growing portions of Kansas, he said. 
23/wsj_2330:The Soviet Union hasn't given any clear indication of its wheat purchase plans, but many analysts expect Moscow to place sizable orders for U.S. wheat in the next few months, further supporting prices. "Wheat prices will increasingly pivot off of Soviet demand" in coming weeks, predicted Richard Feltes, vice president, research, for Refco Inc. in Chicago. 
23/wsj_2330:Late Thursday, after the close of trading, the market received what would normally have been a bullish U.S. Department of Agriculture estimate of the 1989-90 Florida orange crop.
23/wsj_2330:It was near the low range of estimates, at 130 million 90-pound boxes, compared with 146.6 million boxes last season. 
23/wsj_2330:However, as expected, Brazil waited for the crop estimate to come out and then cut the export price of its juice concentrate to about $1.34 a pound from around $1.55.
23/wsj_2330:Friday's consequent selling of futures contracts erased whatever supportive effect the U.S. report might have had and sent the November orange juice contract down as much as 6.55 cents a pound at one time.
23/wsj_2330:It settled with a loss of 4.95 cents at $1.3210 a pound. 
23/wsj_2330:Brazilian juice, after a delay caused by drought at the start of its crop season, is beginning to arrive in the U.S. in large quantities.
23/wsj_2330:The price cut, one analyst said, appeared to be aimed even more at Europe, where consumption of Brazilian juice has fallen.
23/wsj_2330:Barring a cold snap or other crop problems in the growing areas, downward pressure on prices is likely to continue into January, when harvesting and processing of oranges in Florida reach their peak, the analyst said. 
23/wsj_2330:Although some analysts look for profit-taking in the wake of Friday's leap in crude oil prices, last week's rally is generally expected to continue this week. 
23/wsj_2330:Friday capped a week of steadily rising crude oil prices in both futures and spot markets.
23/wsj_2330:On European markets, meanwhile, spot prices of North Sea crudes were up 35 to 75 cents a barrel. 
23/wsj_2330:Analysts generally cite a lack of bearish developments as well as rumors of a possible tightening of supplies of some fuels and crudes.
23/wsj_2330:Many traders foresee a tightening of near-term supplies, particularly of high-quality crudes such as those produced in the North Sea and in Nigeria. 
