23/wsj_2379:Joseph Hardiman, president of the National Association of Securities Dealers, which oversees the Nasdaq computerized trading system, said that despite the rush of selling, he never considered the situation an "emergency." 
23/wsj_2379:"The pace of trading was orderly," he said.
23/wsj_2379:Nevertheless, the shock of another steep plunge in stock prices undoubtedly will shake many investors' confidence.
23/wsj_2379:In the past, the OTC market thrived on a firm base of small-investor participation.
23/wsj_2379:But they are worried. "We were just starting to get the public's confidence back," lamented Mr. Mullins of Dean Witter. 
23/wsj_2379:More troubling is the prospect that the overall collapse in stock prices could permanently erode the base of small-investor support the OTC market was struggling to rebuild in the wake of the October 1987 crash. 
23/wsj_2379:Mr. Cecin of Piper Jaffray says some action from government policy makers would allay investor fears.
23/wsj_2379:It won't take much more to "scare the hell out of retail investors," he says. 
23/wsj_2379:The sellers on Friday came from all corners of the OTC market -- big and small institutional investors, as well as individual investors and market makers.
23/wsj_2379:But grateful traders said the sell orders generally ranged from 20,000 shares to 50,000 shares, compared with blocks of 500,000 shares or more two years ago. 
23/wsj_2379:"We had a good amount of selling from institutions, but not as much panic," Mr. DaPuzzo said. "If they couldn't sell, some of them put the shares back on the shelf." In addition, he said, some bigger institutional investors placed bids to buy some OTC stocks whose prices were beaten down. 
23/wsj_2379:In addition, Mr. DaPuzzo said computer-guided program selling of OTC stocks in the Russell Index of 2000 small stocks and the Standard & Poor's 500-stock Index sent occasional "waves " through the market. 
23/wsj_2379:The Nasdaq 100 Index of the largest nonfinancial issues, including the big OTC technology issues, tumbled 4.2%, or 19.76, to 449.33.
23/wsj_2379:The Nasdaq Financial Index of giant insurance and banking stocks dropped 2%, or 9.31, to 462.98. 
23/wsj_2379:The OTC market has only a handful of takeover-related stocks.
23/wsj_2379:On a day when negative takeover-related news didn't sit well with investors, Commercial Intertech, a maker of engineered metal parts, said Haas & Partners advised it that it doesn't plan to pursue its previously reported $27.50-a-share bid to buy the company.
23/wsj_2379:The issues of companies with ties to the junk bond market also tumbled Friday.
23/wsj_2379:On the OTC market, First Executive, a big buyer of the high-risk, high-yield issues, slid 2 to 12 1/4. 
23/wsj_2379:Among other OTC issues, Intel, dropped 2 1/8 to 33 7/8; Laidlaw Transportation lost 1 1/8 to 19 1/2; the American depositary receipts of Jaguar were off 1/4 to 10 1/4; MCI Communications slipped 2 1/4 to 43 1/2; Apple Computer fell 3 to 45 3/4 and Nike dropped 2 1/4 to 66 3/4. 
