23/wsj_2384:-- By 11:59 p.m. tonight, President Bush must order $16 billion of automatic, across-the-board cuts in government spending to comply with the Gramm-Rudman budget law.
23/wsj_2384:The administration has been trying to push the dollar lower; the Fed has been resisting. "One of the things that continues to worry me is this monetary warfare between the Treasury Department and the Federal Reserve Board," said Lawrence Kudlow, a Bear, Stearns & Co. economist, on ABC's "This Week." 
23/wsj_2384:-- The administration has sent out confusing signals about its response to a recent spate of airline takeovers. 
23/wsj_2384:In many ways, the backdrop to Friday's stock decline is eerily similar to that of October 1987's 508-point crash.
23/wsj_2384:Then, as now, the budget debate was behind schedule and automatic spending cuts were within days of taking hold.
23/wsj_2384:One of the biggest reasons that new talks aren't likely to come about is that, as everyone learned in 1987, the economy and the market can survive a one-day 508-point tumble. "Everybody thought we were looking at a repetition of 1929, that we were looking at a recession," Rep. Panetta said yesterday in an interview. "That did not happen.
23/wsj_2384:In that case, there will be plenty of blame to go around. "There is an underlying concern on the part of the American people -- and there should be-that the administration has not gone far enough in cutting this deficit and that Congress has been unwilling to cut what the administration asked us to cut," said Senate Finance Committee Chairman Lloyd Bentsen (D., Texas). 
23/wsj_2384:Hill Democrats are particularly angry over Mr. Bush's claim that the capital-gains cut was part of April's budget accord and his insistence on combining it with the deficit-reduction legislation. 
23/wsj_2384:"There is no prospect of any so-called grand compromise or deal next year because the administration simply didn't live up to this year's deal," Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell (D., Maine) said yesterday on CBS News's "Face the Nation." 
